mber 9, 2015.</ref>\n<ref name=\"americanmirror 2016-01\">[http://www.theamericanmirror.com/video-stump-for-trump-duo-rock-capacity-crowd-at-ms-rally/ \u2018Stump for Trump\u2019 duo rock capacity crowd at MS rally], The American Mirror, January 3, 2016.</ref>\n<ref name=\"journalnow 2016-11\">{{cite news |date=November 2, 2016 |title=Diamond and Silk, Lara Trump bring Women for Trump tour to Winston-Salem |url=http://www.journalnow.com/news/local/diamond-and-silk-lara-trump-bring-women-for-trump-tour/article_9991442a-a10f-11e6-a433-63ff4b48083e.html |newspaper=[[Winston-Salem Journal]] |location=[[Winston-Salem, North Carolina]] |access-date=November 18, 2016}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"FEC Trump Disbursements\">{{cite web |url=http://docquery.fec.gov/cgi-bin/forms/C00580100/1133930/sb/ALL/4 |title=FEC Donald J. Trump for President, Inc. Itemized Disbursements |access-date=April 30, 2018}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"NOLA\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nola.com/tv/index.ssf/2018/03/fox_news_darlings_diamond_and.html |title=Fox News darlings Diamond and Silk bringing 'Chit Chat Tour' to New Orleans |last=Morris |first=Melinda  |date=March 20, 2018 |website=NOLA.com The Times Picayune |access-date=April 9, 2018}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"kansascity\">{{cite web|url=http://www.kansascity.com/news/nation-world/article208473664.html|title=Mark Zuckerberg: Facebook made 'enforcement error' with Trump fans Diamond and Silk|last=Gutierrez|first=Lisa|date=April 10, 2018|work=The Kansas City Star}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"FoxNewsInsider\">{{cite web |url=http://insider.foxnews.com/2017/08/13/diamond-silk-dont-white-nationalists-antifa |title=Diamond and Silk: We Don't Like White Nationalists or Antifa |date=August 13, 2017 |website=Fox News Insider |access-date=April 8, 2018}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"BlackStar2\">{{cite web |url=http://atlantablackstar.com/2017/12/29/omarosa-gets-defended-diamond-silk-trump-supporters-get-dragged/ |title=Omarosa Gets Defended by Diamond and Silk \u2026 and the Trump Supporters Get Dragged - You may not like Omarosa, but you don't have a right to laugh at her |last=Willis |first=Kiersten  |date=December 29, 2017 |website=Atlanta Black Star |access-date=April 8, 2018}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"ByeFelicia\">{{cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/entertainthis/2017/12/14/gma-host-robin-roberts-omarosas-white-house-exit-bye-felicia/951679001/ |title='GMA' host Robin Roberts on Omarosa's White House exit: 'Bye, Felicia' |last=Deerwester |first=Jayme |date=December 14, 2017 |website=USA Today |access-date=April 8, 2018}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Facebookpage\">{{Cite AV media |url=https://www.facebook.com/DiamondandSilk/?ref=br_rs |title=Diamond and Silk@DiamondandSilk |date=April 8, 2018 |last=Silk |first=Diamond and |type=Social media}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"cnn facebook\">{{Cite news|url=http://money.cnn.com/2018/04/15/media/diamond-silk-facebook-fox-news/index.html|title=Led by Fox News, pro-Trump media fuels false narrative to accuse Facebook of censorship|last=Darcy|first=Oliver|date=|work=CNNMoney |access-date=April 26, 2018|quote=the Diamond & Silk page was never banned. It was never taken down. It was never censored... The tidal wave of media coverage didn't just mislead viewers; it likely influenced the Mark Zuckerberg hearings on Capitol Hill. Several lawmakers chose to use at least a portion of their time questioning the Facebook chief to ask him about the supposed censorship of Hardaway and Richardson. The hearings were scheduled to address Facebook's use and protection of user data in the wake of the Cambridge Analytica scandal.}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"CNET\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnet.com/news/who-are-diamond-silk-and-what-do-they-have-to-do-with-facebooks-mark-zuckerberg/|title=Who are Diamond and Silk, and what do they have to do with Facebook?|last=Ng|first=Alfred|date=April 11, 2018|website=CNET.com|access-date=April 11, 2018}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Newsweek3\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.newsweek.com/diamond-and-silk-facebook-zuckerberg-882332|title=Diamond and Silk hit back at Mark Zuckerberg, Facebook 'censorship': 'We are not terrorists' |last=Kutner|first=Max|date=April 11, 2018|access-date=April 11, 2018}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"cnn congress hearing\">{{Cite news|url=http://money.cnn.com/2018/04/26/media/diamond-and-silk-hearing/index.html|title=The Diamond and Silk show goes to Washington|last=Darcy|first=Oliver|date=|work=CNNMoney|access-date=April 28, 2018|quote=They had not been censored. Hardaway and Richardson's claims had been thoroughly debunked.}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"thehill cuomo\">{{Cite news|url=http://thehill.com/homenews/media/385176-chris-cuomo-confronts-gop-lawmaker-over-diamond-silks-claims-of-censorship|title=Chris Cuomo confronts GOP lawmaker over Diamond and Silk's claims of censorship|last=Bowden|first=John|date=April 27, 2018|work=TheHill|access-date=April 28, 2018|language=en|quote=The two pro-Trump personalities allege that a number of social media platforms, including Facebook, censored their content using algorithms to prevent it from showing up on users' feeds. They have provided no evidence for they claim, which Facebook and other companies deny. In addition, the two were found to have erroneously claimed that Facebook did not contact them over their concerns, despite an investigation showing that Facebook reps attempted to reach out to the two over email.}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"washingtonpost found fame\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/style/diamond-and-silk-how-two-small-town-north-carolina-sisters-found-fame-as-trump-fans/2018/04/26/1de3f50a-4723-11e8-9072-f6d4bc32f223_story.html|title=Who are Diamond and Silk? How two small-town ex-Democrats found fame as 'warriors' for Trump.|last=Hesse|first=Monica|date=April 26, 2018|work=Washington Post|access-date=April 28, 2018|last2=Zak|first2=Dan|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286|quote=Experts testified in Congress that there\u2019s no evidence of targeting... The numbers do not bear out the argument that the sisters have been repressed.}}</ref>\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://www.diamondandsilkinc.com}}\n* [https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCug1cL7vmUvYooOjXyHjsxQ/videos YouTube channel \"The Viewers View\"]\n* [https://twitter.com/DiamondandSilk Official Twitter account]\n* [http://www.facebook.com/DiamondandSilk/?ref=br_rs Official Facebook page]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Diamond and Silk}}\n[[Category:21st-century African-American activists]]\n[[Category:Activists from North Carolina]]\n[[Category:African-American bloggers]]\n[[Category:American bloggers]]\n[[Category:African-American Christians]]\n[[Category:African-American people in North Carolina politics]]\n[[Category:African-American women in politics]]\n[[Category:American media personalities]]\n[[Category:American political activists]]\n[[Category:American political blogs]]\n[[Category:American women bloggers]]\n[[Category:American YouTubers]]\n[[Category:Donald Trump 2016 presidential campaign]]\n[[Category:Entertainer duos]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:North Carolina Republicans]]\n[[Category:People associated with the 2016 United States presidential election]]\n[[Category:Video bloggers]]\n[[Category:Women in North Carolina politics]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "DrSusannaJDodgson", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removed para that had references that did not back up statements.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diamond_and_Silk"}
{"title_page": "Lagrange's theorem (number theory)", "text_new": "{{for|Lagrange's theorem|Lagrange's theorem (disambiguation)}}\nIn [[number theory]], '''Lagrange's theorem''' is a statement named after [[Joseph-Louis Lagrange]] about how frequently a [[polynomial]] over the [[integer]]s may evaluate to a multiple of a fixed [[Prime number|prime]]. More precisely, it states that if ''p'' is a prime number and <math>\\textstyle f(x) \\in \\mathbb{Z}[x]</math> is a polynomial with integer coefficients, then either:\n* every coefficient of {{math|''f''(''x'')}} is divisible by ''p'', or\n* {{math|''f''(''x'') &equiv; 0 (mod ''p'')}} has at most {{math|deg ''f''(''x'')}} incongruent solutions\n\nwhere {{math|deg ''f''(''x'')}} is the [[Degree of a polynomial|degree]] of {{math|''f''(''x'')}}. Solutions are \"incongruent\" if they do not differ by a multiple of ''p''. If the [[Modular arithmetic|modulus]] is not prime, then it is possible for there to be more than {{math|deg ''f''(''x'')}} solutions.\n\n==A proof of Lagrange's theorem==\n\nThe two key ideas are the following. Let {{math|''g''(''x'') &isin; ('''Z'''/''p'')[''x'']}} be the polynomial obtained from {{math|''f''(''x'')}} by taking the coefficients {{math|mod ''p''}}. Now:\n\n# {{math|''f''(''k'')}} is divisible by {{mvar|p}} if and only if {{math|''g''(''k'') {{=}} 0}}; and\n# {{math|''g''(''x'')}} has no more than {{math|deg ''g''(''x'')}} roots.\n\nMore rigorously, start by noting that {{math|''g''(''x'') {{=}} 0}} if and only if each coefficient of {{math|''f''(''x'')}} is divisible by {{mvar|p}}. Assume {{math|''g''(''x'') \u2260 0}}; its degree is thus well-defined. It is easy to see {{math|deg ''g''(''x'') \u2264 deg ''f''(''x'')}}. To prove (1), first note that we can compute {{math|''g''(''k'')}} either directly, i.e. by plugging in (the [[Modular_arithmetic#Congruence_classes|residue class]] of) {{mvar|k}} and performing arithmetic in {{math|'''Z'''/''p''}}, or by reducing {{math|''f''(''k'') mod ''p''}}. Hence {{math|''g''(''k'') {{=}} 0}} if and only if {{math|''f''(''k'') &equiv; 0 (mod ''p'')}}, i.e. if and only if {{math|''f''(''k'')}} is divisible by {{mvar|p}}. To prove (2), note that {{math|'''Z'''/''p''}} is a [[Field (mathematics)|field]], which is a standard fact (a quick proof is to note that since {{mvar|p}} is prime, {{math|'''Z'''/''p''}} is a finite [[integral domain]], hence is a field). Another standard fact is that a non-zero polynomial over a field has at most as many roots as its degree; this follows from the [[Polynomial long division|division algorithm]].\n\nFinally, note that two solutions {{math|''f''(''k''{{sub|1}}) &equiv; ''f''(''k''{{sub|2}}) &equiv; 0 (mod ''p'')}} are incongruent if and only if <math> k_1 \\not\\equiv k_2 </math> {{math|(mod ''p'')}}. Putting everything together, the number of incongruent solutions by (1) is the same as the number of roots of {{math|''g''(''x'')}}, which by (2) is at most {{math|deg ''g''(''x'')}}, which is at most {{math|deg ''f''(''x'')}}.\n\n==References==\n* {{cite book | last = LeVeque | first = William J. | authorlink = William J. LeVeque | title = Topics in Number Theory, Volumes I and II | publisher = Dover Publications | location = New York | year = 2002 | origyear = 1956 | isbn = 978-0-486-42539-9 | zbl = 1009.11001 | page = [https://archive.org/details/topicsinnumberth0000leve/page/42 42] | url = https://archive.org/details/topicsinnumberth0000leve/page/42 }}\n* {{cite book | title=Elementary Number Theory in Nine Chapters | first=James J. | last=Tattersall | edition=2nd | publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]] | year=2005 | isbn=0-521-85014-2 | zbl=1071.11002  | page=198 }}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lagrange's Theorem (Number Theory)}}\n[[Category:Theorems about prime numbers]]\n[[Category:Polynomials]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|Lagrange's theorem|Lagrange's theorem (disambiguation)}}\nIn [[number theory]], '''Lagrange's theorem''' is a statement named after [[Joseph-Louis Lagrange]] about how frequently a polynomial over the integers may evaluate to a multiple of a fixed prime. More precisely, it states that if ''p'' is a [[prime number]] and <math>\\textstyle f(x) \\in \\mathbb{Z}[x]</math> is a polynomial with integer coefficients, then either:\n* every coefficient of ''f''(''x'') is divisible by ''p'', or\n* {{math|''f''(''x'') &equiv; 0 (mod ''p'')}} has at most {{math|deg ''f''(''x'')}} incongruent solutions.\n\nSolutions are \"incongruent\" if they do not differ by a multiple of ''p''. If the [[Modular arithmetic|modulus]] is not prime, then it is possible for there to be more than deg ''f''(''x'') solutions.\n\n==A proof of Lagrange's theorem==\n\nThe two key ideas are the following. Let {{math|''g''(''x'') &isin; ('''Z'''/''p'')[''x'']}} be the polynomial obtained from {{math|''f''(''x'')}} by taking the coefficients {{math|mod ''p''}}. Now:\n\n# {{math|''f''(''k'')}} is divisible by {{mvar|p}} if and only if {{math|''g''(''k'') {{=}} 0}}; and\n# {{math|''g''(''x'')}} has no more than {{math|deg ''g''(''x'')}} roots.\n\nMore rigorously, start by noting that {{math|''g''(''x'') {{=}} 0}} if and only if each coefficient of {{math|''f''(''x'')}} is divisible by {{mvar|p}}. Assume {{math|''g''(''x'') \u2260 0}}; its degree is thus well-defined. It's easy to see {{math|deg ''g''(''x'') \u2264 deg ''f''(''x'')}}. To prove (1), first note that we can compute {{math|''g''(''k'')}} either directly, i.e. by plugging in (the residue class of) {{mvar|k}} and performing arithmetic in {{math|'''Z'''/''p''}}, or by reducing {{math|''f''(''k'') mod ''p''}}. Hence {{math|''g''(''k'') {{=}} 0}} if and only if {{math|''f''(''k'') &equiv; 0 (mod ''p'')}}, i.e. if and only if {{math|''f''(''k'')}} is divisible by {{mvar|p}}. To prove (2), note that {{math|'''Z'''/''p''}} is a field, which is a standard fact; a quick proof is to note that since {{mvar|p}} is prime, {{math|'''Z'''/''p''}} is a finite integral domain, hence is a field. Another standard fact is that a non-zero polynomial over a field has at most as many roots as its degree; this follows from the division algorithm.\n\nFinally, note that two solutions {{math|''f''(''k''{{sub|1}}) &equiv; ''f''(''k''{{sub|2}}) &equiv; 0 (mod ''p'')}} are incongruent if and only if <math> k_1 \\not\\equiv k_2 </math> {{math|(mod ''p'')}}. Putting it all together, the number of incongruent solutions by (1) is the same as the number of roots of {{math|''g''(''x'')}}, which by (2) is at most {{math|deg ''g''(''x'')}}, which is at most {{math|deg ''f''(''x'')}}.\n\n==References==\n* {{cite book | last = LeVeque | first = William J. | authorlink = William J. LeVeque | title = Topics in Number Theory, Volumes I and II | publisher = Dover Publications | location = New York | year = 2002 | origyear = 1956 | isbn = 978-0-486-42539-9 | zbl = 1009.11001 | page = [https://archive.org/details/topicsinnumberth0000leve/page/42 42] | url = https://archive.org/details/topicsinnumberth0000leve/page/42 }}\n* {{cite book | title=Elementary Number Theory in Nine Chapters | first=James J. | last=Tattersall | edition=2nd | publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]] | year=2005 | isbn=0-521-85014-2 | zbl=1071.11002  | page=198 }}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lagrange's Theorem (Number Theory)}}\n[[Category:Theorems about prime numbers]]\n[[Category:Polynomials]]\n", "name_user": "Joel Brennan", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lagrange%27s_theorem_(number_theory)"}
{"title_page": "YIMBY", "text_new": "'''YIMBY''' is an [[acronym]] for \"'''yes, in my back yard'''\", a pro-development movement in contrast and opposition to the [[NIMBY]] phenomenon.<ref name=\"SemuelsYIMBY\"/><ref name=\"AutoN1-1\"/> The YIMBY position typically supports development of housing within cities where housing costs have escalated to unaffordable levels, as opposed to the expansion of [[urban sprawl]]. YIMBYs often seek rezoning that would allow denser housing to be produced or the repurposing of obsolete buildings, such as malls, into housing.<ref>https://www.mercurynews.com/2019/06/25/yimby-neo-liberal-fascists-comment-perceived-threats-spark-backlash-against-local-planning-commissioner/</ref><ref>https://www.bostonglobe.com/opinion/2018/01/14/california-blow-your-lousy-zoning-laws/AcT0vOJCdArOJp3cBH9zmJ/story.html</ref><ref>https://www.citylab.com/equity/2019/07/oregon-single-family-zoning-reform-yimby-affordable-housing/593137/</ref> YIMBYs may also support public-interest projects like clean energy or alternative transport.<ref name=\"Toronto_YIMBY_festival\"/><ref name=\"NYT_Kuntz\"/><ref name=\"Guardian_YIMBY\"/> \n\nThe YIMBY movement has been described as [[populism|populist]], with supporters across the political spectrum including [[Left-wing politics|left-leaning]] adherents who believe housing production is a [[social justice]] issue and free-market [[libertarian]] proponents who think the supply of housing should not be regulated by the government. YIMBYs argue cities can be affordable and accessible to all by building more housing.<ref name=\"Seattle_YIMBYs\"/><ref name=\"Governing\"/>{{ r | NextCity_Stephens | p=1 | q=\"The YIMBY movement is aggressively populist, seeking housing supplies robust enough to enable virtually anyone to live in virtually any city he or she chooses.\" }}\n\n==History==\n\nThe pro-housing YIMBY position has emerged in regions experiencing unaffordable housing prices. ''[[The Guardian]]'' said this movement began in the [[San Francisco bay area]] in the 2010s due to [[California housing shortage|high housing costs]] created as a result of the local [[Silicon Valley|technology industry]] adding many more jobs to the region than the number of housing units constructed in the same time span.<ref> {{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/cities/2017/oct/02/rise-of-the-yimbys-angry-millennials-radical-housing-solution |title=Rise of the yimbys: the angry millennials with a radical housing solution |first=Erin |last=McCormick |location=San Francisco |date=October 2, 2017 |newspaper=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref> \n\nA 1993 essay published in the ''[[Journal of the American Planning Association]]'' entitled \"Planners' Alchemy, Transforming NIMBY to YIMBY: Rethinking NIMBY\" defined 'YIMBY' more broadly by arguing \"the local protectionism characterized as NIMBY represents a barrier not to societal goals but to the goals of capital.\"<ref>{{cite journal |first=Robert W. |last=Lake |date=Winter 1993 |title=Planners' Alchemy Transforming NIMBY to YIMBY: Rethinking NIMBY |journal=Journal of the American Planning Association |volume=59 |issue=1 |pages=87\u201393 |doi=10.1080/01944369308975847}}</ref>\n\n==Political debate==\n\nPolitical debate over housing development generally features YIMBY supporters pitted against local groups composed of [[homeowner|homeowners]] who oppose changes to their communities and [[leasehold estate|tenant]] organizations who say YIMBY policies favoring market-rate housing will ultimately lead to the displacement of vulnerable groups.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fastcompany.com/90384931/welcome-to-housing-twitter-the-shoutiest-debate-on-the-internet |title=Welcome to housing Twitter, the shoutiest debate on the internet |website=[[Fast Company]] |date=August 19, 2019 |df=mdy-all |first=Eillie |last=Anzilotti}}</ref>\n\nYIMBYs advocate for market-rate housing and say this is essential to making its development economically viable, which would create housing supply that would lower prices by [[supply and demand|satisfying demand]].<ref>{{cite AV media |type=Podcast |time=44:30 |title=Will the latest changes to controversial housing bill get Newsom on board? |time-caption=Scott Wiener, author of the YIMBY SB50 law, argues that the percentage of affordable housing is the maximum to make development viable at |url=https://calmatters.org/housing/2020/01/podcast-will-the-latest-changes-to-controversial-housing-bill-get-newsom-on-board/ |first=Matt |last=Levin  |date=January 10, 2020 |publisher=Calmatters |work=Gimme Shelter}}</ref> Those in opposition say adding market-rate housing rather than subsidized and means-tested [[affordable housing]] in a high-demand region can worsen housing affordability, especially for low and middle-income renters.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.livablecalifornia.org/special-report-california-yimby-scott-wiener-and-big-techs-troubling-housing-push/}}</ref> YIMBYs say market-rate development (including luxury development) will eventually result in affordable housing since wealthier residents will occupy these new units by vacating less desirable housing in a process called \"filtering.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://harvardpolitics.com/united-states/a-call-for-intersectional-yimbyism/|title=A Call for Intersectional YIMBYism}}</ref>\n\nYIMBYs say their anti-development counterparts obstruct development in defense of the status quo from which they alone benefit.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://transportationpriorities.org/nimby-yimby-niaby-yieby/ |title=NIMBY, YIMBY, NIABY, YIEBY |date=February 22, 2018 |first=Colin |last=Fiske |publisher=Coalition for Responsible Transportation Priorities}}</ref> Opponents have described YIMBY organizations as \"self-interested political calculations\" by special interests.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://therealdeal.com/la/2017/07/10/meet-the-yimbys-can-tech-bros-change-californias-housing-policies/amp/}}</ref>\n\nThe YIMBY movement cuts across the traditional political alignment, which usually sees developers and renters opposed, with homeowners uninvolved in the conflict. Because of this, equity groups in California have frequently opposed the movement, pointing to its [[Silicon Valley]] funding<ref>{{cite news |newspaper=Sacramento Bee |url=https://www.sacbee.com/news/politics-government/capitol-alert/article161525828.html |access-date=2020-04-09 |title='Yes in my backyard.' Silicon Valley money fuels fight against state\u2019s housing crisis |author=Angela Hart |date=2017-07-17}}</ref> and younger, whiter constituency.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://shelterforce.org/2019/02/19/yimby-white-privilege-and-the-soul-of-our-cities/ |access-date=2020-04-09 |date=2019-02-19 |author=Fernando Marti |title=YIMBY, White Privilege, and the Soul of Our Cities |work=Shelterforce}}</ref> At the same time, affordable-housing developers and environmental groups have endorsed YIMBY policies,<ref>{{cite press release |title=Major Environmental and Affordable Housing Organizations Endorse Senator Wiener\u2019s SB 50, the More HOMES Act |url=https://sd11.senate.ca.gov/news/20190131-major-environmental-and-affordable-housing-organizations-endorse-senator-wiener%E2%80%99s-sb |date=2019-01-13 |access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> while wealthy suburbs have vigorously protested any threat to single-family zoning.<ref>{{cite news|title=The Political Battle Over California's Suburban Dream |author=Laura Bliss |date=2019-04-05 |access-date=2020-04-09 |newspaper=CityLab}}</ref>\n\nYIMBYs and their opposition both cite concerns about the [[environmentalism|environment]], [[quality of life]], and [[social justice]] as motivating factors.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://smith.faculty.polsci.ucsb.edu/Nimby.pdf}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.citylab.com/equity/2019/07/nimby-vs-yimby-single-family-zoning-laws-california-housing/594373/}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://leginfo.legislature.ca.gov/faces/billTextClient.xhtml?bill_id=201920200SB50}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kqed.org/science/1941665/ceqa-some-call-landmark-environmental-law-a-nimby-tool-others-want-it-strenghthened}}</ref> Some journalists have said YIMBY and [[NIMBY]] positions are independent of the [[left\u2013right political spectrum]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/08/21/upshot/home-ownership-nimby-bipartisan.html |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |title=The Bipartisan Cry of 'Not in My Backyard' |first=Emily |last=Badger |date=August 21, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Seattle_YIMBYs\"/>\n\n==Research==\n\nThe central question vital to whether YIMBY policies will help or harm vulnerable communities is the effect of new construction on people already in precarious housing situations. If constructing new housing in an area at-risk for displacement accelerates that displacement, then YIMBYs are inherently opposed to the tenant organizations that have opposed them. New housing is generally very expensive; it can be used to house low-income people in two ways: [[inclusionary zoning]] mandates, where a portion of new housing is subsidized, and by filtering, where wealthier people move into the new homes, freeing up the supply of older, cheaper stock.\n\nA peer-reviewed study by Yonah Freemark published in 2019 found that an upzoning in Chicago which rezoned for denser development in a place where development was constrained by other means led to an increase in property values<ref>{{cite journal | last=Freemark | first=Yonah | title=Upzoning Chicago: Impacts of a Zoning Reform on Property Values and Housing Construction | journal=Urban Affairs Review | publisher=SAGE Publications | volume=56 | issue=3 | date=2019-01-29 | issn=1078-0874 | doi=10.1177/1078087418824672 | pages=758\u2013789 |lay-source=Does Upzoning Boost the Housing Supply and Lower Prices? Maybe Not. |lay-url=https://www.citylab.com/life/2019/01/zoning-reform-house-costs-urban-development-gentrification/581677/ |lay-date=2019-01-31}}</ref>, though the author has cautioned that the findings are easily misinterpreted.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://thefrisc.com/housing-arguments-over-sb-50-distort-my-upzoning-study-heres-how-to-get-zoning-changes-right-40daf85b74dc |author=Yonah Freemark |date=2019-05-22 |access-date=2020-04-09 |work=The Frisc |title=Housing Arguments Over SB 50 Distort My Upzoning Study. Here\u2019s How to Get Zoning Changes Right}}</ref>\n\nThe [[California Legislative Analyst's Office]] reported that parts of California which built more housing saw slower growth in rents for poor households, and that market-rate development has a strong protective effect against displacement, whereas the presence of an inclusionary-zoning mandate does not.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://lao.ca.gov/Publications/Report/3345 |author=[[California Legislative Analyst's Office]] |title=Perspectives on Helping Low-Income Californians Afford Housing |date=2016-02-09}}</ref>\n\nInclusionary zoning is the most direct way to create affordable housing, but it requires that the rest of the development subsidize the below-market-rate (BMR) units. As such, raising the required BMR percentage in San Francisco in 2016 actually led to a net ''reduction'' in the number of affordable units constructed, as it became less economical to construct projects--a slightly larger percentage of a much smaller number multiplied out to a smaller result.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://medium.com/yimby/the-25-inclusionary-rate-is-killing-affordable-housing-db143c4abd31 |date=2017-06-11 |access-date=2020-04-09 |title=The 25% inclusionary rate is killing affordable housing}}</ref>\n\nA peer-reviewed study published in ''[[Urban Studies (journal)|Urban Studies]]'' in 2006 said the \"filtering\" process (whereby wealthier households moving into new and desirable development results in vacancies which increases supply and lowers prices) is extremely slow and fails to provide urgently needed affordable housing.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://journals.sagepub.com/doi/10.1080/00420980500533612|title=Filtering, City Change and the Supply of Low-priced Housing in Canada|author=Andrejs Skaburskis|publisher = Urban Studies|date = 2006-03-01|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> \n\nEvan Mast from the [[Upjohn Institute]], in a 2019 working paper, investigated the filtering effect by tracing address history data, finding that migratory chains reach from low-income neighborhoods into new construction: \"building 100 new market-rate units leads 45-70 and 17-39 people to move out of below-median and bottom-quintile income tracts, respectively, with almost all of the effect occurring within five years\".<ref>{{cite report |url=https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=3426103 |doi=10.2139/ssrn.3426103  |last=Mast |first=Evan |title=The Effect of New Market-Rate Housing Construction on the Low-Income Housing Market |date=2019-07-24 |access-date=2020-04-09 |publisher=Upjohn Institute}}</ref> Another working paper revealed in 2020 by Brian Asquith and Davin Reed, also from the Upjohn Institute, found that new buildings lower rents directly nearby compared to locations without new buildings, because the large supply effect outweighs the amenity effect.<ref>{{cite report | last=Asquith | first=Brian J. | last2=Mast | first2=Evan | last3=Reed | first3=Davin | title=Supply Shock Versus Demand Shock: The Local Effects of New Housing in Low-Income Areas | publisher=Federal Reserve Bank of Philadelphia | year=2020 | issn=2574-0997 | doi=10.21799/frbp.wp.2020.07}}</ref>\n\n== Examples ==\n=== Canada ===\n\nIn [[Toronto]], Canada, a self-styled YIMBY movement was established in 2006 by community members in response to significant development proposals in the [[Queen Street West#Bathurst Street to Gladstone Avenue: West Queen Street West (the Art and Design District)|West Queen West]] area, and a YIMBY festival, launched the same year, has been held annually since.<ref name=\"AutoN1-2\"/><ref name=\"Toronto_Ziedler_interview\"/> The festival's organizer stated that \"YIMBYism is a community mindset that's open to change and development.\"<ref name=Toronto_Ziedler_interview />\n\n=== Sweden ===\n\nYimby is an independent political party network founded in Stockholm in 2007, which advocates physical development, [[densification]] and promotion of urban environment with chapters in [[Stockholm]], [[Gothenburg]], and [[Uppsala]].<ref name=\"NextCity_Sweden_YIMBY\"/>{{citation needed|date=June 2018|reason=There appear to be many references, but they are in Swedish. Need more English references to support all the statements of fact. See: [[WP:Articles for deletion/YIMBY]] references listed by sixth commentor.}} The group believes that the PBL (Plans and Constructions Act, from 1987) is a major impediment to any new construction, and should be eliminated or dramatically reformed.<ref name=\"NextCity_Sweden_YIMBY_2\"/>\n\n=== United Kingdom ===\n\nLondon YIMBY was set up in 2016, publishing its first report with the [[Adam Smith Institute]] in 2017<ref name=\"AutoN1-3\"/> which received national press coverage.<ref>{{cite news |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2017/aug/11/housing-shortage-nimbys-yes-in-my-backyard-yimby}}</ref> Its members advocate a policy termed 'Better Streets'. This proposal would allow residents of individual streets to vote by a two-thirds majority to pick a design code and allow extensions or replacement buildings of up to five or six stories, allowing suburban homes to be gradually replaced by mansion blocks. This flagship policy has achieved a degree of recognition, being endorsed by former Liberal Democrat MP [[Sam Gyimah]]<ref>{{cite news |newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2019/07/07/tories-really-want-provide-homes-need-do/}}</ref> and the leader of the House of Commons [[Jacob Rees-Mogg]].<ref>{{cite book |url=https://iea.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/2019/10/Raising-the-Roof-FULL-Interactive.pdf |website=Institute of Economic Affairs |title=Raising the Roof: How to solve the UK's housing crisis |editor-last1=Rees-Mogg |editor-first1=Jacob |editor-last2=Tylecote |editor-first2=Radomir |date=2019 |isbn=978-0-255-36783-7}}</ref> \n\nOther YIMBY groups have been set up in individual London boroughs and in cities suffering similar housing shortages, such as Brighton, Bristol and Edinburgh.\n\nMembers of the British YIMBY movement have been critical of established planning organisations such as the [[Town and Country Planning Association]] and the [[Campaign to Protect Rural England]], accusing them of pursuing policies that worsen Britain's housing shortage.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.citymetric.com/fabric/which-four-letter-acronym-worse-housing-crisis-cpre-or-tcpa-4719}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.citymetric.com/fabric/when-did-cpre-start-hating-houses-4567}}</ref>\n\n=== United States ===\n\n====California====\n\nSince 2014, in response to California's [[California housing shortage|housing affordability crisis]], several YIMBY groups were created in the [[San Francisco Bay Area]].<ref name=\"YIMBY_groups_fundraiser\"/><ref name=\"NYT_Build_baby_Build\"/> These groups have lobbied both locally and at the state level for increased housing production at all price levels, as well as using California's [[California Housing Accountability Act|Housing Accountability Act]] (the \"anti-NIMBY law\"){{ r | YIMBY_groups_fundraiser | p=1 | q=It has taken Berkeley, Lafayette and now Sausalito to court for alleged violations of the state&apos;s 35-year-old \u201canti-NIMBY (Not In My Backyard)\u201d housing law, the Housing Accountability Act, which requires cities to approve building permits that meet existing zoning rules. }} {{ r | NYT_Build_baby_Build | p=1 | q=She wrote the petition herself, saying the move violated the California Housing Accountability Act, a 1980s law and \u201canti-Nimby\u201d statute that limits cities&apos; ability to downsize housing developments. }} to sue cities when they attempt to block or down-size housing development.<ref name=YIMBY_groups_fundraiser/> ''[[The New York Times]]'' explained about one organization: \"Members want San Francisco and its suburbs to build more of every kind of housing. More subsidized affordable housing, more market-rate rentals, more high-end condominiums.\"<ref name=NYT_Build_baby_Build/>\n\nFrom 2018 to 2020, the lobbying group California YIMBY joined over 100 Bay Area technology industry executives in supporting state senator [[Scott Wiener]]'s [[California Senate Bill 50|transit rezoning bills]]. The bills failed in the state senate after multiple attempts at passage.{{ r | SFC_Yelp_CEO | p=1 | q=Stoppelman gave $100,000 to California YIMBY, a grassroots pro-housing group that sponsored Wiener&apos;s bill, SB827. The measure would have stopped cities from using planning, zoning and other barriers to block certain high-density housing projects up to five stories near public-transit stops. ... More than 100 Bay Area tech executives, including Stoppelman, Marc Benioff of Salesforce, and Jack Dorsey of Twitter and Square, signed a letter to Wiener supporting his bill. }}{{ r | SJMN_Stripe | p=1 | q=Stripe on Thursday became the latest tech company to funnel money toward the Bay Area&apos;s housing crunch, donating $1 million to pro-development political group California YIMBY. The San Francisco-based online payments company, valued at $9 billion, says the money will help YIMBY push policies with the ultimate goal of increasing California&apos;s building rate from 80,000 homes a year to 500,000. ... Other tech leaders are weighing in on housing policy. In January more than 100 California tech leaders, including the CEOs of Salesforce, Lyft, Yelp and Mozilla, signed a letter supporting SB 827 \u2014 the failed bill that would have forced cities to allow denser housing developments near transit hubs. Now Stripe is upping the ante by $1 million with its contribution, the first the company has ever made to a political organization. The sum is the largest single donation California YIMBY has received, and it will increase the organization&apos;s total coffers by about 50 percent, said California YIMBY executive director Brian Hanlon. Prior to Thursday, the organization had raised nearly $2 million from donors including Yelp CEO Jeremy Stoppelman. }}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://sd25.senate.ca.gov/news/2019-05-16/senator-portantino\u2019s-statement-sb-50 |title=Senator Portantino's Statement on SB 50 |website=California State Senate |date=May 16, 2019 |location=Sacramento, California |first=Anthony J. |last=Portantino}}</ref> California YIMBY received $100,000 from [[Yelp]] CEO [[Jeremy Stoppelman]], $1 million from Irish entrepreneurs [[John Collison|John]] and [[Patrick Collison|Patrick]] Collison through their company, [[Stripe (company)|Stripe]], and $500,000 raised by [[Pantheon (software)|Pantheon]] CEO Zach Rosen and [[GitHub]] CEO [[Nat Friedman]].<ref> https://www.theinformation.com/articles/tech-leaders-seek-bigger-political-role-with-housing-push </ref><ref>https://stripe.com/newsroom/news/stripe-donates-to-california-yimby</ref>\n\n====Massachusetts====\n\nSince 2012, several YIMBY groups were established in the greater Boston area.<ref name=\"Boston_YIMBY\"/><ref name=\"Boston_YIMBY_2\"/><ref name=\"Boston_YIMBY_4\"/> One group argues that \"...more smart housing development is the only way to retain a middle class in pricey cities like Boston and Cambridge.\"<ref name=\"Boston_YIMBY_3\"/>\n\n====New York====\n\nIn 2011, a YIMBY news website was created that focuses on construction trends in [[New York City]].{{ r | NYT_NY-YIMBY }} In an interview with ''[[Politico]]'', the creator stated: \"[[Zoning in the United States|Zoning]] is the problem, not development in this city. I think people don't really understand that.\"{{ r | Politico_Fedak }} Several YIMBY groups have also been created in New York City; according to an organizer: \"In high-opportunity areas where people actually really want to live, the well-heeled, mostly white residents are able to use their perceived political power to stop the construction of basically anything,\" adding that low-income communities don't share that ability to keep development at bay: \"Philosophically, we think that the disproportionate share of the burden of growth has been borne by low income, minority or industrial neighborhoods for far too long.\"{{ r | Curbed_NY_YIMBY }}\n\n=== International ===\n\nIn September 2018, the third annual Yes In My Backyard conference, named \"YIMBYTown\" occurred in Boston, hosted by that area's YIMBY community.<ref name=\"AutoN1-4\"/> The first YIMBY conference was held in 2016 in [[Boulder, Colorado]]<ref name=\"Stranger_first_YIMBY_conference\"/> and hosted by a group that included Boulder's former mayor, who commented that: \"It is clearer than ever that if we really care about solving big national issues like inequality and climate change, tackling the lack of housing in thriving urban areas, caused largely by local zoning restrictions, is key.\"<ref name=\"NYT_conference\"/> The second annual conference was held in the San Francisco Bay Area city of [[Oakland, California]].<ref name=\"Curbed_2017\"/> These conferences have attracted attendees from the United States, as well as some from Canada, England, Australia, and other countries.<ref name=\"BC_2017_conf\"/>{{ r | NextCity_Stephens }}\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[CAVE people]]\n* [[Drawbridge mentality]]\n* [[New Urbanism]]\n\n== References ==\n{{refs|30em|refs=\n<ref name=\"SemuelsYIMBY\">{{cite magazine | last1=Semuels | first1=Alana | title=From 'Not in My Backyard' to 'Yes in My Backyard' | url=https://www.theatlantic.com/business/archive/2017/07/yimby-groups-pro-development/532437/ | accessdate=5 July 2017 | magazine=[[The Atlantic]] | date=5 July 2017 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180325163835/https://www.theatlantic.com/business/archive/2017/07/yimby-groups-pro-development/532437/ | archive-date=2018-03-25 | url-status=live | quote=Out of a desire for more-equitable housing policy, some city dwellers have started allying with developers instead of opposing them. }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"AutoN1-1\">{{cite web|url=http://acronyms.thefreedictionary.com/YIMBY|title=YIMBY|publisher=|accessdate=15 September 2016|via=The Free Dictionary}}</ref>\n<ref name=Toronto_YIMBY_festival>{{ cite news | url=http://www.metronews.ca/news/toronto/2015/09/09/yimby-festival-coming-to-toronto.html | title=YIMBY Festival brings together Toronto's city-builders | last=Bateman | first=Chris | publisher=Toronto Metro | date=2015-09-09 | accessdate=15 September 2016 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160302090236/http://www.metronews.ca/news/toronto/2015/09/09/yimby-festival-coming-to-toronto.html | archive-date=2016-03-02 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n<ref name=NYT_Kuntz >{{cite news | url=https://ideas.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/08/17/from-liberal-nimby-to-green-yimby/ | title=From Liberal NIMBY to Green YIMBY | last=Kuntz | first=Tom | newspaper=[[The New York Times]] | date=2009-08-17 | accessdate=2018-07-31 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091220034138/https://ideas.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/08/17/from-liberal-nimby-to-green-yimby/ | archive-date=2009-12-20 | url-status=live | quote=\"There's a growing recognition that opposition to growth \u2014 in Berkeley and Oakland, for example \u2014 contributed to environmentally unfriendly suburban and exurban sprawl, and that \"infill development\" \u2014 dense urban housing near mass transit \u2014 is now the way to go.\" }}</ref>\n<ref name=Guardian_YIMBY >{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/cities/2017/oct/02/rise-of-the-yimbys-angry-millennials-radical-housing-solution | title=Rise of the yimbys: the angry millennials with a radical housing solution | last=McCormick | first=Erin | newspaper=[[The Guardian]] | date=2017-10-02 | accessdate=2018-08-23 | archiveurl=https://web.ar