{"title_page": "Ni\u00f1a", "text_new": "{{About||atmospheric phenomenon|La Ni\u00f1a|La 5\u00aa Estaci\u00f3n song|Ni\u00f1a (song)|the Reik song|Reik (album)}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin |display title=ital}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image   = Gustav Adolf Closs - Die Schiffe des Columbus - 1892.jpg\n|Ship image size = 250px\n|Ship caption = A depiction of ''Ni\u00f1a'' as a [[caravel]] on the left\n}}\n\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header        =\n|Ship country       = [[Spain]]\n|Ship flag          = [[Image:Banner of arms crown of Castille Habsbourg style.svg|60px]]\n|Ship name          = ''Santa Clara''\n|Ship namesake      = Santa Clara Monastery\n|Ship owner         = [[Ni\u00f1o brothers|Juan Ni\u00f1o]]\n|Ship ordered       =\n|Ship builder       =\n|Ship original cost =\n|Ship laid down     =\n|Ship launched      = Before 1492\n|Ship fate          = Last log 1501\n|Ship status        =\n|Ship notes         = Name is Spanish for \"little girl\" \u2013 captained by Balboa\n|Ship nickname      = ''Ni\u00f1a''\n}}\n\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header       =\n|Header caption    =\n|Ship class        = [[Caravel]]\n|Ship tons burthen = 50\u201360 tons\n|Ship length       = {{convert|15.24|m|ft|abbr=on}} on deck\n|Ship beam         = {{convert|4.85|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship draught      = {{convert|2.07|m|ft|abbr=on}}\n|Ship draft        =\n|Ship hold depth   =\n|Ship propulsion   =\n|Ship sail plan    =\n|Ship complement   = 24\n|Ship armament     =\n|Ship notes        =\n}}\n|}\n\n'''''La Ni\u00f1a''''' ([[Spanish language|Spanish]] for ''The Little Girl'') was one of the three [[Spain|Spanish]] ships used by [[Genoa|Genoan]] explorer [[Christopher Columbus]] in his first voyage to the [[West Indies]] in 1492. As was tradition for Spanish ships of the day, she bore a female saint's name, '''''Santa Clara.''''' However, she was commonly referred to by her nickname, ''La Ni\u00f1a,'' which was probably a pun on the name of her owner, [[Ni\u00f1o brothers|Juan Ni\u00f1o]] of [[Moguer]].<ref>{{cite book |first1=Patrick J. |last1=Murphy |first2=Ray W. |last2=Coye |title=Mutiny and Its Bounty: Leadership Lessons from the Age of Discovery |url=http://yalepress.yale.edu/yupbooks/Book.asp?isbn=9780300170283 |date=2013|publisher=Yale University Press|isbn=9780300170283 |ref=harv}}</ref> She was a standard [[caravel]]-type vessel.\n\nThe other ships of the Columbus expedition were the caravel-type {{ship||Pinta|ship|2}} and the [[carrack]]-type {{ship||Santa Mar\u00eda|ship|2}}. ''Ni\u00f1a'' was by far Columbus' favorite. She was originally [[lateen sail]] rigged ''caravela latina'', but she was re-rigged as ''caravela redonda'' at [[Las Palmas]], in the [[Canary Islands]], with [[square sail]]s for better ocean performance.<ref>{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uBhLAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA140&dq=Lateen+Sails+of+the+Ni%C3%B1a+changed+into+square+ones&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjs7YTM8M_JAhXIHh4KHdwfBEYQ6AEIHTAA#v=onepage&q=Lateen%20Sails%20of%20the%20Ni%C3%B1a%20changed%20into%20square%20ones&f=false | title=The Life of Christopher Columbus: From Authentic Spanish and Italian Documents | publisher=The American News Company | author=Barry, J. J. | year=1869 | location=New York | pages=140}}</ref> There is no authentic documentation on the specifics of ''Ni\u00f1a''{{'}}s design, although Michele de Cuneo, who accompanied Columbus on his second voyage, mentioned that ''Ni\u00f1a'' was \"''about'' 60 toneladas\" (60 tons), which may indicate a medium-sized caravel of around {{convert|50|ft|m}} in length on deck.<ref>{{cite book|author1=William D. Phillips|author2=Carla Rahn Phillips|title=The Worlds of Christopher Columbus|year=1992|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-44652-5|pages=143\u2013145|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8jhtmzLlX70C&pg=PA145&lpg=PA145&dq=carla+rahn+phillips+ship+60+feet#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref> Often said to have had three masts, there is some evidence she may have had four masts.<ref name=thenina>{{cite web |url=http://www.thenina.com/building_thereplica.htm |title=The Story of the Ni\u00f1a |website=TheNina.com - Official site of the replica ship |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080515071023/http://www.thenina.com/building_thereplica.htm |archivedate=2008-05-15 |df= }}</ref>\n\n''Ni\u00f1a'', like ''Pinta'' and ''Santa Mar\u00eda'', was a smaller trade ship built to sail the Mediterranean sea, not the open ocean. It was greatly surpassed in size by ships like {{ship||Peter von Danzig|ship|2}} of the [[Hanseatic League]], built in 1462, {{convert|51|m|ft|abbr=on}} in length, and the [[England|English]] carrack {{ship||Grace Dieu|ship|2}}, built during the period 1420\u20131439, weighing between 1,400 and 2,750 tons,  and {{convert|66.4|m|ft|abbr=on}} long, in both weight and length.\n\n==History==\nOn Columbus' first expedition, ''Ni\u00f1a'' carried 26 men, captained by [[Vicente Y\u00e1\u00f1ez Pinz\u00f3n]]. They left [[Palos de la Frontera]] on 3 August 1492, stopping at the [[Canary Islands]] on 12 August 1492, and continued westward. Landfall was made in the [[Bahamas]] at dawn on 12 October 1492.\n\nOn 14 February 1493, in the east of the [[Azores]], a storm threatened to capsize ''Ni\u00f1a'', and at Columbus' instigation, he and the crew took [[Columbus' vow|a series of vows]] to perform certain acts including religious pilgrimages upon their return to Spain.<ref>[[Christopher Columbus]] and [[Bartolom\u00e9 de las Casas]], Samuel Kettell (translator), ''Personal narrative of the first voyage of Columbus to America: From a manuscript recently discovered in Spain'', T. B. Wait and Son, 1827. p. 216. [https://books.google.com/books?id=M8QRAAAAYAAJ Online] at [[Google Books]]. A version in modern Spanish\u2014[http://www.artehistoria.jcyl.es/cronicas/contextos/9733.htm Text for 11-16 February] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090414113518/http://www.artehistoria.jcyl.es/cronicas/contextos/9733.htm |date=2009-04-14 }}\u2014can be accessed online at artehistoria.jcyl.es.</ref> ''Ni\u00f1a'' reached [[Lisbon]], [[Portugal]], on 4 March 1493, and arrived in Palos de la Frontera on 15 March 1493.<ref>{{cite book |last=Fern\u00e1ndez Duro |first=Ces\u00e1reo |authorlink=Ces\u00e1reo Fern\u00e1ndez Duro |title=Pinz\u00f3n en el descubrimiento de las Indias |url=https://archive.org/stream/pinzbonenel00fernrich#page/n3/mode/2up |publisher=Sucesores de Rivadeneyra |location=Madrid |year=1892 |page=113}}</ref> On the first voyage to America, the crew of ''Ni\u00f1a'' slept on the deck but adopted the use of [[hammock]]s after seeing Native Americans utilizing them.<ref name=thenina/>\n\nIn September 1493, ''Ni\u00f1a'' joined a grand fleet of 17 ships for the second voyage to [[Hispaniola]], becoming the flagship for an exploration of [[Cuba]]. She was the only ship to survive the 1495 hurricane, returning quickly to [[Spain]] in 1496.\n\n''Ni\u00f1a'' was then chartered for an unauthorized voyage to [[Rome]]. She was captured by a pirate corsair when leaving the port of [[Cagliari]] and brought to [[Pula, Sardinia|Cape Pula]], Sardinia. The Captain, Alonso Medel, escaped with a few men. He stole a boat, rowed back to ''Ni\u00f1a'', and made sail, returning to [[C\u00e1diz]].\n\nIn 1498, she returned to [[Hispaniola]] as advance guard of Columbus' Third Voyage. She was lying in wait at [[Santo Domingo]] in 1500. In 1501, she made a trading voyage to the Pearl Coast on the island of [[Cubagua]], [[Venezuela]], and no further log of her is found in historic archives.<ref>{{cite book |title=Environment and History ('Ruined and Lost': Spanish Destruction of the Pearl Coast in the Early Sixteenth Century) |author=Michael Perri |url=http://www.erica.demon.co.uk/EH/EH1505.html |volume=15 |year=2009 |pages=129\u2013161 |doi=10.3197/096734009X437963 |accessdate=2013-12-04}}</ref>\n\n''Ni\u00f1a'' logged at least {{convert|25000|nmi|km|-3}} under Columbus' command.\n\n==Replicas==\n[[File:The Nina And Pinta \u2014 Official Views Of The World's Columbian Exposition \u2014 86.jpg|right|thumb|''Ni\u00f1a'' and ''Pinta'' replicas at the 1893 [[World's Columbian Exposition|Columbian Exposition]]]]\n[[File:Ni\u00f1a replica - Morro Bay CA.jpg|right|thumb|The replica of the Columbus Foundation]]\nA replica of ''Ni\u00f1a'' was built by the Spanish government for the Columbian Naval Review of 1893. Along with replicas of ''Santa Mar\u00eda'' and ''Pinta'' she participated in the review.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=9D07EED61731E033A25755C2A9629C94629ED7CF|title=QUEER CRAFT THESE CARAVELS. -  Those Who Saw Them Hobble to Anchor Marveled at Columbus's Pluck.|date=26 April 1893|newspaper=New York Times|accessdate=18 November 2015|url-access=subscription }}</ref>\n\nA replica of ''Ni\u00f1a'' (based upon theory; there are no known contemporary likenesses of any of the three ships) now sails around the world.\n\nThe 4-masted replica ''Ni\u00f1a'' was built 1988-1991 by engineer and naval researcher John Patrick Sarsfield, British naval historian Jonathan Morton Nance, and a group of master shipbuilders in Bahia, Brazil who were still using design and construction techniques dating back to the 15th century. They built it from heavy, teredo-resistant Brazilian hardwoods using only [[adze]]s, axes, hand saws, and chisels. The sails were designed by Nance using square main sails and two aft lateen sails as were used by ships of this size at the end of the 15th century. The crew of ''Ni\u00f1a'' say that it can make about {{convert|5|\u2013|7|kn|lk=in}}, which is quicker than older designs of the era. The replica weighs 75 tons.\n\nIn 1991, the replica sailed to Costa Rica to take part in the filming of ''[[1492: Conquest of Paradise]]'',<ref>{{cite web|title=The Ni\u00f1a|publisher=Ni\u00f1a Traveling Museum|url=http://www.thenina.com|accessdate=2008-05-10}}</ref> and ''Ni\u00f1a'' has visited hundreds of North America ports to give the public a chance to see and tour the ship. The vessel continues to visit ports across the Eastern to mid-United States along with its sister replica ship, ''Pinta''. The replicas of ''Ni\u00f1a'' and ''Pinta'' were built in [[Valen\u00e7a, Rio de Janeiro|Valen\u00e7a, Brazil]] using the same methods as the 15th century [[Portuguese people|Portuguese]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thesunnews.com/2011/05/12/2153691/history-visits-strand.html|archive-url=https://archive.is/20120912112551/http://www.thesunnews.com/2011/05/12/2153691/history-visits-strand.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=2012-09-12|title=History visits Bucksport in form of boats|last=Slate|first=Charles|work=[[The Sun News]]|date=2011-05-12|accessdate=2011-05-12}}</ref>\n\nOther replicas are located in Andalusia, Spain (at [[El Puerto de Santa Mar\u00eda]] and at the [[Wharf of the Caravels]] in Palos de la Frontera). A replica had been harbored in Corpus Christi, Texas in the United States, but it sunk on April 23, 2019\u2014from Hurricane Harvey.\n\nThe historic [[San Francisco]] restaurant [[Bernstein's Fish Grotto]] was designed to look like ''Ni\u00f1a''.<ref name=\"timeshutter\">{{cite web|url=http://www.timeshutter.com/image/bernsteins-fish-grotto-123-powell-st-san-francisco-calif|title=Bernstein's Fish Grotto, 123 Powell Street. San Francisco|publisher=timeshutter.com|accessdate=26 April 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140427000243/http://www.timeshutter.com/image/bernsteins-fish-grotto-123-powell-st-san-francisco-calif|archivedate=27 April 2014|df=}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Columbian Exchange]] \n*[[Nina (disambiguation)]]\n* [[The Grand Exchange]]\n*[[The Pinz\u00f3n Brothers]]\n*[[Voyages of Christopher Columbus]]\n*[[Wharf of the Caravels]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Ni\u00f1a (ship, 1491)|Ni\u00f1a}}\n*[http://www.thenina.com TheNina.com \u2013 Official site of one of the replica ships]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nina}}\n[[Category:Exploration ships]]\n[[Category:Age of Discovery ships]]\n[[Category:Christopher Columbus]]\n[[Category:1492 in the Spanish West Indies]]\n[[Category:Spanish West Indies]]\n[[Category:15th-century ships]]\n[[Category:Age of Sail individual ships]]\n", "text_old": "{{About||atmospheric phenomenon|La Ni\u00f1a|La 5\u00aa Estaci\u00f3n song|Ni\u00f1a (song)|the Reik song|Reik (album)}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin |display title=ital}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image   = Gustav Adolf Closs - Die Schiffe des Columbus - 1892.jpg\n|Ship image size = 250px\n|Ship caption = A depiction of ''Ni\u00f1a'' as a [[caravel]] on the left\n}}\n\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header        =\n|Ship country       = [[Spain]]\n|Ship flag          = [[Image:Banner of arms crown of Castille Habsbourg style.svg|60px]]\n|Ship name          = ''Santa Clara''\n|Ship namesake      = Santa Clara Monastery\n|Ship owner         = [[Ni\u00f1o brothers|Juan Ni\u00f1o]]\n|Ship ordered       =\n|Ship builder       =\n|Ship original cost =\n|Ship laid down     =\n|Ship launched      = Before 1492\n|Ship fate          = Last log 1501\n|Ship status        =\n|Ship notes         = Name is Spanish for \"little girl\" \u2013 captained by Balboa\n|Ship nickname      = ''Ni\u00f1a''\n}}\n\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header       =\n|Header caption    =\n|Ship class        = [[Caravel]]\n|Ship tons burthen = 50\u201360 tons\n|Ship length       = {{convert|15.24|m|ft|abbr=on}} on deck\n|Ship beam         = {{convert|4.85|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship draught      = {{convert|2.07|m|ft|abbr=on}}\n|Ship draft        =\n|Ship hold depth   =\n|Ship propulsion   =\n|Ship sail plan    =\n|Ship complement   = 24\n|Ship armament     =\n|Ship notes        =\n}}\n|}\n\n'''''La Ni\u00f1a''''' ([[Spanish language|Spanish]] for ''The Little Girl'') was one of the three [[Spain|Spanish]] ships used by [[Genoan]] explorer [[Christopher Columbus]] in his first voyage to the [[West Indies]] in 1492. As was tradition for Spanish ships of the day, she bore a female saint's name, '''''Santa Clara.''''' However, she was commonly referred to by her nickname, ''La Ni\u00f1a,'' which was probably a pun on the name of her owner, [[Ni\u00f1o brothers|Juan Ni\u00f1o]] of [[Moguer]].<ref>{{cite book |first1=Patrick J. |last1=Murphy |first2=Ray W. |last2=Coye |title=Mutiny and Its Bounty: Leadership Lessons from the Age of Discovery |url=http://yalepress.yale.edu/yupbooks/Book.asp?isbn=9780300170283 |date=2013|publisher=Yale University Press|isbn=9780300170283 |ref=harv}}</ref> She was a standard [[caravel]]-type vessel.\n\nThe other ships of the Columbus expedition were the caravel-type {{ship||Pinta|ship|2}} and the [[carrack]]-type {{ship||Santa Mar\u00eda|ship|2}}. ''Ni\u00f1a'' was by far Columbus' favorite. She was originally [[lateen sail]] rigged ''caravela latina'', but she was re-rigged as ''caravela redonda'' at [[Las Palmas]], in the [[Canary Islands]], with [[square sail]]s for better ocean performance.<ref>{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uBhLAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA140&dq=Lateen+Sails+of+the+Ni%C3%B1a+changed+into+square+ones&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjs7YTM8M_JAhXIHh4KHdwfBEYQ6AEIHTAA#v=onepage&q=Lateen%20Sails%20of%20the%20Ni%C3%B1a%20changed%20into%20square%20ones&f=false | title=The Life of Christopher Columbus: From Authentic Spanish and Italian Documents | publisher=The American News Company | author=Barry, J. J. | year=1869 | location=New York | pages=140}}</ref> There is no authentic documentation on the specifics of ''Ni\u00f1a''{{'}}s design, although Michele de Cuneo, who accompanied Columbus on his second voyage, mentioned that ''Ni\u00f1a'' was \"''about'' 60 toneladas\" (60 tons), which may indicate a medium-sized caravel of around {{convert|50|ft|m}} in length on deck.<ref>{{cite book|author1=William D. Phillips|author2=Carla Rahn Phillips|title=The Worlds of Christopher Columbus|year=1992|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-44652-5|pages=143\u2013145|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8jhtmzLlX70C&pg=PA145&lpg=PA145&dq=carla+rahn+phillips+ship+60+feet#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref> Often said to have had three masts, there is some evidence she may have had four masts.<ref name=thenina>{{cite web |url=http://www.thenina.com/building_thereplica.htm |title=The Story of the Ni\u00f1a |website=TheNina.com - Official site of the replica ship |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080515071023/http://www.thenina.com/building_thereplica.htm |archivedate=2008-05-15 |df= }}</ref>\n\n''Ni\u00f1a'', like ''Pinta'' and ''Santa Mar\u00eda'', was a smaller trade ship built to sail the Mediterranean sea, not the open ocean. It was greatly surpassed in size by ships like {{ship||Peter von Danzig|ship|2}} of the [[Hanseatic League]], built in 1462, {{convert|51|m|ft|abbr=on}} in length, and the [[England|English]] carrack {{ship||Grace Dieu|ship|2}}, built during the period 1420\u20131439, weighing between 1,400 and 2,750 tons,  and {{convert|66.4|m|ft|abbr=on}} long, in both weight and length.\n\n==History==\nOn Columbus' first expedition, ''Ni\u00f1a'' carried 26 men, captained by [[Vicente Y\u00e1\u00f1ez Pinz\u00f3n]]. They left [[Palos de la Frontera]] on 3 August 1492, stopping at the [[Canary Islands]] on 12 August 1492, and continued westward. Landfall was made in the [[Bahamas]] at dawn on 12 October 1492.\n\nOn 14 February 1493, in the east of the [[Azores]], a storm threatened to capsize ''Ni\u00f1a'', and at Columbus' instigation, he and the crew took [[Columbus' vow|a series of vows]] to perform certain acts including religious pilgrimages upon their return to Spain.<ref>[[Christopher Columbus]] and [[Bartolom\u00e9 de las Casas]], Samuel Kettell (translator), ''Personal narrative of the first voyage of Columbus to America: From a manuscript recently discovered in Spain'', T. B. Wait and Son, 1827. p. 216. [https://books.google.com/books?id=M8QRAAAAYAAJ Online] at [[Google Books]]. A version in modern Spanish\u2014[http://www.artehistoria.jcyl.es/cronicas/contextos/9733.htm Text for 11-16 February] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090414113518/http://www.artehistoria.jcyl.es/cronicas/contextos/9733.htm |date=2009-04-14 }}\u2014can be accessed online at artehistoria.jcyl.es.</ref> ''Ni\u00f1a'' reached [[Lisbon]], [[Portugal]], on 4 March 1493, and arrived in Palos de la Frontera on 15 March 1493.<ref>{{cite book |last=Fern\u00e1ndez Duro |first=Ces\u00e1reo |authorlink=Ces\u00e1reo Fern\u00e1ndez Duro |title=Pinz\u00f3n en el descubrimiento de las Indias |url=https://archive.org/stream/pinzbonenel00fernrich#page/n3/mode/2up |publisher=Sucesores de Rivadeneyra |location=Madrid |year=1892 |page=113}}</ref> On the first voyage to America, the crew of ''Ni\u00f1a'' slept on the deck but adopted the use of [[hammock]]s after seeing Native Americans utilizing them.<ref name=thenina/>\n\nIn September 1493, ''Ni\u00f1a'' joined a grand fleet of 17 ships for the second voyage to [[Hispaniola]], becoming the flagship for an exploration of [[Cuba]]. She was the only ship to survive the 1495 hurricane, returning quickly to [[Spain]] in 1496.\n\n''Ni\u00f1a'' was then chartered for an unauthorized voyage to [[Rome]]. She was captured by a pirate corsair when leaving the port of [[Cagliari]] and brought to [[Pula, Sardinia|Cape Pula]], Sardinia. The Captain, Alonso Medel, escaped with a few men. He stole a boat, rowed back to ''Ni\u00f1a'', and made sail, returning to [[C\u00e1diz]].\n\nIn 1498, she returned to [[Hispaniola]] as advance guard of Columbus' Third Voyage. She was lying in wait at [[Santo Domingo]] in 1500. In 1501, she made a trading voyage to the Pearl Coast on the island of [[Cubagua]], [[Venezuela]], and no further log of her is found in historic archives.<ref>{{cite book |title=Environment and History ('Ruined and Lost': Spanish Destruction of the Pearl Coast in the Early Sixteenth Century) |author=Michael Perri |url=http://www.erica.demon.co.uk/EH/EH1505.html |volume=15 |year=2009 |pages=129\u2013161 |doi=10.3197/096734009X437963 |accessdate=2013-12-04}}</ref>\n\n''Ni\u00f1a'' logged at least {{convert|25000|nmi|km|-3}} under Columbus' command.\n\n==Replicas==\n[[File:The Nina And Pinta \u2014 Official Views Of The World's Columbian Exposition \u2014 86.jpg|right|thumb|''Ni\u00f1a'' and ''Pinta'' replicas at the 1893 [[World's Columbian Exposition|Columbian Exposition]]]]\n[[File:Ni\u00f1a replica - Morro Bay CA.jpg|right|thumb|The replica of the Columbus Foundation]]\nA replica of ''Ni\u00f1a'' was built by the Spanish government for the Columbian Naval Review of 1893. Along with replicas of ''Santa Mar\u00eda'' and ''Pinta'' she participated in the review.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=9D07EED61731E033A25755C2A9629C94629ED7CF|title=QUEER CRAFT THESE CARAVELS. -  Those Who Saw Them Hobble to Anchor Marveled at Columbus's Pluck.|date=26 April 1893|newspaper=New York Times|accessdate=18 November 2015|url-access=subscription }}</ref>\n\nA replica of ''Ni\u00f1a'' (based upon theory; there are no known contemporary likenesses of any of the three ships) now sails around the world.\n\nThe 4-masted replica ''Ni\u00f1a'' was built 1988-1991 by engineer and naval researcher John Patrick Sarsfield, British naval historian Jonathan Morton Nance, and a group of master shipbuilders in Bahia, Brazil who were still using design and construction techniques dating back to the 15th century. They built it from heavy, teredo-resistant Brazilian hardwoods using only [[adze]]s, axes, hand saws, and chisels. The sails were designed by Nance using square main sails and two aft lateen sails as were used by ships of this size at the end of the 15th century. The crew of ''Ni\u00f1a'' say that it can make about {{convert|5|\u2013|7|kn|lk=in}}, which is quicker than older designs of the era. The replica weighs 75 tons.\n\nIn 1991, the replica sailed to Costa Rica to take part in the filming of ''[[1492: Conquest of Paradise]]'',<ref>{{cite web|title=The Ni\u00f1a|publisher=Ni\u00f1a Traveling Museum|url=http://www.thenina.com|accessdate=2008-05-10}}</ref> and ''Ni\u00f1a'' has visited hundreds of North America ports to give the public a chance to see and tour the ship. The vessel continues to visit ports across the Eastern to mid-United States along with its sister replica ship, ''Pinta''. The replicas of ''Ni\u00f1a'' and ''Pinta'' were built in [[Valen\u00e7a, Rio de Janeiro|Valen\u00e7a, Brazil]] using the same methods as the 15th century [[Portuguese people|Portuguese]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thesunnews.com/2011/05/12/2153691/history-visits-strand.html|archive-url=https://archive.is/20120912112551/http://www.thesunnews.com/2011/05/12/2153691/history-visits-strand.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=2012-09-12|title=History visits Bucksport in form of boats|last=Slate|first=Charles|work=[[The Sun News]]|date=2011-05-12|accessdate=2011-05-12}}</ref>\n\nOther replicas are located in Andalusia, Spain (at [[El Puerto de Santa Mar\u00eda]] and at the [[Wharf of the Caravels]] in Palos de la Frontera). A replica had been harbored in Corpus Christi, Texas in the United States, but it sunk on April 23, 2019\u2014from Hurricane Harvey.\n\nThe historic [[San Francisco]] restaurant [[Bernstein's Fish Grotto]] was designed to look like ''Ni\u00f1a''.<ref name=\"timeshutter\">{{cite web|url=http://www.timeshutter.com/image/bernsteins-fish-grotto-123-powell-st-san-francisco-calif|title=Bernstein's Fish Grotto, 123 Powell Street. San Francisco|publisher=timeshutter.com|accessdate=26 April 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140427000243/http://www.timeshutter.com/image/bernsteins-fish-grotto-123-powell-st-san-francisco-calif|archivedate=27 April 2014|df=}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Columbian Exchange]] \n*[[Nina (disambiguation)]]\n* [[The Grand Exchange]]\n*[[The Pinz\u00f3n Brothers]]\n*[[Voyages of Christopher Columbus]]\n*[[Wharf of the Caravels]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Ni\u00f1a (ship, 1491)|Ni\u00f1a}}\n*[http://www.thenina.com TheNina.com \u2013 Official site of one of the replica ships]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nina}}\n[[Category:Exploration ships]]\n[[Category:Age of Discovery ships]]\n[[Category:Christopher Columbus]]\n[[Category:1492 in the Spanish West Indies]]\n[[Category:Spanish West Indies]]\n[[Category:15th-century ships]]\n[[Category:Age of Sail individual ships]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toGenoese(link changed toGenoa) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ni%C3%B1a"}
{"title_page": "Effective altruism", "text_new": "{{short description|Philosophy and social movement that applies evidence and reason to determine the most effective ways to benefit others}}\n[[File:London Thinks - Prof Peter Singer - What's the most good you can do.webm|thumb|Professor [[Peter Singer]] lectures on 'What's [[The Most Good You Can Do|the most good you can do]]?' at [[Conway Hall]] in 2015.]]\n'''Effective altruism''' is a [[philosophy]] and [[social movement]] that advocates using [[Scientific evidence|evidence]] and [[reasoning]] to determine the most effective ways to benefit others.<ref name=\"MacAskill-intro\">{{cite journal|last=MacAskill|first=William|authorlink=William MacAskill|title=Effective altruism: introduction|journal=Essays in Philosophy|date=January 2017|volume=18|issue=1|page=eP1580:1\u20135|doi=10.7710/1526-0569.1580|language=en|issn=1526-0569|url=https://commons.pacificu.edu/eip/vol18/iss1/1|ref=harv}}</ref>{{rp|2}}<ref name=\"Singer2015\">{{cite book |last=Singer |first=Peter |authorlink=Peter Singer |date=2015 |title=[[The Most Good You Can Do|The Most Good You Can Do: How Effective Altruism Is Changing Ideas About Living Ethically]] |series=Castle lectures in ethics, politics, and economics |location=New Haven |publisher=[[Yale University Press]] |isbn=9780300180275 |oclc=890614537 |ref=harv}}</ref>{{rp|4\u20137}} ''[[Altruism]]'' refers to improving the lives of others\u2014as opposed to [[egoism]], which emphasizes only self-interest.<ref name=\"Singer2015\"/>{{rp|4\u20135}}<ref name=\"doing-good-better\">{{cite book |last=MacAskill |first=William |authorlink=William MacAskill |title=[[Doing Good Better|Doing Good Better: How Effective Altruism Can Help You Help Others, Do Work that Matters, and Make Smarter Choices about Giving Back]] |date=2016 |origyear=2015 |location=New York |publisher=Avery |isbn=9781592409662 |oclc=932001639 |ref=harv}}</ref>{{rp|12}} ''[[Effectiveness]]'' refers to doing the ''most'' good with whatever resources are available\u2014as opposed to only doing ''some'' amount of good\u2014as well as determining what is the most good by using evidence and reasoning\u2014as opposed to only doing what [[Emotion|feels]] good or appears intuitively appealing.<ref name=\"Singer2015\"/>{{rp|6\u20137}}<ref name=\"doing-good-better\"/>{{rp|12}}\n\nMany people who espouse effective altruism call themselves ''effective altruists''.<ref>For example, a public [[Facebook group]] for effective altruists with the group ID \"effective.altruists\" had around 17,900 members on January 31, 2020: {{cite web |title=Effective Altruism |website=facebook.com |url=https://www.facebook.com/groups/effective.altruists/about/ |archiveurl=https://archive.is/l9CAN |archivedate=January 31, 2020 |accessdate=January 31, 2020}} At the same time, another social networking website listed over 200 local groups for effective altruists from around the world, the majority of them located in Europe and North America: {{cite web |title=EA Hub Groups |website=eahub.org |url=https://eahub.org/groups/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200201150010/https://eahub.org/groups/ |archivedate=February 1, 2020 |accessdate=February 1, 2020}} The term ''effective altruists'' is also used in many published sources such as {{harvtxt|Singer|2015}} and {{harvtxt|MacAskill|2017}}.</ref> While many effective altruists have focused on the [[nonprofit sector]], the philosophy of effective altruism applies more broadly to prioritizing the scientific projects, companies, and policy initiatives which can be estimated to save lives, help people, or otherwise have the biggest benefit.<ref name=\"doing-good-better\"/>{{rp|179\u2013195}}\n\n==Philosophy==\n[[File:Peter Singer MIT Veritas.jpg|thumb|[[Peter Singer]] is one of several philosophers who helped popularize effective altruism.]]\nPhilosophers played an important role in creating effective altruism (see {{slink||History of the social movement}} below), and much of the published literature about effective altruism poses philosophical questions about why and how to use evidence and reasoning to determine the most effective ways to benefit others, and then tries to figure out the most plausible answers to those questions, so that people can take action on the basis of those answers.<ref name=\"EA-IEE\">{{cite encyclopedia |last1=Pummer |first1=Theron |last2=MacAskill |first2=William |authorlink2=William MacAskill |date=2019 |title=Effective altruism |editor-last=LaFollette |editor-first=Hugh |encyclopedia=International Encyclopedia of Ethics |location=Hoboken, NJ |publisher=[[John Wiley & Sons]] |isbn=9781444367072 |oclc=829259960 |doi=10.1002/9781444367072 |url=https://philarchive.org/archive/PUMEA |ref=harv}}</ref><ref name=\"MacAskill-definition\">{{cite book |last=MacAskill |first=William |authorlink=William MacAskill |chapter=The definition of effective altruism |date=2019 |editor1-last=Greaves |editor1-first=Hilary |editor1-link=Hilary Greaves |editor2-last=Pummer |editor2-first=Theron |title=Effective Altruism: Philosophical Issues |series=Engaging philosophy |location=Oxford; New York |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |pages=10\u201328 |isbn=9780198841364 |oclc=1101772304 |doi=10.1093/oso/9780198841364.003.0001 |ref=harv}}</ref> Such philosophical questions shift the starting point of reasoning from \"what to do\" to why and how to do it.<ref name=\"practical-ethics\">{{cite web |last=Crouch |first=Will |date=May 30, 2013 |title=What is effective altruism? |url=http://blog.practicalethics.ox.ac.uk/2013/05/what-is-effective-altruism/ |website=blog.practicalethics.ox.ac.uk |publisher=Practical Ethics blog, Philosophy Faculty, [[University of Oxford]] |accessdate=February 4, 2020 |ref=harv}}</ref>\n\nThe \"guiding question\"<ref name=\"doing-good-better\"/>{{rp|14}} of effective altruism is: How can we, individually and collectively, do the most good?<ref name=\"Singer2015\"/>{{rp|5}}<ref name=\"EA-IEE\"/> Other questions that quickly follow include:\n* \"What counts as 'the most good'?\"<ref name=\"Singer2015\"/>{{rp|7}}\n* \"How can I do the most good, given what others are likely to do?\"<ref name=\"EA-IEE\"/>\n* \"Does everyone's suffering count equally?\"<ref name=\"Singer2015\"/>{{rp|7}}\n* \"Does 'the most good you can do' mean that it is wrong to give priority to one's own children?\"<ref name=\"Singer2015\"/>{{rp|8}}\n* \"What about other values, like [[justice]], [[freedom]], [[Social equality|equality]], and [[knowledge]]?\"<ref name=\"Singer2015\"/>{{rp|8}}\n* \"Can everyone practice effective altruism?\"<ref name=\"Singer2015\"/>{{rp|9}}\n* Is it better to think of effective altruism \"as an 'opportunity' or an 'obligation'?\"<ref name=\"MacAskill-definition\"/>{{rp|16}}\n* \"What if one's act reduces suffering, but to do so one must lie or harm an innocent person?\"<ref name=\"Singer2015\"/>{{rp|9}} Do \"[[the ends justify the means]]\"?<ref name=\"MacAskill-definition\"/>{{rp|20}}\n* \"What would have happened otherwise?\"<ref name=\"doing-good-better\"/>{{rp|13}}\n* \"What are the chances of success, and how good would success be?\"<ref name=\"doing-good-better\"/>{{rp|13}}\n\nThere is reasonable disagreement, among philosophers and other people, about the answers to such questions.<ref name=\"EA-IEE\"/> But the minimal philosophical core of effective altruism involves at least having some reason to benefit all others, that is, reason to promote their [[well-being]],<ref>{{harvtxt|MacAskill|2019}} said of the emphasis on well-being in effective altruism: \"This [[welfarism]] is 'tentative', however, insofar as it is taken to be merely a working assumption. The ultimate aim of the effective altruist project is to do as much good as possible; the current focus on wellbeing rests on the idea that, given the current state of the world and our incredible opportunity to benefit others, the best ways of promoting welfarist value are broadly the same as the best ways of promoting the good.\" (p.&nbsp;18)</ref> \"and more reason to benefit them more, and most reason to benefit them as much as possible, at least [[Defeasibility|defeasibly]] and [[all other things being equal]]\".<ref name=\"EA-IEE\"/> This minimal philosophical core of effective altruism is likely to be supported by a wide variety of views about [[morality]] and [[meta-ethics]].<ref name=\"MacAskill-intro\"/><ref name=\"EA-IEE\"/> For example, the moral theory of [[consequentialism]], including [[utilitarianism]], supports the aim of using resources to benefit others as much as possible, but effective altruism is not necessarily, as has sometimes been said, the same as consequentialism.<ref name=\"MacAskill-intro\"/><ref name=\"EA-IEE\"/>\n\nThere are different views about whether effective altruism entails [[Normative ethics|normative ethical]] claims such as \"we should do the most good we can\".<ref>{{harvtxt|Singer|2015}} expressed a clearly normative view: \"Effective altruism is based on a very simple idea: we should do the most good we can. Obeying the usual rules about not stealing, cheating, hurting, and killing is not enough, or at least not enough for those of us who have the great good fortune to live in material comfort, who can feed, house, and clothe ourselves and our families and still have money or time to spare. Living a minimally acceptable ethical life involves using a substantial part of our spare resources to make the world a better place. Living a fully ethical life involves doing the most good we can.\" (p.&nbsp;vii)</ref><ref name=\"MacAskill-definition\"/>{{rp|12\u201315}} One view says that effective altruism is not a set of normative claims (telling what people \"should do\") but instead is a project, intellectual and practical, of \"trying to figure out how to use resources in whatever way will do the most good with a given unit of resources\" and of putting what has been learned into practice.<ref name=\"MacAskill-definition\"/>{{rp|15}} According to this view, the normative ethical theories of consequentialism, [[egalitarianism]], [[prioritarianism]], [[contractualism]], [[deontological ethics]], [[virtue ethics]], as well as many traditional religious teachings on altruism, can all be compatible with the project of effective altruism.<ref name=\"MacAskill-intro\"/><ref name=\"EA-IEE\"/> Effective altruism is not a ''complete'' philosophy of how to live morally, but effective altruism may be relevant for any view that assumes some reason to promote the good and that assumes that the well-being of others is part of the good.<ref name=\"MacAskill-definition\"/>{{rp|19}}\n\nSome people have reported that the questions and answers posed by the philosophy of effective altruism have helped them learn more about complex problems and gain a deeper sense of meaning as well as a feeling of satisfaction about helping others more effectively.<ref>For example, ''[[Vox (website)|Vox]]'' staff writer and self-identified effective altruist Kelsey Piper wrote: \"You're asked to sacrifice to do good, but in return you get real and important results, as well as a life filled with meaning and purpose. You're asked to spend a lot of time thinking about complicated, intimidating questions, but you will learn how to approach hard questions and come away with a clearer picture of the world.\" {{cite book |last=Piper |first=Kelsey |date=2020 |chapter=Effective altruism |editor1-last=Pigliucci |editor1-first=Massimo |editor1-link=Massimo Pigliucci |editor2-last=Cleary |editor2-first=Skye |editor3-last=Kaufman |editor3-first=Daniel |title=How to Live a Good Life: A Guide to Choosing Your Personal Philosophy |location=New York |publisher=[[Vintage Books]] |pages=255\u2013270 (268) |isbn=9780525566144 |oclc=1133275390 |ref=harv}} And {{harvtxt|Singer|2015}} reported: \"Second, effective altruism is a way of giving meaning to our own lives and finding fulfillment in what we do. Many effective altruists say that in doing good, they feel good. Effective altruists directly benefit others, but indirectly they often benefit themselves.\" (p.&nbsp;viii)</ref>\n\nThe following subsections describe important ideas that are discussed in the published literature about effective altruism.\n\n===Impartiality===\n[[File:1793 Equality anagoria.JPG|thumb|An allegorical image of equality by Jean-Guillaume Moitte, 1793]]\nAltruism, or benefitting others, can be driven by various kinds of motivation and justification, including impartial or impersonal reasoning and sentiments such as sympathy and compassion.<ref>{{cite SEP |url-id=altruism |title=Altruism |edition=Spring 2018 |last=Kraut |first=Richard |date=August 25, 2016 |accessdate=February 4, 2020 |ref=harv}} See especially the section [https://plato.stanford.edu/archives/spr2018/entries/altruism/#WhyCareAbouOthe \"4. Why care about others?\"]: \"Radically different ways of answering these questions [about why to benefit others] can be found in moral philosophy.\"</ref> Much of the published literature on effective altruism emphasizes impartial or impersonal reasoning and concludes that, all other things being equal, everyone's well-being (and suffering) counts equally, without regard to the individual identities of others.<ref name=\"Singer2015\"/>{{rp|85\u201395}}<ref name=\"EA-IEE\"/><ref name=\"MacAskill-definition\"/>{{rp|17\u201319}}\n\nImpartiality about benefitting others combined with seeking to do the most good is compatible with prioritizing benefits to those who are in a worse state, because anyone who happens to be worse off will benefit more from an improvement in their state, all other things being equal (see {{slink||Global poverty alleviation}} below).<ref name=\"EA-IEE\"/> Impartiality is also the basis of what is called the ''cause neutrality'' of effective altruism (see {{slink||Cause prioritization}} below): choosing among possible altruistic activities or causes (problems) based on whether they will do the most good with limited resources\u2014as opposed to choosing among them based on other factors such as personal connections.<ref name=\"EA-IEE\"/>\n\nSome effective altruists have argued that there will be many more members of future generations than there are members of current populations, so the way to do the most good is to focus on promoting long-term well-being by, for example, reducing [[Risks to civilization, humans, and planet Earth|existential risks to humanity]] (see {{slink||Long-term future and global catastrophic risks}} below).<ref name=\"Singer2015\"/>{{rp|165\u2013178}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://80000hours.org/articles/future-generations/|title=Introducing longtermism: How important are future generations?|last=Todd|first=Benjamin|date=October 24, 2017|website=80000 Hours|access-date=February 8, 2020|quote=Since the future is big, there could be far more people in the future than in the present generation. This means that if you want to help people in general, your ''key concern'' shouldn't be to help the present generation, but to ensure that the future goes well in the long-term. Previously, we called this the 'long-term value thesis', though it is now most commonly called 'longtermism'. This thesis is often confused with the claim that we shouldn't ''do'' anything to help people in the present generation. But the long-term value thesis is about what most ''matters''\u2014what we should ''do'' about it is a further question. It might turn out that the best way to help those in the future is to improve the lives of people in the present, such as through providing health and education.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Beckstead |first=Nick |chapter=A brief argument for the overwhelming importance of shaping the far future |date=2019 |editor1-last=Greaves |editor1-first=Hilary |editor1-link=Hilary Greaves |editor2-last=Pummer |editor2-first=Theron |title=Effective Altruism: Philosophical Issues |series=Engaging philosophy |location=Oxford; New York |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |pages=80\u201398 |isbn=9780198841364 |oclc=1101772304 |doi=10.1093/oso/9780198841364.003.0006 |ref=harv}}</ref>\n\nSome effective altruists think that the [[Animal rights|interests of non-human animals]] should be accorded equal moral weight as similar interests of humans, so they work to prevent the suffering of animals (see {{slink||Animal welfare}} below),<ref>{{cite journal |last=Fisher |first=Andrew |date=January 2017 |title=Theory-neutral arguments for 'effective animal advocacy' |journal=Essays in Philosophy |volume=18 |issue=1 |pages=eP1578:1\u201314 |doi=10.7710/1526-0569.1578 |url=https://commons.pacificu.edu/eip/vol18/iss1/3 |issn=1526-0569 |ref=harv}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last=Broad |first=Garrett M. |date=December 2018 |title=Effective animal advocacy: effective altruism, the social economy, and the animal protection movement |journal=Agriculture and Human Values |volume=35 |issue=4 |pages=777\u2013789 |doi=10.1007/s10460-018-9873-5 |ref=harv}}</ref> especially animals raised in [[Factory farming|factory farms]].<ref name=whyfarmedanimals>{{Cite web|url=https://animalcharityevaluators.org/donation-advice/why-farmed-animals/|title=Why Farmed Animals?|website=Animal Charity Evaluators|language=en-US|access-date=|date=November 2016}}</ref>\n\nThere are many kinds of motivation and justification for impartiality, as for altruism.<ref name=\"sep-impartiality\">{{cite SEP |url-id=impartiality |title=Impartiality |edition=Spring 2018 |last=Jollimore |first=Troy |date=February 6, 2017 |accessdate=March 11, 2017 |ref=harv}}</ref> An argument for impartiality that has been influential among effective altruists<ref>On the influence of Singer's essay \"[[Famine, Affluence, and Morality]]\" see, for example: {{harvnb|Snow|2015}}, {{harvnb|Singer|2015|pp=13\u201320}}, and {{cite magazine |last=Lichtenberg |first=Judith |date=November 30, 2015 |title=Peter Singer's extremely altruistic heirs: Forty years after it was written, 'Famine, Affluence, and Morality' has spawned a radical new movement |url=https://newrepublic.com/article/124690/peter-singers-extremely-altruistic-heirs |magazine=[[The New Republic]] |ref=harv}}</ref> was expressed by philosopher [[Peter Singer]] in his 1972 essay \"[[Famine, Affluence, and Morality]]\", in which he wrote:\n\n<blockquote>It makes no moral difference whether the person I can help is a neighbor's child ten yards away from me or a Bengali whose name I shall never know, ten thousand miles away.&nbsp;... The moral point of view requires us to look beyond the interests of our own society. Previously,&nbsp;... this may hardly have been feasible, but it is quite feasible now. From the moral point of view, the prevention of the starvation of millions of people outside our society must be considered at least as pressing as the upholding of property norms within our society.<ref name=\"Singer1972\">{{cite journal |last=Singer |first=Peter |date=Spring 1972 |title=Famine, Affluence, and Morality |journal=[[Philosophy and Public Affairs]] |volume=1 |issue=3 |pages=229\u2013243 |jstor=2265052 |ref=harv}} The essay was republished in book form in 2016 with a new preface and two extra essays by Singer: {{cite book |last=Singer |first=Peter |date=2016 |title=Famine, Affluence, and Morality |location=Oxford; New York |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |isbn=9780190219208 |oclc=907446001 |ref=harv}}</ref>{{rp|231\u2013232, 237}}</blockquote>\n\nThis argument for impartiality was later repeated in other books by Singer<ref name=\"Singer2015\"/><ref name=\"Singer2009\"/> and expanded on in the 1996 book ''[[Living High and Letting Die]]'' by philosopher [[Peter Unger]].<ref>{{cite journal |last=Feldman |first=Fred |date=March 1998 |title=Review of ''Living High and Letting Die: Our Illusion of Innocence'' by Peter Unger |journal=[[No\u00fbs]] |volume=32 |issue=1 |pages=138\u2013147 |doi=10.1111/0029-4624.00093 |jstor=2671931 |url=https://people.umass.edu/ffeldman/Unger.pdf |ref=harv}}</ref>\n\n====Obstacles to impartiality====\nSinger speculated in \"Famine, Affluence, and Morality\" that whether people actually reason and act impartially is likely to be affected by [[social influence]]: \"What it is possible for a man to do and what he is likely to do are both, I think, very greatly influenced by what people around him are doing and expecting him to do.\"<ref name=\"Singer1972\"/>{{rp|237}} In his 2015 book ''[[The Most Good You Can Do]]'', Singer admitted that even though he had argued in 1972 that \"we ought to give large proportions of our income to disaster relief funds\", nevertheless \"even though I argued that this is what we ought to do, I did not do it myself\".<ref name=\"Singer2015\"/>{{rp|13}} He noted the role of social influence and [[psychological inertia]] as obstacles to acting altruistically.<ref name=\"Singer2015\"/>{{rp|13\u201314}} Sociological research has shown that social influence can undermine altruistic activity.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Simpson |first1=Brent |last2=Willer |first2=Robb |authorlink2=Robb Willer |date=August 2015 |title=Beyond altruism: sociological foundations of cooperation and prosocial behavior |journal=[[Annual Review of Sociology]] |volume=41 |pages=43\u201363 |doi=10.1146/annurev-soc-073014-112242 |ref=harv}} \"More generally, laboratory studies of socially decontextualized groups show that person-level factors alone are generally unable to sustain cooperation at the high levels observed in many human groups. As noted above, these groups initially show much variation in contributions, with more altruistic individuals giving at high levels and more egoistic people contributing little or nothing at all. Contributions of more altruistic individuals then decline over time in response to their egoistic counterparts' noncooperation (Fehr & Gintis 2007, Sell & Wilson 1991). Thus, in the absence of social mechanisms\u2014e.g., clear enforceable norms, opportunities to gain reputation or status for contributions to group efforts, or social connections between group members\u2014contributions fall to very low levels.\" (p.&nbsp;56)</ref> To support people's ability to act altruistically on the basis of impartial reasoning, the effective altruism movement promotes additional values and actions that are not part of the minimal philosophical core of effective altruism, such as a collaborative spirit, honesty and transparency, and publicly pledging to donate a certain percentage of income or other resources.<ref name=\"MacAskill-intro\"/>{{rp|2}}\n\n===Cause prioritization===\nMany nonprofits emphasize effectiveness and evidence, but this is usually done with a single cause (problem) in mind, such as education or climate change.<ref>{{cite web |last=Schambra |first=William A. |date=May 22, 2014 |title=Opinion: The coming showdown between philanthrolocalism and effective altruism |url=https://www.philanthropydaily.com/the-coming-showdown-between-philanthrolocalism-and-effective-altruism/ |website=Philanthropy Daily |quote=Strategic philanthropists like Paul Brest seek only to apply metrics to the selection of groups once a cause has been selected. But, altruist critics note, this foolishly leaves the choice of the cause itself willy-nilly to the all-too-often idiosyncratic, short-sighted, selfish impulses of the donor.}}</ref> Effective altruists, however, seek to compare the relative importance of different causes and allocate resources among them objectively, a concept that is usually referred to as ''cause neutrality''.<ref name=\"cause-neutrality\">{{Cite web |last=Schubert |first=Stefan |date=March 10, 2017 |url=https://www.centreforeffectivealtruism.org/blog/understanding-cause-neutrality/ |title=Understanding cause-neutrality |website=Centre for Effective Altruism |language=en-US |access-date=March 10, 2020 |ref=harv}} Schubert said that the term ''cause neutrality'' has been used by various authors with different meanings and different [[decision rule]]s.</ref> One approach to cause neutrality, for example, is to choose the highest priority causes based on whether activities in each cause area could efficiently advance broad goals, such as increasing human or animal welfare, and then focus attention on interventions in those cause areas.<ref>{{harvtxt|Schubert|2017}} called this approach the \"cause-flexible investments\" strategy and compared it to other strategies such as \"cause-divergent investments\". With regard to these two strategies, he noted: \"How to prioritize between these two strategies is an important and understudied question.\"</ref>\n\nThe information required for cause prioritization can be difficult to produce; it may involve collecting and processing complex [[data set]]s, comparing possible outcomes with what would have happened under other conditions (see {{slink||Counterfactual reasoning}} below), and identifying various kinds of [[uncertainty]].<ref name=\"EA-IEE\"/><ref>{{cite journal |last=MacAskill |first=William |authorlink=William MacAskill |date=September 2019 |title=Practical ethics given moral uncertainty |journal=[[Utilitas]] |volume=31 |issue=3 |pages=231\u2013245 |doi=10.1017/S0953820819000013 |ref=harv}}</ref> These challenges have led to the creation of organizations that specialize in researching the relative prioritization of causes.<ref name=\"EA-IEE\"/><ref name=\"Problems\">{{Cite web|url=https://80000hours.org/problem-profiles/|title=Our current view of the world's most pressing problems|website=80,000 Hours|language=en-US|access-date=March 10, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|last=Karnofsky|first=Holden|authorlink=Holden Karnofsky|date=January 26, 2018|url=https://www.openphilanthropy.org/blog/update-cause-prioritization-open-philanthropy|title=Update on cause prioritization at Open Philanthropy|website=www.openphilanthropy.org|access-date=March 10, 2020}}</ref> Some common priorities among effective altruists have included poverty in the [[Developing country|developing world]], the suffering of animals in [[Factory farming|factory farms]], and [[Global catastrophic risk|risks to civilization, humans and planet Earth]] (see {{slink||Cause priorities}} below).<ref name=\"doing-good-better\" /><ref name=practical-ethics/>\n\n===Cost-effectiveness===\nEffective altruist organizations have argued that some charities are far more effective than others, either because some do not achieve their goals or because of variability in the cost of achieving those goals.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.givewell.org/giving101/Funding-the-Right-Program | publisher = GiveWell | title = Your dollar goes further when you fund the right program }}</ref><ref name=dollar-overseas>{{cite web | url = http://www.givewell.org/giving101/Your-dollar-goes-further-overseas | publisher = GiveWell | title = Your Dollar Goes Further Overseas}}</ref> When possible, they seek to identify charities that are highly [[cost-effectiveness analysis|cost-effective]], meaning that they achieve a large benefit for a given amount of money.<ref name=\"The Atlantic article The Greatest Good\" /> For example, they select health interventions on the basis of their impact as measured by lives saved per dollar, [[quality-adjusted life year]]s (QALY) saved per dollar, or [[disability-adjusted life year]]s (DALY) averted per dollar. This measure of disease burden is expressed as the number of years lost due to ill-health, disability or early death.\n\nSome effective altruism organizations use [[randomized controlled trial]]s as a primary form of evidence,<ref name=\"The Atlantic article The Greatest Good\" /><ref name=\"skelton\">{{cite journal|last1=Skelton|first1=Anthony|title=The ethical principles of effective altruism|journal=Journal of Global Ethics|date=2016|volume=12|issue=2|pages=137\u2013146|url=https://philpapers.org/rec/SKETEP|accessdate= March 11, 2017|doi=10.1080/17449626.2016.1193552|ref=harv}}</ref> as they are often considered to be at the highest level of strong evidence in healthcare research.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://nhmrc.gov.au/about-us/publications/guide-development-evaluation-and-implementation-clinical-practice-guidelines|title=A guide to the development, implementation and evaluation of clinical practice guidelines|last=|first=|publisher=National Health and Medical Research Council|year=1998|isbn=1864960485|location=Canberra: Commonwealth of Australia|pages=21\u201325}}</ref> Others have argued that requiring this stringent level of evidence unnecessarily narrows the focus to only those issues on which this kind of evidence is possible, and that the history of philanthropy suggests that the most effective interventions have often proceeded without this level of evidence.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Karnofsky|first=Holden|authorlink=Holden Karnofsky|date=April 4, 2016|url=https://www.openphilanthropy.org/blog/hits-based-giving|title=Hits-based giving|website=www.openphilanthropy.org|access-date=March 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Room for more funding====\nEffective altruist organizations make philanthropic recommendations for charities on the basis of the impact from marginal funding rather than merely evaluating the average value of all donations to the charity.<ref name=\"givewell-interview-huffpo\">{{cite web|last1=Zhang|first1=Linch|title=How Can You do the Most Good with Your Charitable Giving? This Expert's Answers Might Surprise You|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/linch-zhang/how-can-you-do-the-most-g_b_10597442.html|website=Huffington Post|accessdate= March 18, 2017|date= June 21, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"SSIR-holden\">{{cite web|last1=Karnofsky|first1=Holden|title=We Should Expect Good Giving To Be Hard (SSIR)|url=https://ssir.org/articles/entry/we_should_expect_good_giving_to_be_hard|website=Stanford Social Innovation Review|publisher=Stanford University|accessdate=March 18, 2017|language=en-us}}</ref> Effective altruists avoid donating to organizations that have no \"room for more funding\" \u2013 those that face bottlenecks other than money which prevent them from spending the funds they have already accumulated or are expected to receive.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.givewell.org/how-we-work/criteria/room-for-more-funding|title=Room for More Funding {{!}} GiveWell|website=www.givewell.org|access-date=2019-01-12}}</ref> For example, a medical charity might not be able to hire enough doctors or nurses to distribute the medical supplies it is capable of purchasing, or it might already be serving all of the potential patients in its market. There are many other organizations which ''do'' have room for more funding, so giving to one of those instead would produce real-world improvements.\n\n===Counterfactual reasoning===\nEffective altruists argue that [[Counterfactual conditional|counterfactual]] reasoning is important to determine which course of action maximizes positive impact. Many people assume that the best way to help people is through direct methods, such as working for a charity or providing social services,<ref>{{cite news | title = Best jobs for saving the world | first1 = Donna | last1  = Rosato | first2 = Grace | last2 = Wong | date = November 2011 | url = http://money.cnn.com/magazines/moneymag/best-jobs/2011/jobs-helping-others/1.html | accessdate = February 28, 2013 | work=CNN}}</ref> but since charities and social-service providers usually can find people willing to work for them, effective altruists compare the amount of good somebody does in a conventional altruistic career to how much good would have been done had the next-best candidate been hired for the position. According to this reasoning, the impact of a career may be smaller than it appears.<ref name=\"todd-career-paper\">{{cite web|last1=Todd|first1=Benjamin|title=Which Ethical Careers Make a Difference?: The Replaceability Issue in the Ethics of Career Choice|url=https://www.academia.edu/1807196|website=University of Oxford|accessdate= March 11, 2017|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://80000hours.org/2015/07/replaceability-isnt-as-important-as-you-might-think-or-weve-suggested/|title='Replaceability' isn't as important as you might think (or we've suggested)|date=2015-07-27|website=80,000 Hours|language=en-US|access-date=2019-01-12}}</ref>\n\n==Behavior==\nThe philosophical or intellectual part of effective altruism, described above, is about learning how to do the most good through the use of evidence and reasoning. The behavioral or practical part is about using what has been learned to try to do the most good through altruistic activities.<ref name=\"EA-IEE\"/><ref name=\"MacAskill-definition\"/>{{rp|14}}\n\n===Donation===\n\nEffective altruism encourages significant charitable donation. Some believe it is a moral duty to alleviate suffering through donations if the purchases that one forgoes to donate do not cause comparable suffering to oneself,<ref name=Singer1972 /> leading some of them to lead a frugal lifestyle in order to give substantially more than is typical in their society.<ref name=\"kaufman-wise\">{{cite news|last1=Burton|first1=Paul|title=Family Gives Away Half Their Income To Help Others|url=http://boston.cbslocal.com/2015/10/13/family-gives-away-half-their-income-to-help-others/|accessdate= March 11, 2017|date=October 13, 2015}}</ref> Advocacy focuses on increasing the amount that people donate or identifying nonprofits that best meet the criteria of effective altruism, in particular cost-effectiveness, transparency and strong evidence.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.givewell.org/how-we-work/criteria|title=Our Criteria for Top Charities {{!}} GiveWell|website=www.givewell.org|access-date=2018-12-09}}</ref>\n\n[[Giving What We Can]] (GWWC) is an organization that hosts a community of individuals who have pledged to donate at least 10% of their income for the remainder of their working lives to the causes that they believe are the most effective. GWWC was founded in 2009 by [[Toby Ord]], a moral philosopher, who lives on \u00a318,000 ($27,000) per year and donates the remainder of his income to charity.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/magazine-11950843|title=Toby Ord: Why I'm giving \u00a31m to charity|last=Geoghegan|first=Tom|date= December 13, 2010|accessdate= March 2, 2013|newspaper=BBC News}}</ref> As of 2019, more than 4,100 individuals have taken the pledge, who have collectively pledged to donate upwards of $1.5 billion over the course of their lifetimes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.givingwhatwecan.org/|title=Giving What We Can|website=www.givingwhatwecan.org|access-date=2018-12-09}}</ref><ref name=\"ox-gwwc-pledges\">{{cite news|title=1000 people match Oxford philosopher's '10% of future income' charity pledge|url=http://www.ox.ac.uk/news/2015-07-15-1000-people-match-oxford-philosopher%E2%80%99s-%E2%80%9810-future-income%E2%80%99-charity-pledge|accessdate= March 11, 2017|work=University of Oxford|date= July 15, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Founders Pledge]] is a similar initiative run by the nonprofit Founders Forum for Good where startup founders make a legally binding commitment to donate at least 2% of their personal proceeds to charity in the event that they sell their business.<ref name=\"founders-pledge-80k-interview\">{{cite web|last=MacAskill|first=William|authorlink=William MacAskill|title=One of the most exciting new effective altruist organisations: An interview with David Goldberg of the Founders Pledge|url=https://80000hours.org/2015/11/one-of-the-most-exciting-new-effective-altruist-organisations-an-interview-with-david-goldberg-of-the-founders-pledge/|website=80,000 Hours|accessdate= March 11, 2017|date=November 26, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"founders-pledge-forbes\">{{cite news|last1=Prosser|first1=David|title=Entrepreneurs Pledge Millions To Social Good|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/davidprosser/2015/06/10/entrepreneurs-pledge-millions-to-social-good/#3d2f84e66bb9|accessdate=11 March 2017|work=Forbes|date=10 June 2015}}</ref><ref name=techcrunch>{{cite news|url = https://techcrunch.com/2015/06/09/uk-tech-founders-take-the-founders-pledge-to-2-commiting-28m-to-good-causes/|title = UK Tech Founders Take The Founders Pledge To 2%, Committing $28m+ To Good Causes|last = Butcher|first = Mike|date = June 9, 2015|accessdate = December 5, 2015|work = [[TechCrunch]]}}</ref> By January 2019, three years after launch, more than 1400 entrepreneurs have pledged an estimated total value of $700 million based on the founders' equity and the companies' valuation and at least $91 million were raised.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fastcompany.com/90240242/why-nonprofits-should-be-courting-entrepreneurs-as-donors|title=Why nonprofits should be courting entrepreneurs as donors|last=Paynter|first=Ben|date=2018-09-25|website=Fast Company|language=en-US|access-date=2018-12-09}}</ref>\n\n===Career selection===\n\nEffective altruists argue that selection of one's career is an important determinant of the amount of good one does,<ref name=\"oliver\">{{cite web|last1=Oliver|first1=Huw|title='Effective altruists' are a new type of nice person|url=https://www.vice.com/en_uk/article/why-are-young-people-being-so-altruistic-209|website=[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]|accessdate= March 11, 2017|language=en-us}}</ref> both directly (through the services one provides to the world) and indirectly (through the ways one directs the money earned based on the career).<ref name=\"macaskill-replaceability-paper\" />\n\n[[80,000 Hours]] is an organisation in the effective altruism community that conducts research on which careers have the largest positive social impact and provides career advice based on that research.<ref name=\"career-choice-vox\" /><ref name=yc-techcrunch>{{cite news|url = https://techcrunch.com/2015/08/04/80000-hours/|title = Want To Make An Impact With Your Work? Try Some Advice From 80,000 Hours|date = August 4, 2015|accessdate = October 31, 2015|work = [[TechCrunch]]}}</ref> It considers indirect methods of altruistic employment, such as earning a high salary in a conventional career and donating a portion of it, as well as direct practices, such as scientific research. It was co-founded by [[William MacAskill]] and Benjamin Todd.<ref name=\"fastcoexist\">{{cite web|last1=Alcorn|first1=Stan|title=How To Choose An Ethical Career (With Help From Oxford Philosophers)|url=https://www.fastcoexist.com/1682193/how-to-choose-an-ethical-career-with-help-from-oxford-philosophers|website=Co.Exist|publisher=Fast Company Inc|accessdate= March 11, 2017|date= June 4, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://80000hours.org/about/meet-the-team/|title=Meet the team|website=80,000 Hours|language=en-US|access-date=2018-12-09}}</ref>\n\n[[Earning to give]] has been proposed as a possible strategy for effective altruists. This strategy involves choosing to work in high-paying careers with the explicit goal of donating large sums of money to charity.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://80000hours.org/articles/earning-to-give/|title=Why and how to earn to give|website=80,000 Hours|language=en-US|access-date=|first = Benjamin|last = Todd|date =April 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"join-ws-save-world\">{{cite news|last1=Matthews|first1=Dylan|title=Join Wall Street. Save the world.|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/wonk/wp/2013/05/31/join-wall-street-save-the-world/|accessdate= March 11, 2017|work= Washington Post}}</ref> MacAskill argues that it might even be worth earning to give in morally controversial careers, since the marginal impact of taking an unethical job is small if someone else would have taken it regardless, while the counterfactual impact of the donations would be large.<ref name=\"macaskill-replaceability-paper\">{{cite journal|last1=William|first1=MacAskill|title=Replaceability, Career Choice, and Making a Difference|journal=Ethical Theory and Moral Practice|volume=17|issue=2|pages=269\u2013283|date=2014|doi=10.1007/s10677-013-9433-4|url=https://www.academia.edu/1557895|language=en|issn=1386-2820}}</ref> However, 80,000 Hours have more recently argued that it is better to avoid careers that do significant direct harm, even if it seems like the negative consequences would be outweighed by donations. This is because there are often hidden harms in following unethical careers, and because they think it is important to take moral uncertainty into account.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://80000hours.org/articles/harmful-career/|title=Is it ever okay to take a harmful job in order to do more good? An in-depth analysis.|website=80,000 Hours|language=en-US|access-date= June 27, 2019|first = Benjamin|last = Todd|date =August 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[David Brooks (journalist)|David Brooks]], a columnist for ''[[The New York Times]]'', criticized earning to give. He wrote that most people who work in finance and other high-paying industries value money for selfish reasons and that being surrounded by these people will cause effective altruists to become less altruistic.<ref name=\"brooks2013\">{{cite web|last1=Brooks|first1=David | title=The Way to Produce a Person |newspaper=The New York Times|date=June 3, 2013| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/06/04/opinion/brooks-the-way-to-produce-a-person.html?_r=0|accessdate=July 7, 2015}}</ref> [[Peter Singer]] responded to these criticisms in his book ''The Most Good You Can Do'' by giving examples of people who have been earning to give for years without losing their altruistic motivation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://blog.yupnet.org/2016/08/09/earning-to-give-leads-to-happiness/|title='Earning to Give' Leads to Happiness|date=2016-08-09|website=Yale Press Log|access-date=2017-04-04}}</ref> In ''[[The Week]]'', Pascal-Emmanuel Gobry argued that the practice was \"unsettling\".<ref name=\"gobry\">{{cite magazine|url=https://theweek.com/articles/542955/effective-altruism-really-change-world|title = Can Effective Altruism really change the world?|last = Gobry|first = Pascal-Emmanuel|date = March 16, 2015|accessdate = March 21, 2015|magazine = [[The Week]]}}</ref>\n\n==Cause priorities==\n\nSince effective altruism aims for cause neutrality (see {{slink||Cause prioritization}} above),<ref name=\"cause-neutrality\" /> it is in principle open to helping in whichever causes (problems) allow people to do the most good, impartially considered.<ref name=practical-ethics/><ref name=\"kissel\" /> Such causes may include, for example, providing food for the [[hungry]], protecting [[endangered species]], mitigating [[climate change]], reforming [[immigration policy]], researching [[cure]]s for illnesses, preventing [[sexual violence]], [[Poverty alleviation|alleviating poverty]], eliminating [[factory farming]], or averting [[nuclear warfare]].<ref name=\"EA-IEE\"/> Many people in the effective altruist movement have prioritized global poverty, animal welfare, and risks to the survival and flourishing of humanity and its descendants over the long-term future.<ref name=vox>{{cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/2015/4/24/8457895/givewell-open-philanthropy-charity|title = You have $8 billion. You want to do as much good as possible. What do you do? Inside the Open Philanthropy Project |last=Matthews |first=Dylan |authorlink=Dylan Matthews |date=April 24, 2015 |accessdate=April 27, 2015 |website=[[Vox (website)|Vox]]}}</ref><ref name=skelton/><ref name=\"Problems\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://forum.effectivealtruism.org/posts/pfbLKnJmDKYSPPCEW/four-focus-areas-of-effective-altruism|title=Four focus areas of effective altruism \u2013 Effective Altruism Forum|last=Muehlhauser|first=Luke|date=July 8, 2013|website=forum.effectivealtruism.org|language=en|access-date=January 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Global poverty alleviation===\n\nGlobal [[poverty alleviation]] has been a focus of some of the earliest and most prominent organizations associated with effective altruism.\n\nCharity evaluator [[GiveWell]] was founded by [[Holden Karnofsky]] and Elie Hassenfeld in 2007 to address poverty and is part of the effective altruism community.<ref name=\"givewell-opt-in\">{{cite web|url=http://blog.givewell.org/2013/08/13/effective-altruism/|title=Effective Altruism|last=Karnofsky|first=Holden|date=August 13, 2013|publisher=[[GiveWell]]|accessdate=April 11, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Konduri|first1=Vimal|title=GiveWell Co-Founder Explains Effective Altruism Frameworks|url=http://www.thecrimson.com/article/2015/12/4/givewell-founder-effective-altruism/|website=The Harvard Crimson|publisher=The Harvard Crimson, Inc|accessdate= March 10, 2017|ref=crimson|language=en}}</ref> GiveWell has argued that the value of donations is greatest for international poverty alleviation and developing world health issues,<ref name=\"dollar-overseas\" /><ref name=\"bloomberg-givewell\">{{cite news|last1=Wolfe|first1=Alexandra|title=Hedge Fund Analytics for Nonprofits|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2011-11-23/hedge-fund-analytics-for-nonprofits|accessdate= March 11, 2017|work=Bloomberg.com|publisher=Bloomberg LP|date= November 24, 2011}}</ref> and its leading recommendations have been in these domains (including [[malaria]] prevention charities [[Against Malaria Foundation]] and [[Malaria Consortium]], deworming charities [[Schistosomiasis Control Initiative]] and [[Deworm the World Initiative]], and [[GiveDirectly]] for direct unconditional cash transfers).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.economist.com/news/international/21651815-lessons-business-charities-doing-good-doing-well|title=Doing good by doing well|website=The Economist|publisher=Hearst Communications, Inc|accessdate=10 March 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"huffpo-elie\">{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2015/03/26/elie-hassenfeld-givewell_n_6927320.html|title=That Time A Hedge Funder Quit His Job And Then Raised $60 Million For Charity|last=Pitney|first=Nico|date=March 26, 2015|work=[[Huffington Post]]|accessdate=April 27, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe effective altruism organization The Life You Can Save, which originated from Singer's book by the same name,<ref name=\"Singer2009\">{{cite book |last=Singer |first=Peter |authorlink=Peter Singer |date=2009 |title=[[The Life You Can Save|The Life You Can Save: Acting Now to End World Poverty]] |location=New York |publisher=Random House |isbn=9781400067107 |oclc=232980306 |ref=harv}}</ref> also works to alleviate global poverty by promoting evidence-backed charities, conducting philanthropy education and changing the culture of giving in affluent countries.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/how-to-do-good-a-conversation-with-the-worlds-leading_us_58cb8dcee4b0537abd956f91|title=How To Do Good: A Conversation With The World's Leading Ethicist|last=Zhang|first=Linch|date=March 17, 2017|website=Huffington Post|language=en-US|access-date=June 1, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thelifeyoucansave.org/about-us|title=About The Life You Can Save non-profit organization|website=www.thelifeyoucansave.org|access-date=2019-01-12}}</ref>\n\nWhile much of the initial focus of effective altruism was on direct strategies such as health interventions and cash transfers, there has also been interest in more systematic social, economic, and political reform that would facilitate larger long-term poverty reduction.<ref name=\"scott-weathers\">{{cite web|last1=Weathers|first1=Scott|title=Can 'effective altruism' change the world? It already has.|url=https://www.opendemocracy.net/transformation/scott-weathers/can-effective-altruism-change-world-it-already-has|website=Transformation|accessdate=11 March 2017|language=en|date=29 February 2016}}</ref> In 2011, GiveWell announced GiveWell Labs, which was later renamed as the [[Open Philanthropy Project]], for research and philanthropic funding of more speculative and diverse causes such as policy reform, global catastrophic risk reduction and scientific research.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.openphilanthropy.org/focus|title=Focus Areas {{!}} Open Philanthropy Project|website=www.openphilanthropy.org|access-date=2019-01-12}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.givewell.org/2011/09/08/announcing-givewell-labs/|title=Announcing GiveWell Labs|last=Karnofsky|first=Holden|date=September 8, 2011|website=|publisher=[[GiveWell]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=April 11, 2015}}</ref> It is a collaboration between GiveWell and [[Good Ventures]], a philanthropic foundation founded by [[Facebook]] co-founder [[Dustin Moskovitz]] and his wife Cari Tuna.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.openphilanthropy.org/about/who-we-are|title=Who We Are {{!}} Open Philanthropy Project|website=www.openphilanthropy.org|access-date=2019-01-12}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.givewell.org/2014/08/20/open-philanthropy-project-formerly-givewell-labs/|title=Open Philanthropy Project (formerly GiveWell Labs)|last=Karnofsky|first=Holden|date=August 20, 2014|website=|publisher=[[GiveWell]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=April 11, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Moses\">{{cite news|last1=Moses|first1=Sue-Lynn|title=Leverage: Why This Silicon Valley Funder Is Doubling Down on a Beltway Think Tank|url=https://www.insidephilanthropy.com/home/2016/3/9/leverage-why-this-silicon-valley-funder-is-doubling-down-on.html|accessdate=11 March 2017|work=Inside Philanthropy|date=9 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Animal welfare===\n{{See also|Veganism}}\nSome effective altruists believe that reducing [[animal suffering]] should be a major priority and that, at the current margin, there are cost-effective ways of accomplishing this.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.effectivealtruism.org/articles/cause-profile-animal-welfare/|title=Cause Profile: Animal Welfare|last=Whittlestone|first=Jess|date=November 16, 2017|website=Effective Altruism|access-date=2019-01-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/davidebanis/2018/11/27/new-book-draws-detailed-roadmap-of-how-we-can-end-animal-farming/|title=New Book Draws Detailed Roadmap Of How We Can End Animal Farming |last=Banis|first=Davide|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2019-01-12}}</ref> Singer quotes estimates by the [[Food and Agriculture Organization]] of the [[United Nations]] and the British organization Fishcount according to which 60 billion land animals are [[Animal slaughter|slaughtered]] and between 1 and 2.7 trillion individual fish are killed each year for human consumption.<ref>{{Cite news|url= https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/cif-green/2010/sep/14/fish-forgotten-victims |title=Fish: the forgotten victims on our plate|date=2010-09-14|work=The Guardian|access-date=June 14, 2017|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url= http://www.fao.org/fileadmin/user_upload/animalwelfare/GlobalWarningExecutiveSummary1.pdf|title=Global Warming Climate Change and Farm Animal Welfare|last=|first=|publisher=Compassion in World Farming|year=2008|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url= http://www.fishcount.org.uk/published/standard/fishcountfullrptSR.pdf|title=Worse things happen at sea: the welfare of wild-caught fish|last=Mood|first=Alison|publisher=fishcount.org.uk|year=2010|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> He argues that effective animal welfare altruists should prioritize [[Intensive animal farming|factory farming]] over more overfunded popular causes such as pet welfare.<ref name=\"kristof\" /><ref name = whyfarmedanimals/> Singer also argues that, if farm animals such as chickens are assigned even a modicum of [[consciousness]], efforts to reduce factory farming (for example, by reducing global [[meat]] consumption) could be an even more underfunded and cost-effective way of reducing current global suffering than human [[poverty]] reduction.<ref name=\"Singer2015\"/>{{rp|138, 146\u2013147}} Philosophically, [[wild animal suffering]] may be an additional moral concern for effective altruists.<ref>{{cite web|title=\"Effective Altruism for Animals\" Panel, Animal Studies|url=http://animalstudies.as.nyu.edu/object/as.events.20150729|website=New York University Animal Studies Initiative |publisher=NYU|accessdate=11 March 2017}}</ref> In 2018, the book ''[[The End of Animal Farming]]'' by [[Jacy Reese]] discussed animal welfare issues from an effective altruism perspective, with a specific focus on the potential for [[cultured meat]] to address farm animal suffering and the importance of expanding the moral circle to help people care more about future beings, wild animals, invertebrates, and artificial sentience.<ref>{{cite book|title=The End of Animal Farming|publisher=[[Beacon Press]]|isbn=978-0807019450|year=2018}}</ref>\n\n'''Animal Charity Evaluators'''<!--boldface per [[WP:R#PLA]]--> (ACE) is an effective altruism organization that evaluates and compares various animal charities based on their cost-effectiveness and transparency, particularly those that are tackling factory farming.<ref name=\"animal-welfare-vox\" /><ref name=\"auto\">Daniel Engber, [http://www.slate.com/articles/health_and_science/science/2016/08/animal_activists_crunched_the_numbers_to_learn_that_the_creature_most_in.html \"Save the Chicken\"], ''Slate'', August 18, 2016.</ref><ref name=\"Singer2015\"/>{{rp|139}} [[Faunalytics]] (formerly the Humane Research Council) is an organization loosely affiliated with the effective altruism community that conducts independent research on important animal welfare topics, provides resources for advocates and donors, and works with animal protection organizations to evaluate their work.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/future-perfect/2018/10/31/18026418/vegan-vegetarian-animal-welfare-corporate-advocacy|title=Vegan diets are hard to sell. Animal activists might do better focused on corporate decisions, not people's plates.|last=Piper|first=Kelsey|date=2018-10-31|website=Vox|access-date=2019-01-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://faunalytics.org/about/|title=What We Do|website=Faunalytics|language=en-US|access-date=2019-01-12}}</ref> The [[Sentience Institute]] is a new effective altruism [[think tank]] founded in 2017 to address the expansion of the moral circle.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=5 August 2019 |title=Introducing Sentience Institute |url=https://www.sentienceinstitute.org/blog/introducing-sentience-institute |last1=Witwicki |first1=Kelly |last2=Reese |first2=Jacy|publisher=Sentience Institute}}</ref>\n\n===Long-term future and global catastrophic risks===\nFocusing on the long-term future, some effective altruists believe that the total value of any meaningful metric (wealth, potential for suffering, potential for happiness, etc.) summed up over future generations, far exceeds the value for people living today.<ref name=vox/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://80000hours.org/articles/future-generations/|title=If you want to do good, here's why future generations should be your focus|last=Todd|first=Benjamin|date=October 24, 2017|website=80,000 Hours|language=en-US|access-date=2019-01-12}}</ref><ref name=\"eaf-far-future\">{{cite web|title=The Importance of the Far Future|url=https://ea-foundation.org/blog/the-importance-of-the-far-future/|website=Effective Altruism Foundation|publisher=Effective Altruism Foundation|accessdate= March 11, 2017|date= August 5, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bostrom|first=Nick|date=2003|title=Astronomical Waste: The Opportunity Cost of Delayed Technological Development|url=http://www.nickbostrom.com/astronomical/waste.pdf|journal=Utilitas|volume=15|issue=3|pages=308\u2013314|via=|doi=10.1017/S0953820800004076}}</ref> Some researchers have found it psychologically difficult to contemplate the trade-off; Toby Ord has stated that \"Since there is so much work to be done to fix the needless suffering in our present, I was slow to turn to the future.\"<ref name=Precipice/>{{rp|8}} Reasons Ord gave for working on long-term issues include a belief that preventing long-term suffering is \"even more neglected\" than causes related to current suffering, and that the residents of the future are even more powerless to affect risks caused by current events than are current dispossessed populations.<ref name=Precipice>{{cite book |last=Ord |first=Toby |authorlink=Toby Ord |chapter=Introduction |title=[[The Precipice: Existential Risk and the Future of Humanity]] | date=2020 |location=London |publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing |isbn=9781526600196 |oclc=1143365836 |chapterurl=https://cdn.80000hours.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/The-Precipice-Introduction-Chapter-1.pdf}}</ref>{{rp|8}}\n\nPhilosophically, attempts to reduce the suffering of future populations (given they exist) depend on attitudes toward [[Social discount rate#\"Pure time preference\" debates|pure time discounting]], and initiatives focused on preventing human extinction (as opposed to preventing other dystopian futures) additionally depend on attitudes toward [[population ethics]] in order to compare with scenarios where future populations do not exist.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bostrom |first1=Nick |authorlink1=Nick Bostrom |title=Existential risk prevention as global priority |work=[[Global Policy]] |date=February 2013 |pages=15\u201331 |doi=10.1111/1758-5899.12002}}</ref> Peter Singer has argued that existential risk should not be \"the dominant public face of the effective altruism movement\" as doing so would drastically limit the movement's reach.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Klein |first1=Ezra |title=Peter Singer on the lives you can save |url=https://www.vox.com/future-perfect/2019/12/6/20992100/peter-singer-effective-altruism-lives-you-can-save-animal-liberation |accessdate=6 April 2020 |work=Vox |date=6 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn particular, the importance of addressing [[existential risk]]s such as dangers associated with [[biotechnology]] and [[Existential risk from advanced artificial intelligence|advanced artificial intelligence]] is often highlighted and the subject of active research.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://80000hours.org/articles/extinction-risk/|title=Why despite global progress, humanity is probably facing its most dangerous time ever|last=Todd|first=Benjamin|date=2017|website=80,000 Hours|language=en-US|access-date=2019-01-12}}</ref> Because it is often infeasible to use empirical science (such as randomized control trials) to measure the probability of an existential risk, researchers such as [[Nick Bostrom]] have used other methods such as expert opinion elicitation to estimate their importance.<ref name=\"xrisk methods\">{{cite journal |last1=Rowe |first1=Thomas |last2=Beard |first2=Simon |title=Probabilities, methodologies and the evidence base in existential risk assessments |journal=Working Paper, Centre for the Study of Existential Risk |date=2018 |url=http://eprints.lse.ac.uk/89506/1/Beard_Existential-Risk-Assessments_Accepted.pdf |accessdate=26 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nSome organizations that work actively on research and advocacy for improving the long term future, and have connections with the effective altruism community, are the [[Future of Humanity Institute]] at the University of Oxford, the [[Centre for the Study of Existential Risk]] at the University of Cambridge, and the [[Future of Life Institute]].<ref name=\"guan-op-ed\">{{cite news|last1=Guan|first1=Melody|title=The New Social Movement of our Generation: Effective Altruism|url=http://harvardpolitics.com/harvard/new-social-movement-generation-effective-altruism/|accessdate=11 March 2017|work=Harvard Political Review|date=19 April 2015}}</ref> In addition, the [[Machine Intelligence Research Institute]] is focused on the more narrow mission of [[Existential risk from artificial general intelligence#Mitigation|aligning advanced artificial intelligence]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/future-perfect/2018/12/21/18126576/ai-artificial-intelligence-machine-learning-safety-alignment|title=The case for taking AI seriously as a threat to humanity|last=Piper|first=Kelsey|date=2018-12-21|website=Vox|access-date=2019-01-12}}</ref><ref name=\"washpost-ai\">{{cite news|last1=Basulto|first1=Dominic|title=The very best ideas for preventing artificial intelligence from wrecking the planet|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/innovations/wp/2015/07/07/the-very-best-ideas-for-preventing-artificial-intelligence-from-wrecking-the-planet/|accessdate= March 11, 2017|work=Washington Post|date=July 7, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==History of the social movement==\n\nThe movement that came to identify with the name ''effective altruism'' was created in the late 2000s as a community formed around [[Giving What We Can]], founded in 2009 by philosopher Toby Ord with help from philosopher William MacAskill, who also co-founded [[80,000 Hours]] in 2011.<ref name=\"EA-history\">{{cite web|last=MacAskill|first=William|authorlink=William MacAskill|date=March 10, 2014|title=The history of the term 'effective altruism'|url=https://forum.effectivealtruism.org/posts/9a7xMXoSiQs3EYPA2/the-history-of-the-term-effective-altruism|website=forum.effectivealtruism.org|accessdate=February 2, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Singer2015\"/>{{rp|16\u201319}} Those two groups, while planning to incorporate as a charity under a new [[umbrella organization]], held a vote in late 2011 to choose a name for the new organization; the name \"Centre for Effective Altruism\" won.<ref name=ft>{{cite news|last1=Ram|first1=Aliya|title=The power and efficacy of effective altruism|url=https://www.ft.com/content/1954323c-8eb3-11e5-8be4-3506bf20cc2b|accessdate=February 14, 2018|work=Financial Times|date=December 4, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"EA-history\"/><ref name=\"Singer2015\"/>{{rp|18}} Ruair\u00ed Donnelly set up the \"Effective Altruists\" [[Facebook group]] in November 2012, and the movement gained wider exposure with Peter Singer's [[TED talk]] \"The Why and How of Effective Altruism\" in May 2013.<ref name=\"EA-history\"/> Other contributions to the social movement were the writings of philosophers such as Singer on [[applied ethics]] and Bostrom on reducing the risk of [[human extinction]], the founding of organizations such as [[GiveWell]] and [[The Life You Can Save]], and the creation of internet forums such as [[LessWrong]].<ref name=\"Utilitarianism2017\">{{cite book|last1=de Lazari-Radek|first1=Katarzyna|last2=Singer|first2=Peter|chapter=Effective altruism|title=Utilitarianism: A Very Short Introduction|date=September 27, 2017|series=Very short introductions|volume=530|location=Oxford; New York|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780198728795|oclc=965456936|doi=10.1093/actrade/9780198728795.003.0001|pages=108\u2013112}}</ref>{{rp|110}}<ref name=\"Lessons of EA\">{{cite web |last1=Rubenstein |first1=Jennifer |title=The Lessons of Effective Altruism |url=https://www.ethicsandinternationalaffairs.org/2016/the-lessons-of-effective-altruism/ |website=Ethics & International Affairs |accessdate=26 August 2018 |date=14 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nEffective altruism conferences (called [[Effective Altruism Global]]) have been held since 2013.<ref name=\"huffpost-ea-global\">{{cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/elon-musk-google-effective-altruism_us_55a56626e4b04740a3de3130|title=Elon Musk To Address 'Nerd Altruists' At Google HQ|last1=Pitney|first1=Nico|date=July 16, 2015|website=Huffington Post|accessdate=March 11, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.exponentialtimes.net/videos/jaan-tallinns-keynote-effective-altruism-summit-2013|title = Jaan Tallinn's Keynote - Effective Altruism Summit 2013 |date = November 13, 2013|accessdate = April 11, 2015|work= Exponential Times}}</ref> In 2015, Peter Singer published ''[[The Most Good You Can Do]]'', a book on effective altruism. The book describes the philosophy and social movement of effective altruism and argues in favor of it.<ref name=\"kristof\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/04/05/opinion/sunday/nicholas-kristof-the-trader-who-donates-half-his-pay.html|title = The Trader Who Donates Half His Pay|last = Kristof|first = Nicholas|authorlink = Nicholas Kristof|date = April 4, 2015|accessdate = April 11, 2015|newspaper = [[New York Times]]}}</ref> In the same year William MacAskill published his book ''[[Doing Good Better|Doing Good Better: How Effective Altruism Can Help You Make a Difference]]'' which helped to further popularize the movement.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2015/aug/20/doing-good-better-william-macaskill-review|title=Doing Good Better by William MacAskill review \u2013 if you read this book, you'll change the charities you donate to|last=Shariatmadari|first=David|date=August 20, 2015|work=The Guardian|access-date=May 21, 2017|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/08/16/upshot/effective-altruism-where-charity-and-rationality-meet.html|title=Effective Altruism: Where Charity and Rationality Meet|last=Cowen|first=Tyler|date=August 14, 2015|work=The New York Times|access-date=May 21, 2017|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref name=\"The Atlantic article The Greatest Good\" />\n\nIn 2018, American news website ''[[Vox (website)|Vox]]'' launched its ''Future Perfect'' section, led by journalist [[Dylan Matthews]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Schmidt |first=Christine |date=October 15, 2018 |title=Will Vox's new section on effective altruism... well, do any good? |url=https://www.niemanlab.org/2018/10/will-voxs-new-section-on-effective-altruism-well-do-any-good/ |website=[[Nieman Journalism Lab]] |accessdate=February 1, 2020}}</ref> ''Future Perfect'' has published written pieces and podcasts that cover effective altruism ideas on the mission of \"Finding the best ways to do good\",<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/future-perfect/2018/10/15/17924288/future-perfect-explained|title=Future Perfect, explained|last=Matthews|first=Dylan|date=October 15, 2018|website=Vox|access-date=December 8, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/future-perfect|title=Future Perfect|website=www.vox.com|access-date=February 1, 2020}}</ref> including topics such as effective philanthropy,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/2015/12/1/9826838/best-charities-donate-2018-giving-tuesday|title=These are the charities where your money will do the most good|last=Matthews|first=Dylan|date=December 17, 2019|website=Vox|access-date=February 1, 2020}}</ref> high-impact career choice,<ref name=\"career-choice-vox\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/future-perfect/2018/11/28/18114601/future-perfect-podcast-career-choice|title=How to pick a career that counts|last=Matthews|first=Dylan|date=November 28, 2018|website=Vox|access-date=December 8, 2018}}</ref> poverty reduction through [[women's empowerment]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/2018/11/5/18037688/gender-equality-poverty-human-rights|title=Want less poverty in the world? Empower women.|last=Illing|first=Sean|date=March 8, 2019|website=Vox|access-date=February 1, 2020}}</ref> improving children's learning efficiently through improving [[environmental health]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/2020/1/8/21051869/indoor-air-pollution-student-achievement|title=Installing air filters in classrooms has surprisingly large educational benefits: $1,000 can raise a class's test scores by as much as cutting class size by a third|last=Yglesias|first=Matthew|date=January 8, 2020|website=Vox|access-date=February 1, 2020}}</ref> animal welfare improvements,<ref name=\"animal-welfare-vox\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/2018/11/27/18111908/giving-tuesday-best-animal-charity|title=Where will your donations do the most for animals?|last=Piper|first=Kelsey|date=November 27, 2018|website=Vox|access-date=December 8, 2018}}</ref> and ways to reduce global catastrophic risks.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vox.com/future-perfect/2018/11/19/18097663/nick-bostrom-vulnerable-world-global-catastrophic-risks|title=How technological progress is making it likelier than ever that humans will destroy ourselves|last=Piper|first=Kelsey|date=November 19, 2018|work=Vox|access-date=December 9, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Key figures==\nKey figures in the effective altruism movement have included:\n* Princeton University philosopher [[Peter Singer]]<ref name=\"blog.ted.com\">{{cite web|last1=Walters|first1=Helen|title=The why and how of effective altruism: Peter Singer's talk visualized|url=http://blog.ted.com/why-how-effective-altruism-peter-singer-visualized/|website=TED Blog}}</ref>\n* Oxford University philosopher [[Derek Parfit]]<ref>{{cite news | last = Matthews | first = Derek | title = The whole philosophy community is mourning Derek Parfit. Here's why he mattered. | newspaper = Vox | date = January 3, 2017 | url = https://www.vox.com/science-and-health/2017/1/3/14148208/derek-parfit-rip-obit}}</ref>\n* Facebook cofounder [[Dustin Moskovitz]]<ref name=\"Washington Post on Dustin Moskovitz and Cari Tuna\">{{cite news | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/billionaire-couple-give-plenty-to-charity-but-they-do-quite-a-bit-of-homework/2014/12/26/19fae34c-86d6-11e4-b9b7-b8632ae73d25_story.html | title=Cari Tuna and Dustin Moskovitz: Young Silicon Valley billionaires pioneer new approach to philanthropy | date=December 26, 2014 | agency=The Washington Post}}</ref>\n* Future of Humanity Institute director [[Nick Bostrom]]<ref name=\"Utilitarianism2017\"/>{{rp|110}}\n* Global Priorities Institute director [[Hilary Greaves]]<ref>{{cite web | title = Global Priorities Institute opens at Oxford | date = April 5, 2018 | url = https://www.development.ox.ac.uk/news/new-global-priorities-institute-opens | access-date = 1 December 2019}}</ref>\n* Oxford University philosopher [[William MacAskill]]<ref name=\"The Atlantic article The Greatest Good\">{{cite news|last1=Thompson|first1=Derek|title=The Greatest Good|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/business/archive/2015/06/what-is-the-greatest-good/395768/#b06g25t20w15|work=The Atlantic|date=June 15, 2015}}</ref>\n* Future of Humanity Institute researcher [[Toby Ord]]<ref name=\"Peter Singer The Most Good You Can Do\">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NBWWX4ViD3E/|website=YouTube|title=Peter Singer: \"The Most Good You Can Do\" &#124; Talks at Google}}</ref>\n* Professional poker player [[Liv Boeree]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pokerstrategy.com/news/world-of-poker/Liv-Boeree-on-Effective-Altruism_100487/|title=News: Liv Boeree on Effective Altruism|website=www.pokerstrategy.com|access-date=April 11, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.livboeree.com/effective-altruism/|title=Effective Altruism {{!}} Liv Boeree|website=www.livboeree.com|language=en-GB|access-date=April 11, 2017}}</ref>\n* Artificial intelligence researcher [[Eliezer Yudkowsky]]{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n* GiveWell co-founder and Open Philanthropy Project CEO [[Holden Karnofsky]]<ref name=\"Lessons of EA\">{{cite web |last1=Rubenstein |first1=Jennifer |title=The Lessons of Effective Altruism |url=https://www.ethicsandinternationalaffairs.org/2016/the-lessons-of-effective-altruism/ |website=Ethics & International Affairs |accessdate=26 August 2018 |date=14 December 2016}}</ref>\n* Nanyang Technological University economist [[Yew-Kwang Ng]]<ref>{{cite web | last = Wiblin | first = Robert | title = Prof Yew-Kwang Ng is a visionary economist who anticipated many key ideas in effective altruism decades ago. Here's his take on ethics and how to create a much happier world. | website = 80,000 Hours | date = July 26, 2018| url = https://80000hours.org/podcast/episodes/yew-kwang-ng-anticipating-effective-altruism/ | access-date = 1 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Criticism==\n\n===Claims that comparisons within and across cause areas are illegitimate===\nIn the ''[[Stanford Social Innovation Review]]'', Ken Berger and Robert Penna of [[Charity Navigator]] condemned effective altruism's practice of \"weighing causes and beneficiaries against one another\", calling this \"moralistic, in the worst sense of the word\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ssireview.org/blog/entry/the_elitist_philanthropy_of_so_called_effective_altruism|title=The Elitist Philanthropy of So-Called Effective Altruism|last=Berger|first=Ken|last2=Penna|first2=Robert|date=November 25, 2013|website=|publisher=[[Stanford Social Innovation Review]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=November 26, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Bias toward measurable interventions===\nPascal-Emmanuel Gobry warns about the \"measurement problem\", stating that some areas, such as medical research, or helping to reform third-world governance \"one grinding step at a time\", are hard to measure with controlled cost-effectiveness experiments and therefore risk being undervalued by the effective altruism movement.<ref name=\"gobry\" /> Jennifer Rubenstein also hypothesizes that effective altruism can be biased against causes that are not straightforward to measure.<ref name=\"Lessons of EA\" />\n\n===Perceived neglect of radical economic change===\nIn ''[[Jacobin (magazine)|Jacobin]]'' magazine, Mathew Snow argued that effective altruism \"implores individuals to use their money to procure necessities for those who desperately need them, but says nothing about the system that determines how those necessities are produced and distributed in the first place\".<ref name=\"Jacobin\">{{cite web|url=https://www.jacobinmag.com/2015/08/peter-singer-charity-effective-altruism/|title=Against Charity|last=Snow|first=Mathew|date=August 25, 2015|website=|publisher=[[Jacobin (magazine)|Jacobin]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150828121204/https://www.jacobinmag.com/2015/08/peter-singer-charity-effective-altruism/|archive-date=August 28, 2015|accessdate=September 5, 2016|ref=harv}}</ref> Various critics have similarly objected to effective altruism on the basis of the fact that its proponents tend not to support political causes such as [[anti-capitalism]] that change \"the existing global institutional order\".<ref name=\"Berkey\" /> Joshua Kissel has replied that anti-capitalism is compatible with effective altruism in theory, while adding that effective altruists and anti-capitalists have reason to be more sympathetic to each other.<ref name=\"kissel\">{{cite web|url=http://commons.pacificu.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1573&context=eip/|title=Effective Altruism and Anti-Capitalism: An Attempt at Reconciliation|last=Kissel|first=Joshua|date=January 31, 2017|website=|publisher=Essays in Philosophy|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=February 19, 2017}}</ref> Brian Berkey has also argued that support for changing institutions such as capitalism does not contradict the principles of effective altruism, because effective altruism is open to any action that will have the greatest positive impact on the world, including the possibility of changing the existing global institutional order.<ref name=Berkey>{{cite journal |last1=Berkey |first1=Brian |title=The Institutional Critique of Effective Altruism |journal=Utilitas |date=2018 |volume=30 |issue=2 |url=https://faculty.wharton.upenn.edu/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/The-Institutional-Critique-of-Effective-Altruism.pdf |accessdate=26 August 2018}}</ref> Elizabeth Ashford argues that we are separately obligated to donate to effective aid charities and to reform the structures that are responsible for poverty.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Ashford |first1=Elizabeth |title=Severe Poverty as an Unjust Emergency |journal=The Ethics of Giving: Philosophers' Perspectives on Philanthropy |date=2018 |pages=103\u2013148 |doi=10.1093/oso/9780190648879.001.0001 |isbn=9780190648879 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Div col}}\n*[[Appropriate technology]]\n*[[Charity (practice)]]\n*[[Charity evaluator]]\n*[[Prosocial behavior]]\n*[[Speciesism]]\n*[[Structural fix]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n== Notes and references ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite journal |last1=Earle |first1=Samantha |last2=Read |first2=Rupert |date=March 2016 |title=Effective altruism: Is it effective? Should it be more affective? |journal=[[The Philosophers' Magazine]] |issue=73 |pages=84\u201391 |doi=10.5840/tpm20167378 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Gabriel |first=Iason |date=August 2016 |title=Effective altruism and its critics |journal=[[Journal of Applied Philosophy]] |volume=34 |issue=4 |pages=457\u2013473 |doi=10.1111/japp.12176 |url=https://www.academia.edu/13786913 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |editor1-last=Greaves |editor1-first=Hilary |editor1-link=Hilary Greaves |editor2-last=Pummer |editor2-first=Theron |date=2019 |title=Effective Altruism: Philosophical Issues |series=Engaging philosophy |location=Oxford; New York |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |isbn=9780198841364 |oclc=1101772304 |doi=10.1093/oso/9780198841364.001.0001 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Lechterman |first=Theodore M. |date=June 2019 |title=Being good in a world of uncertainty: a reply to Temkin |journal=Journal of Practical Ethics |volume=7 |issue=1 |pages=33\u201339 |url=http://philarchive.org/archive/LECBGIv1 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Lechterman |first=Theodore M. |date=January 2020 |title=The effective altruist's political problem |journal=Polity |volume=52 |issue=1 |pages=88\u2013115 |doi=10.1086/706867 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |last=MacAskill |first=William |authorlink=William MacAskill |date=June 2019 |title=Aid scepticism and effective altruism |journal=Journal of Practical Ethics |volume=7 |issue=1 |pages=49\u201360 |url=http://philarchive.org/archive/MACASA-4v1 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |last=McMahan |first=Jeff |authorlink=Jeff McMahan (philosopher) |date=March 2016 |title=Philosophical critiques of effective altruism |journal=[[The Philosophers' Magazine]] |issue=73 |pages=92\u201399 |doi=10.5840/tpm20167379 |url=http://jeffersonmcmahan.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/11/Philosophical-Critiques-of-Effective-Altruism-refs-in-text.pdf |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite web |last1=Singer |first1=Peter |authorlink1=Peter Singer |last2=Saunders-Hastings |first2=Emma |last3=Deaton |first3=Angus |authorlink3=Angus Deaton |last4=Gabriel |first4=Iason |last5=Janah |first5=Leila |authorlink5=Leila Janah |last6=Acemoglu |first6=Daron |authorlink6=Daron Acemoglu |last7=Brest |first7=Paul |authorlink7=Paul Brest |last8=MacFarquhar |first8=Larissa |authorlink8=Larissa MacFarquhar |last9=Tumber |first9=Catherine |last10=Reich |first10=Rob |authorlink10=Rob Reich |title=Forum: The logic of effective altruism |url=https://bostonreview.net/forum/peter-singer-logic-effective-altruism |website=[[Boston Review]] |date=July 1, 2015 |accessdate=February 5, 2020}} An article based on the preface and first chapter of Singer's book ''[[The Most Good You Can Do]]'' was published in the ''Boston Review'' on July 1, 2015 with a forum of responses by other writers and a final response by Singer.\n* {{cite journal |last=Temkin |first=Larry S. |authorlink=Larry Temkin |date=June 2019 |title=Being good in a world of need: some empirical worries and an uncomfortable philosophical possibility |journal=Journal of Practical Ethics |volume=7 |issue=1 |pages=1\u201323 |url=http://philarchive.org/archive/TEMBGI |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Zuolo |first=Federico |date=July 2019 |title=Beyond moral efficiency: effective altruism and theorizing about effectiveness |journal=[[Utilitas]] |pages=1\u201314 |doi=10.1017/S0953820819000281 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/333618104 |ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote|Effective altruism}}\n\n*[https://www.effectivealtruism.org/ Effective Altruism]\n*[https://www.centreforeffectivealtruism.org/ Centre for Effective Altruism]\n*[https://80000hours.org/ 80,000 Hours]\n\n{{Effective altruism|state=expanded}}\n{{Charity}}\n{{Evidence-based practice|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Effective Altruism}}\n[[Category:Altruism]]\n[[Category:Career development]]\n[[Category:Charity]]\n[[Category:Consequentialism]]\n[[Category:Donation]]\n[[Category:Ethical principles]]\n[[Category:Ethical theories]]\n[[Category:Ethics]]\n[[Category:Evidence]]\n[[Category:Evidence-based practices]]\n[[Category:Giving]]\n[[Category:Morality]]\n[[Category:Philanthropy]]\n[[Category:Philosophical concepts]]\n[[Category:Philosophical movements]]\n[[Category:Philosophical theories]]\n[[Category:Philosophy of life]]\n[[Category:Social change]]\n[[Category:Social movements]]\n[[Category:Social philosophy]]\n[[Category:Utilitarianism]]\n[[Category:Virtue]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Philosophy and social movement that applies evidence and reason to determine the most effective ways to benefit others}}\n[[File:London Thinks - Prof Peter Singer - What's the most good you can do.webm|thumb|Professor [[Peter Singer]] lectures on 'What's [[The Most Good You Can Do|the most good you can do]]?' at [[Conway Hall]] in 2015.]]\n'''Effective altruism''' is a [[philosophy]] and [[social movement]] that advocates using [[Scientific evidence|evidence]] and [[reasoning]] to determine the most effective ways to benefit others.<ref name=\"MacAskill-intro\">{{cite journal|last=MacAskill|first=William|authorlink=William MacAskill|title=Effective altruism: introduction|journal=Essays in Philosophy|date=January 2017|volume=18|issue=1|page=eP1580:1\u20135|doi=10.7710/1526-0569.1580|language=en|issn=1526-0569|url=https://commons.pacificu.edu/eip/vol18/iss1/1|ref=harv}}</ref>{{rp|2}}<ref name=\"Singer2015\">{{cite book |last=Singer |first=Peter |authorlink=Peter Singer |date=2015 |title=[[The Most Good You Can Do|The Most Good You Can Do: How Effective Altruism Is Changing Ideas About Living Ethically]] |series=Castle lectures in ethics, politics, and economics |location=New Haven |publisher=[[Yale University Press]] |isbn=9780300180275 |oclc=890614537 |ref=harv}}</ref>{{rp|4\u20137}} ''[[Altruism]]'' refers to improving the lives of others\u2014as opposed to [[egoism]], which emphasizes only self-interest.<ref name=\"Singer2015\"/>{{rp|4\u20135}}<ref name=\"doing-good-better\">{{cite book |last=MacAskill |first=William |authorlink=William MacAskill |title=[[Doing Good Better|Doing Good Better: How Effective Altruism Can Help You Help Others, Do Work that Matters, and Make Smarter Choices about Giving Back]] |date=2016 |origyear=2015 |location=New York |publisher=Avery |isbn=9781592409662 |oclc=932001639 |ref=harv}}</ref>{{rp|12}} ''[[Effectiveness]]'' refers to doing the ''most'' good with whatever resources are available\u2014as opposed to only doing ''some'' amount of good\u2014as well as determining what is the most good by using evidence and reasoning\u2014as opposed to only doing what [[Emotion|feels]] good or appears intuitively appealing.<ref name=\"Singer2015\"/>{{rp|6\u20137}}<ref name=\"doing-good-better\"/>{{rp|12}}\n\nMany people who espouse effective altruism call themselves ''effective altruists''.<ref>For example, a public [[Facebook group]] for effective altruists with the group ID \"effective.altruists\" had around 17,900 members on January 31, 2020: {{cite web |title=Effective Altruism |website=facebook.com |url=https://www.facebook.com/groups/effective.altruists/about/ |archiveurl=https://archive.is/l9CAN |archivedate=January 31, 2020 |accessdate=January 31, 2020}} At the same time, another social networking website listed over 200 local groups for effective altruists from around the world, the majority of them located in Europe and North America: {{cite web |title=EA Hub Groups |website=eahub.org |url=https://eahub.org/groups/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200201150010/https://eahub.org/groups/ |archivedate=February 1, 2020 |accessdate=February 1, 2020}} The term ''effective altruists'' is also used in many published sources such as {{harvtxt|Singer|2015}} and {{harvtxt|MacAskill|2017}}.</ref> While many effective altruists have focused on the [[nonprofit sector]], the philosophy of effective altruism applies more broadly to prioritizing the scientific projects, companies, and policy initiatives which can be estimated to save lives, help people, or otherwise have the biggest benefit.<ref name=\"doing-good-better\"/>{{rp|179\u2013195}}\n\n==Philosophy==\n[[File:Peter Singer MIT Veritas.jpg|thumb|[[Peter Singer]] is one of several philosophers who helped popularize effective altruism.]]\nPhilosophers played an important role in creating effective altruism (see {{slink||History of the social movement}} below), and much of the published literature about effective altruism poses philosophical questions about why and how to use evidence and reasoning to determine the most effective ways to benefit others, and then tries to figure out the most plausible answers to those questions, so that people can take action on the basis of those answers.<ref name=\"EA-IEE\">{{cite encyclopedia |last1=Pummer |first1=Theron |last2=MacAskill |first2=William |authorlink2=William MacAskill |date=2019 |title=Effective altruism |editor-last=LaFollette |editor-first=Hugh |encyclopedia=International Encyclopedia of Ethics |location=Hoboken, NJ |publisher=[[John Wiley & Sons]] |isbn=9781444367072 |oclc=829259960 |doi=10.1002/9781444367072 |url=https://philarchive.org/archive/PUMEA |ref=harv}}</ref><ref name=\"MacAskill-definition\">{{cite book |last=MacAskill |first=William |authorlink=William MacAskill |chapter=The definition of effective altruism |date=2019 |editor1-last=Greaves |editor1-first=Hilary |editor1-link=Hilary Greaves |editor2-last=Pummer |editor2-first=Theron |title=Effective Altruism: Philosophical Issues |series=Engaging philosophy |location=Oxford; New York |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |pages=10\u201328 |isbn=9780198841364 |oclc=1101772304 |doi=10.1093/oso/9780198841364.003.0001 |ref=harv}}</ref> Such philosophical questions shift the starting point of reasoning from \"what to do\" to why and how to do it.<ref name=\"practical-ethics\">{{cite web |last=Crouch |first=Will |date=May 30, 2013 |title=What is effective altruism? |url=http://blog.practicalethics.ox.ac.uk/2013/05/what-is-effective-altruism/ |website=blog.practicalethics.ox.ac.uk |publisher=Practical Ethics blog, Philosophy Faculty, [[University of Oxford]] |accessdate=February 4, 2020 |ref=harv}}</ref>\n\nThe \"guiding question\"<ref name=\"doing-good-better\"/>{{rp|14}} of effective altruism is: How can we, individually and collectively, do the most good?<ref name=\"Singer2015\"/>{{rp|5}}<ref name=\"EA-IEE\"/> Other questions that quickly follow include:\n* \"What counts as 'the most good'?\"<ref name=\"Singer2015\"/>{{rp|7}}\n* \"How can I do the most good, given what others are likely to do?\"<ref name=\"EA-IEE\"/>\n* \"Does everyone's suffering count equally?\"<ref name=\"Singer2015\"/>{{rp|7}}\n* \"Does 'the most good you can do' mean that it is wrong to give priority to one's own children?\"<ref name=\"Singer2015\"/>{{rp|8}}\n* \"What about other values, like [[justice]], [[freedom]], [[Social equality|equality]], and [[knowledge]]?\"<ref name=\"Singer2015\"/>{{rp|8}}\n* \"Can everyone practice effective altruism?\"<ref name=\"Singer2015\"/>{{rp|9}}\n* Is it better to think of effective altruism \"as an 'opportunity' or an 'obligation'?\"<ref name=\"MacAskill-definition\"/>{{rp|16}}\n* \"What if one's act reduces suffering, but to do so one must lie or harm an innocent person?\"<ref name=\"Singer2015\"/>{{rp|9}} Do \"[[the ends justify the means]]\"?<ref name=\"MacAskill-definition\"/>{{rp|20}}\n* \"What would have happened otherwise?\"<ref name=\"doing-good-better\"/>{{rp|13}}\n* \"What are the chances of success, and how good would success be?\"<ref name=\"doing-good-better\"/>{{rp|13}}\n\nThere is reasonable disagreement, among philosophers and other people, about the answers to such questions.<ref name=\"EA-IEE\"/> But the minimal philosophical core of effective altruism involves at least having some reason to benefit all others, that is, reason to promote their [[well-being]],<ref>{{harvtxt|MacAskill|2019}} said of the emphasis on well-being in effective altruism: \"This [[welfarism]] is 'tentative', however, insofar as it is taken to be merely a working assumption. The ultimate aim of the effective altruist project is to do as much good as possible; the current focus on wellbeing rests on the idea that, given the current state of the world and our incredible opportunity to benefit others, the best ways of promoting welfarist value are broadly the same as the best ways of promoting the good.\" (p.&nbsp;18)</ref> \"and more reason to benefit them more, and most reason to benefit them as much as possible, at least [[Defeasibility|defeasibly]] and [[all other things being equal]]\".<ref name=\"EA-IEE\"/> This minimal philosophical core of effective altruism is likely to be supported by a wide variety of views about [[morality]] and [[meta-ethics]].<ref name=\"MacAskill-intro\"/><ref name=\"EA-IEE\"/> For example, the moral theory of [[consequentialism]], including [[utilitarianism]], supports the aim of using resources to benefit others as much as possible, but effective altruism is not necessarily, as has sometimes been said, the same as consequentialism.<ref name=\"MacAskill-intro\"/><ref name=\"EA-IEE\"/>\n\nThere are different views about whether effective altruism entails [[Normative ethics|normative ethical]] claims such as \"we should do the most good we can\".<ref>{{harvtxt|Singer|2015}} expressed a clearly normative view: \"Effective altruism is based on a very simple idea: we should do the most good we can. Obeying the usual rules about not stealing, cheating, hurting, and killing is not enough, or at least not enough for those of us who have the great good fortune to live in material comfort, who can feed, house, and clothe ourselves and our families and still have money or time to spare. Living a minimally acceptable ethical life involves using a substantial part of our spare resources to make the world a better place. Living a fully ethical life involves doing the most good we can.\" (p.&nbsp;vii)</ref><ref name=\"MacAskill-definition\"/>{{rp|12\u201315}} One view says that effective altruism is not a set of normative claims (telling what people \"should do\") but instead is a project, intellectual and practical, of \"trying to figure out how to use resources in whatever way will do the most good with a given unit of resources\" and of putting what has been learned into practice.<ref name=\"MacAskill-definition\"/>{{rp|15}} According to this view, the normative ethical theories of consequentialism, [[egalitarianism]], [[prioritarianism]], [[contractualism]], [[deontological ethics]], [[virtue ethics]], as well as many traditional religious teachings on altruism, can all be compatible with the project of effective altruism.<ref name=\"MacAskill-intro\"/><ref name=\"EA-IEE\"/> Effective altruism is not a ''complete'' philosophy of how to live morally, but effective altruism may be relevant for any view that assumes some reason to promote the good and that assumes that the well-being of others is part of the good.<ref name=\"MacAskill-definition\"/>{{rp|19}}\n\nSome people have reported that the questions and answers posed by the philosophy of effective altruism have helped them learn more about complex problems and gain a deeper sense of meaning as well as a feeling of satisfaction about helping others more effectively.<ref>For example, ''[[Vox (website)|Vox]]'' staff writer and self-identified effective altruist Kelsey Piper wrote: \"You're asked to sacrifice to do good, but in return you get real and important results, as well as a life filled with meaning and purpose. You're asked to spend a lot of time thinking about complicated, intimidating questions, but you will learn how to approach hard questions and come away with a clearer picture of the world.\" {{cite book |last=Piper |first=Kelsey |date=2020 |chapter=Effective altruism |editor1-last=Pigliucci |editor1-first=Massimo |editor1-link=Massimo Pigliucci |editor2-last=Cleary |editor2-first=Skye |editor3-last=Kaufman |editor3-first=Daniel |title=How to Live a Good Life: A Guide to Choosing Your Personal Philosophy |location=New York |publisher=[[Vintage Books]] |pages=255\u2013270 (268) |isbn=9780525566144 |oclc=1133275390 |ref=harv}} And {{harvtxt|Singer|2015}} reported: \"Second, effective altruism is a way of giving meaning to our own lives and finding fulfillment in what we do. Many effective altruists say that in doing good, they feel good. Effective altruists directly benefit others, but indirectly they often benefit themselves.\" (p.&nbsp;viii)</ref>\n\nThe following subsections describe important ideas that are discussed in the published literature about effective altruism.\n\n===Impartiality===\n[[File:1793 Equality anagoria.JPG|thumb|An allegorical image of equality by Jean-Guillaume Moitte, 1793]]\nAltruism, or benefitting others, can be driven by various kinds of motivation and justification, including impartial or impersonal reasoning and sentiments such as sympathy and compassion.<ref>{{cite SEP |url-id=altruism |title=Altruism |edition=Spring 2018 |last=Kraut |first=Richard |date=August 25, 2016 |accessdate=February 4, 2020 |ref=harv}} See especially the section [https://plato.stanford.edu/archives/spr2018/entries/altruism/#WhyCareAbouOthe \"4. Why care about others?\"]: \"Radically different ways of answering these questions [about why to benefit others] can be found in moral philosophy.\"</ref> Much of the published literature on effective altruism emphasizes impartial or impersonal reasoning and concludes that, all other things being equal, everyone's well-being (and suffering) counts equally, without regard to the individual identities of others.<ref name=\"Singer2015\"/>{{rp|85\u201395}}<ref name=\"EA-IEE\"/><ref name=\"MacAskill-definition\"/>{{rp|17\u201319}}\n\nImpartiality about benefitting others combined with seeking to do the most good is compatible with prioritizing benefits to those who are in a worse state, because anyone who happens to be worse off will benefit more from an improvement in their state, all other things being equal (see {{slink||Global poverty alleviation}} below).<ref name=\"EA-IEE\"/> Impartiality is also the basis of what is called the ''cause neutrality'' of effective altruism (see {{slink||Cause prioritization}} below): choosing among possible altruistic activities or causes (problems) based on whether they will do the most good with limited resources\u2014as opposed to choosing among them based on other factors such as personal connections.<ref name=\"EA-IEE\"/>\n\nSome effective altruists have argued that there will be many more members of future generations than there are members of current populations, so the way to do the most good is to focus on promoting long-term well-being by, for example, reducing [[Risks to civilization, humans, and planet Earth|existential risks to humanity]] (see {{slink||Long-term future and global catastrophic risks}} below).<ref name=\"Singer2015\"/>{{rp|165\u2013178}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://80000hours.org/articles/future-generations/|title=Introducing longtermism: How important are future generations?|last=Todd|first=Benjamin|date=October 24, 2017|website=80000 Hours|access-date=February 8, 2020|quote=Since the future is big, there could be far more people in the future than in the present generation. This means that if you want to help people in general, your ''key concern'' shouldn't be to help the present generation, but to ensure that the future goes well in the long-term. Previously, we called this the 'long-term value thesis', though it is now most commonly called 'longtermism'. This thesis is often confused with the claim that we shouldn't ''do'' anything to help people in the present generation. But the long-term value thesis is about what most ''matters''\u2014what we should ''do'' about it is a further question. It might turn out that the best way to help those in the future is to improve the lives of people in the present, such as through providing health and education.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Beckstead |first=Nick |chapter=A brief argument for the overwhelming importance of shaping the far future |date=2019 |editor1-last=Greaves |editor1-first=Hilary |editor1-link=Hilary Greaves |editor2-last=Pummer |editor2-first=Theron |title=Effective Altruism: Philosophical Issues |series=Engaging philosophy |location=Oxford; New York |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |pages=80\u201398 |isbn=9780198841364 |oclc=1101772304 |doi=10.1093/oso/9780198841364.003.0006 |ref=harv}}</ref>\n\nSome effective altruists think that the [[Animal rights|interests of non-human animals]] should be accorded equal moral weight as similar interests of humans, so they work to prevent the suffering of animals (see {{slink||Animal welfare}} below),<ref>{{cite journal |last=Fisher |first=Andrew |date=January 2017 |title=Theory-neutral arguments for 'effective animal advocacy' |journal=Essays in Philosophy |volume=18 |issue=1 |pages=eP1578:1\u201314 |doi=10.7710/1526-0569.1578 |url=https://commons.pacificu.edu/eip/vol18/iss1/3 |issn=1526-0569 |ref=harv}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last=Broad |first=Garrett M. |date=December 2018 |title=Effective animal advocacy: effective altruism, the social economy, and the animal protection movement |journal=Agriculture and Human Values |volume=35 |issue=4 |pages=777\u2013789 |doi=10.1007/s10460-018-9873-5 |ref=harv}}</ref> especially animals raised in [[Factory farming|factory farms]].<ref name=whyfarmedanimals>{{Cite web|url=https://animalcharityevaluators.org/donation-advice/why-farmed-animals/|title=Why Farmed Animals?|website=Animal Charity Evaluators|language=en-US|access-date=|date=November 2016}}</ref>\n\nThere are many kinds of motivation and justification for impartiality, as for altruism.<ref name=\"sep-impartiality\">{{cite SEP |url-id=impartiality |title=Impartiality |edition=Spring 2018 |last=Jollimore |first=Troy |date=February 6, 2017 |accessdate=March 11, 2017 |ref=harv}}</ref> An argument for impartiality that has been influential among effective altruists<ref>On the influence of Singer's essay \"[[Famine, Affluence, and Morality]]\" see, for example: {{harvnb|Snow|2015}}, {{harvnb|Singer|2015|pp=13\u201320}}, and {{cite magazine |last=Lichtenberg |first=Judith |date=November 30, 2015 |title=Peter Singer's extremely altruistic heirs: Forty years after it was written, 'Famine, Affluence, and Morality' has spawned a radical new movement |url=https://newrepublic.com/article/124690/peter-singers-extremely-altruistic-heirs |magazine=[[The New Republic]] |ref=harv}}</ref> was expressed by philosopher [[Peter Singer]] in his 1972 essay \"[[Famine, Affluence, and Morality]]\", in which he wrote:\n\n<blockquote>It makes no moral difference whether the person I can help is a neighbor's child ten yards away from me or a Bengali whose name I shall never know, ten thousand miles away.&nbsp;... The moral point of view requires us to look beyond the interests of our own society. Previously,&nbsp;... this may hardly have been feasible, but it is quite feasible now. From the moral point of view, the prevention of the starvation of millions of people outside our society must be considered at least as pressing as the upholding of property norms within our society.<ref name=\"Singer1972\">{{cite journal |last=Singer |first=Peter |date=Spring 1972 |title=Famine, Affluence, and Morality |journal=[[Philosophy and Public Affairs]] |volume=1 |issue=3 |pages=229\u2013243 |jstor=2265052 |ref=harv}} The essay was republished in book form in 2016 with a new preface and two extra essays by Singer: {{cite book |last=Singer |first=Peter |date=2016 |title=Famine, Affluence, and Morality |location=Oxford; New York |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |isbn=9780190219208 |oclc=907446001 |ref=harv}}</ref>{{rp|231\u2013232, 237}}</blockquote>\n\nThis argument for impartiality was later repeated in other books by Singer<ref name=\"Singer2015\"/><ref name=\"Singer2009\"/> and expanded on in the 1996 book ''[[Living High and Letting Die]]'' by philosopher [[Peter Unger]].<ref>{{cite journal |last=Feldman |first=Fred |date=March 1998 |title=Review of ''Living High and Letting Die: Our Illusion of Innocence'' by Peter Unger |journal=[[No\u00fbs]] |volume=32 |issue=1 |pages=138\u2013147 |doi=10.1111/0029-4624.00093 |jstor=2671931 |url=https://people.umass.edu/ffeldman/Unger.pdf |ref=harv}}</ref>\n\n====Obstacles to impartiality====\nSinger speculated in \"Famine, Affluence, and Morality\" that whether people actually reason and act impartially is likely to be affected by [[social influence]]: \"What it is possible for a man to do and what he is likely to do are both, I think, very greatly influenced by what people around him are doing and expecting him to do.\"<ref name=\"Singer1972\"/>{{rp|237}} In his 2015 book ''[[The Most Good You Can Do]]'', Singer admitted that even though he had argued in 1972 that \"we ought to give large proportions of our income to disaster relief funds\", nevertheless \"even though I argued that this is what we ought to do, I did not do it myself\".<ref name=\"Singer2015\"/>{{rp|13}} He noted the role of social influence and [[psychological inertia]] as obstacles to acting altruistically.<ref name=\"Singer2015\"/>{{rp|13\u201314}} Sociological research has shown that social influence can undermine altruistic activity.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Simpson |first1=Brent |last2=Willer |first2=Robb |authorlink2=Robb Willer |date=August 2015 |title=Beyond altruism: sociological foundations of cooperation and prosocial behavior |journal=[[Annual Review of Sociology]] |volume=41 |pages=43\u201363 |doi=10.1146/annurev-soc-073014-112242 |ref=harv}} \"More generally, laboratory studies of socially decontextualized groups show that person-level factors alone are generally unable to sustain cooperation at the high levels observed in many human groups. As noted above, these groups initially show much variation in contributions, with more altruistic individuals giving at high levels and more egoistic people contributing little or nothing at all. Contributions of more altruistic individuals then decline over time in response to their egoistic counterparts' noncooperation (Fehr & Gintis 2007, Sell & Wilson 1991). Thus, in the absence of social mechanisms\u2014e.g., clear enforceable norms, opportunities to gain reputation or status for contributions to group efforts, or social connections between group members\u2014contributions fall to very low levels.\" (p.&nbsp;56)</ref> To support people's ability to act altruistically on the basis of impartial reasoning, the effective altruism movement promotes additional values and actions that are not part of the minimal philosophical core of effective altruism, such as a collaborative spirit, honesty and transparency, and publicly pledging to donate a certain percentage of income or other resources.<ref name=\"MacAskill-intro\"/>{{rp|2}}\n\n===Cause prioritization===\nMany nonprofits emphasize effectiveness and evidence, but this is usually done with a single cause (problem) in mind, such as education or climate change.<ref>{{cite web |last=Schambra |first=William A. |date=May 22, 2014 |title=Opinion: The coming showdown between philanthrolocalism and effective altruism |url=https://www.philanthropydaily.com/the-coming-showdown-between-philanthrolocalism-and-effective-altruism/ |website=Philanthropy Daily |quote=Strategic philanthropists like Paul Brest seek only to apply metrics to the selection of groups once a cause has been selected. But, altruist critics note, this foolishly leaves the choice of the cause itself willy-nilly to the all-too-often idiosyncratic, short-sighted, selfish impulses of the donor.}}</ref> Effective altruists, however, seek to compare the relative importance of different causes and allocate resources among them objectively, a concept that is usually referred to as ''cause neutrality''.<ref name=\"cause-neutrality\">{{Cite web |last=Schubert |first=Stefan |date=March 10, 2017 |url=https://www.centreforeffectivealtruism.org/blog/understanding-cause-neutrality/ |title=Understanding cause-neutrality |website=Centre for Effective Altruism |language=en-US |access-date=March 10, 2020 |ref=harv}} Schubert said that the term ''cause neutrality'' has been used by various authors with different meanings and different [[decision rule]]s.</ref> One approach to cause neutrality, for example, is to choose the highest priority causes based on whether activities in each cause area could efficiently advance broad goals, such as increasing human or animal welfare, and then focus attention on interventions in those cause areas.<ref>{{harvtxt|Schubert|2017}} called this approach the \"cause-flexible investments\" strategy and compared it to other strategies such as \"cause-divergent investments\". With regard to these two strategies, he noted: \"How to prioritize between these two strategies is an important and understudied question.\"</ref>\n\nThe information required for cause prioritization can be difficult to produce; it may involve collecting and processing complex [[data set]]s, comparing possible outcomes with what would have happened under other conditions (see {{slink||Counterfactual reasoning}} below), and identifying various kinds of [[uncertainty]].<ref name=\"EA-IEE\"/><ref>{{cite journal |last=MacAskill |first=William |authorlink=William MacAskill |date=September 2019 |title=Practical ethics given moral uncertainty |journal=[[Utilitas]] |volume=31 |issue=3 |pages=231\u2013245 |doi=10.1017/S0953820819000013 |ref=harv}}</ref> These challenges have led to the creation of organizations that specialize in researching the relative prioritization of causes.<ref name=\"EA-IEE\"/><ref name=\"Problems\">{{Cite web|url=https://80000hours.org/problem-profiles/|title=Our current view of the world's most pressing problems|website=80,000 Hours|language=en-US|access-date=March 10, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|last=Karnofsky|first=Holden|authorlink=Holden Karnofsky|date=January 26, 2018|url=https://www.openphilanthropy.org/blog/update-cause-prioritization-open-philanthropy|title=Update on cause prioritization at Open Philanthropy|website=www.openphilanthropy.org|access-date=March 10, 2020}}</ref> Some common priorities among effective altruists have included poverty in the [[Developing country|developing world]], the suffering of animals in [[Factory farming|factory farms]], and [[Global catastrophic risk|risks to civilization, humans and planet Earth]] (see {{slink||Cause priorities}} below).<ref name=\"doing-good-better\" /><ref name=practical-ethics/>\n\n===Cost-effectiveness===\nEffective altruist organizations have argued that some charities are far more effective than others, either because some do not achieve their goals or because of variability in the cost of achieving those goals.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.givewell.org/giving101/Funding-the-Right-Program | publisher = GiveWell | title = Your dollar goes further when you fund the right program }}</ref><ref name=dollar-overseas>{{cite web | url = http://www.givewell.org/giving101/Your-dollar-goes-further-overseas | publisher = GiveWell | title = Your Dollar Goes Further Overseas}}</ref> When possible, they seek to identify charities that are highly [[cost-effectiveness analysis|cost-effective]], meaning that they achieve a large benefit for a given amount of money.<ref name=\"The Atlantic article The Greatest Good\" /> For example, they select health interventions on the basis of their impact as measured by lives saved per dollar, [[quality-adjusted life year]]s (QALY) saved per dollar, or [[disability-adjusted life year]]s (DALY) averted per dollar. This measure of disease burden is expressed as the number of years lost due to ill-health, disability or early death.\n\nSome effective altruism organizations use [[randomized controlled trial]]s as a primary form of evidence,<ref name=\"The Atlantic article The Greatest Good\" /><ref name=\"skelton\">{{cite journal|last1=Skelton|first1=Anthony|title=The ethical principles of effective altruism|journal=Journal of Global Ethics|date=2016|volume=12|issue=2|pages=137\u2013146|url=https://philpapers.org/rec/SKETEP|accessdate= March 11, 2017|doi=10.1080/17449626.2016.1193552|ref=harv}}</ref> as they are often considered to be at the highest level of strong evidence in healthcare research.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://nhmrc.gov.au/about-us/publications/guide-development-evaluation-and-implementation-clinical-practice-guidelines|title=A guide to the development, implementation and evaluation of clinical practice guidelines|last=|first=|publisher=National Health and Medical Research Council|year=1998|isbn=1864960485|location=Canberra: Commonwealth of Australia|pages=21\u201325}}</ref> Others have argued that requiring this stringent level of evidence unnecessarily narrows the focus to only those issues on which this kind of evidence is possible, and that the history of philanthropy suggests that the most effective interventions have often proceeded without this level of evidence.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Karnofsky|first=Holden|authorlink=Holden Karnofsky|date=April 4, 2016|url=https://www.openphilanthropy.org/blog/hits-based-giving|title=Hits-based giving|website=www.openphilanthropy.org|access-date=March 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Room for more funding====\nEffective altruist organizations make philanthropic recommendations for charities on the basis of the impact from marginal funding rather than merely evaluating the average value of all donations to the charity.<ref name=\"givewell-interview-huffpo\">{{cite web|last1=Zhang|first1=Linch|title=How Can You do the Most Good with Your Charitable Giving? This Expert's Answers Might Surprise You|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/linch-zhang/how-can-you-do-the-most-g_b_10597442.html|website=Huffington Post|accessdate= March 18, 2017|date= June 21, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"SSIR-holden\">{{cite web|last1=Karnofsky|first1=Holden|title=We Should Expect Good Giving To Be Hard (SSIR)|url=https://ssir.org/articles/entry/we_should_expect_good_giving_to_be_hard|website=Stanford Social Innovation Review|publisher=Stanford University|accessdate=March 18, 2017|language=en-us}}</ref> Effective altruists avoid donating to organizations that have no \"room for more funding\" \u2013 those that face bottlenecks other than money which prevent them from spending the funds they have already accumulated or are expected to receive.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.givewell.org/how-we-work/criteria/room-for-more-funding|title=Room for More Funding {{!}} GiveWell|website=www.givewell.org|access-date=2019-01-12}}</ref> For example, a medical charity might not be able to hire enough doctors or nurses to distribute the medical supplies it is capable of purchasing, or it might already be serving all of the potential patients in its market. There are many other organizations which ''do'' have room for more funding, so giving to one of those instead would produce real-world improvements.\n\n===Counterfactual reasoning===\nEffective altruists argue that [[Counterfactual conditional|counterfactual]] reasoning is important to determine which course of action maximizes positive impact. Many people assume that the best way to help people is through direct methods, such as working for a charity or providing social services,<ref>{{cite news | title = Best jobs for saving the world | first1 = Donna | last1  = Rosato | first2 = Grace | last2 = Wong | date = November 2011 | url = http://money.cnn.com/magazines/moneymag/best-jobs/2011/jobs-helping-others/1.html | accessdate = February 28, 2013 | work=CNN}}</ref> but since charities and social-service providers usually can find people willing to work for them, effective altruists compare the amount of good somebody does in a conventional altruistic career to how much good would have been done had the next-best candidate been hired for the position. According to this reasoning, the impact of a career may be smaller than it appears.<ref name=\"todd-career-paper\">{{cite web|last1=Todd|first1=Benjamin|title=Which Ethical Careers Make a Difference?: The Replaceability Issue in the Ethics of Career Choice|url=https://www.academia.edu/1807196|website=University of Oxford|accessdate= March 11, 2017|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://80000hours.org/2015/07/replaceability-isnt-as-important-as-you-might-think-or-weve-suggested/|title='Replaceability' isn't as important as you might think (or we've suggested)|date=2015-07-27|website=80,000 Hours|language=en-US|access-date=2019-01-12}}</ref>\n\n==Behavior==\nThe philosophical or intellectual part of effective altruism, described above, is about learning how to do the most good through the use of evidence and reasoning. The behavioral or practical part is about using what has been learned to try to do the most good through altruistic activities.<ref name=\"EA-IEE\"/><ref name=\"MacAskill-definition\"/>{{rp|14}}\n\n===Donation===\n\nEffective altruism encourages significant charitable donation. Some believe it is a moral duty to alleviate suffering through donations if the purchases that one forgoes to donate do not cause comparable suffering to oneself,<ref name=Singer1972 /> leading some of them to lead a frugal lifestyle in order to give substantially more than is typical in their society.<ref name=\"kaufman-wise\">{{cite news|last1=Burton|first1=Paul|title=Family Gives Away Half Their Income To Help Others|url=http://boston.cbslocal.com/2015/10/13/family-gives-away-half-their-income-to-help-others/|accessdate= March 11, 2017|date=October 13, 2015}}</ref> Advocacy focuses on increasing the amount that people donate or identifying nonprofits that best meet the criteria of effective altruism, in particular cost-effectiveness, transparency and strong evidence.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.givewell.org/how-we-work/criteria|title=Our Criteria for Top Charities {{!}} GiveWell|website=www.givewell.org|access-date=2018-12-09}}</ref>\n\n[[Giving What We Can]] (GWWC) is an organization that hosts a community of individuals who have pledged to donate at least 10% of their income for the remainder of their working lives to the causes that they believe are the most effective. GWWC was founded in 2009 by [[Toby Ord]], a moral philosopher, who lives on \u00a318,000 ($27,000) per year and donates the remainder of his income to charity.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/magazine-11950843|title=Toby Ord: Why I'm giving \u00a31m to charity|last=Geoghegan|first=Tom|date= December 13, 2010|accessdate= March 2, 2013|newspaper=BBC News}}</ref> As of 2019, more than 4,100 individuals have taken the pledge, who have collectively pledged to donate upwards of $1.5 billion over the course of their lifetimes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.givingwhatwecan.org/|title=Giving What We Can|website=www.givingwhatwecan.org|access-date=2018-12-09}}</ref><ref name=\"ox-gwwc-pledges\">{{cite news|title=1000 people match Oxford philosopher's '10% of future income' charity pledge|url=http://www.ox.ac.uk/news/2015-07-15-1000-people-match-oxford-philosopher%E2%80%99s-%E2%80%9810-future-income%E2%80%99-charity-pledge|accessdate= March 11, 2017|work=University of Oxford|date= July 15, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Founders Pledge]] is a similar initiative run by the nonprofit Founders Forum for Good where startup founders make a legally binding commitment to donate at least 2% of their personal proceeds to charity in the event that they sell their business.<ref name=\"founders-pledge-80k-interview\">{{cite web|last=MacAskill|first=William|authorlink=William MacAskill|title=One of the most exciting new effective altruist organisations: An interview with David Goldberg of the Founders Pledge|url=https://80000hours.org/2015/11/one-of-the-most-exciting-new-effective-altruist-organisations-an-interview-with-david-goldberg-of-the-founders-pledge/|website=80,000 Hours|accessdate= March 11, 2017|date=November 26, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"founders-pledge-forbes\">{{cite news|last1=Prosser|first1=David|title=Entrepreneurs Pledge Millions To Social Good|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/davidprosser/2015/06/10/entrepreneurs-pledge-millions-to-social-good/#3d2f84e66bb9|accessdate=11 March 2017|work=Forbes|date=10 June 2015}}</ref><ref name=techcrunch>{{cite news|url = https://techcrunch.com/2015/06/09/uk-tech-founders-take-the-founders-pledge-to-2-commiting-28m-to-good-causes/|title = UK Tech Founders Take The Founders Pledge To 2%, Committing $28m+ To Good Causes|last = Butcher|first = Mike|date = June 9, 2015|accessdate = December 5, 2015|work = [[TechCrunch]]}}</ref> By January 2019, three years after launch, more than 1400 entrepreneurs have pledged an estimated total value of $700 million based on the founders' equity and the companies' valuation and at least $91 million were raised.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fastcompany.com/90240242/why-nonprofits-should-be-courting-entrepreneurs-as-donors|title=Why nonprofits should be courting entrepreneurs as donors|last=Paynter|first=Ben|date=2018-09-25|website=Fast Company|language=en-US|access-date=2018-12-09}}</ref>\n\n===Career selection===\n\nEffective altruists argue that selection of one's career is an important determinant of the amount of good one does,<ref name=\"oliver\">{{cite web|last1=Oliver|first1=Huw|title='Effective altruists' are a new type of nice person|url=https://www.vice.com/en_uk/article/why-are-young-people-being-so-altruistic-209|website=[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]|accessdate= March 11, 2017|language=en-us}}</ref> both directly (through the services one provides to the world) and indirectly (through the ways one directs the money earned based on the career).<ref name=\"macaskill-replaceability-paper\" />\n\n[[80,000 Hours]] is an organisation in the effective altruism community that conducts research on which careers have the largest positive social impact and provides career advice based on that research.<ref name=\"career-choice-vox\" /><ref name=yc-techcrunch>{{cite news|url = https://techcrunch.com/2015/08/04/80000-hours/|title = Want To Make An Impact With Your Work? Try Some Advice From 80,000 Hours|date = August 4, 2015|accessdate = October 31, 2015|work = [[TechCrunch]]}}</ref> It considers indirect methods of altruistic employment, such as earning a high salary in a conventional career and donating a portion of it, as well as direct practices, such as scientific research. It was co-founded by [[William MacAskill]] and Benjamin Todd.<ref name=\"fastcoexist\">{{cite web|last1=Alcorn|first1=Stan|title=How To Choose An Ethical Career (With Help From Oxford Philosophers)|url=https://www.fastcoexist.com/1682193/how-to-choose-an-ethical-career-with-help-from-oxford-philosophers|website=Co.Exist|publisher=Fast Company Inc|accessdate= March 11, 2017|date= June 4, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://80000hours.org/about/meet-the-team/|title=Meet the team|website=80,000 Hours|language=en-US|access-date=2018-12-09}}</ref>\n\n[[Earning to give]] has been proposed as a possible strategy for effective altruists. This strategy involves choosing to work in high-paying careers with the explicit goal of donating large sums of money to charity.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://80000hours.org/articles/earning-to-give/|title=Why and how to earn to give|website=80,000 Hours|language=en-US|access-date=|first = Benjamin|last = Todd|date =April 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"join-ws-save-world\">{{cite news|last1=Matthews|first1=Dylan|title=Join Wall Street. Save the world.|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/wonk/wp/2013/05/31/join-wall-street-save-the-world/|accessdate= March 11, 2017|work= Washington Post}}</ref> MacAskill argues that it might even be worth earning to give in morally controversial careers, since the marginal impact of taking an unethical job is small if someone else would have taken it regardless, while the counterfactual impact of the donations would be large.<ref name=\"macaskill-replaceability-paper\">{{cite journal|last1=William|first1=MacAskill|title=Replaceability, Career Choice, and Making a Difference|journal=Ethical Theory and Moral Practice|volume=17|issue=2|pages=269\u2013283|date=2014|doi=10.1007/s10677-013-9433-4|url=https://www.academia.edu/1557895|language=en|issn=1386-2820}}</ref> However, 80,000 Hours have more recently argued that it is better to avoid careers that do significant direct harm, even if it seems like the negative consequences would be outweighed by donations. This is because there are often hidden harms in following unethical careers, and because they think it is important to take moral uncertainty into account.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://80000hours.org/articles/harmful-career/|title=Is it ever okay to take a harmful job in order to do more good? An in-depth analysis.|website=80,000 Hours|language=en-US|access-date= June 27, 2019|first = Benjamin|last = Todd|date =August 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[David Brooks (journalist)|David Brooks]], a columnist for ''[[The New York Times]]'', criticized earning to give. He wrote that most people who work in finance and other high-paying industries value money for selfish reasons and that being surrounded by these people will cause effective altruists to become less altruistic.<ref name=\"brooks2013\">{{cite web|last1=Brooks|first1=David | title=The Way to Produce a Person |newspaper=The New York Times|date=June 3, 2013| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/06/04/opinion/brooks-the-way-to-produce-a-person.html?_r=0|accessdate=July 7, 2015}}</ref> [[Peter Singer]] responded to these criticisms in his book ''The Most Good You Can Do'' by giving examples of people who have been earning to give for years without losing their altruistic motivation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://blog.yupnet.org/2016/08/09/earning-to-give-leads-to-happiness/|title='Earning to Give' Leads to Happiness|date=2016-08-09|website=Yale Press Log|access-date=2017-04-04}}</ref> In ''[[The Week]]'', Pascal-Emmanuel Gobry argued that the practice was \"unsettling\".<ref name=\"gobry\">{{cite magazine|url=https://theweek.com/articles/542955/effective-altruism-really-change-world|title = Can Effective Altruism really change the world?|last = Gobry|first = Pascal-Emmanuel|date = March 16, 2015|accessdate = March 21, 2015|magazine = [[The Week]]}}</ref>\n\n==Cause priorities==\n\nSince effective altruism aims for cause neutrality (see {{slink||Cause prioritization}} above),<ref name=\"cause-neutrality\" /> it is in principle open to helping in whichever causes (problems) allow people to do the most good, impartially considered.<ref name=practical-ethics/><ref name=\"kissel\" /> Such causes may include, for example, providing food for the [[hungry]], protecting [[endangered species]], mitigating [[climate change]], reforming [[immigration policy]], researching [[cure]]s for illnesses, preventing [[sexual violence]], [[Poverty alleviation|alleviating poverty]], eliminating [[factory farming]], or averting [[nuclear warfare]].<ref name=\"EA-IEE\"/> Many people in the effective altruist movement have prioritized global poverty, animal welfare, and risks to the survival and flourishing of humanity and its descendants over the long-term future.<ref name=vox>{{cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/2015/4/24/8457895/givewell-open-philanthropy-charity|title = You have $8 billion. You want to do as much good as possible. What do you do? Inside the Open Philanthropy Project |last=Matthews |first=Dylan |authorlink=Dylan Matthews |date=April 24, 2015 |accessdate=April 27, 2015 |website=[[Vox (website)|Vox]]}}</ref><ref name=skelton/><ref name=\"Problems\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://forum.effectivealtruism.org/posts/pfbLKnJmDKYSPPCEW/four-focus-areas-of-effective-altruism|title=Four focus areas of effective altruism \u2013 Effective Altruism Forum|last=Muehlhauser|first=Luke|date=July 8, 2013|website=forum.effectivealtruism.org|language=en|access-date=January 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Global poverty alleviation===\n\nGlobal [[poverty alleviation]] has been a focus of some of the earliest and most prominent organizations associated with effective altruism.\n\nCharity evaluator [[GiveWell]] was founded by [[Holden Karnofsky]] and Elie Hassenfeld in 2007 to address poverty and is part of the effective altruism community.<ref name=\"givewell-opt-in\">{{cite web|url=http://blog.givewell.org/2013/08/13/effective-altruism/|title=Effective Altruism|last=Karnofsky|first=Holden|date=August 13, 2013|publisher=[[GiveWell]]|accessdate=April 11, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Konduri|first1=Vimal|title=GiveWell Co-Founder Explains Effective Altruism Frameworks|url=http://www.thecrimson.com/article/2015/12/4/givewell-founder-effective-altruism/|website=The Harvard Crimson|publisher=The Harvard Crimson, Inc|accessdate= March 10, 2017|ref=crimson|language=en}}</ref> GiveWell has argued that the value of donations is greatest for international poverty alleviation and developing world health issues,<ref name=\"dollar-overseas\" /><ref name=\"bloomberg-givewell\">{{cite news|last1=Wolfe|first1=Alexandra|title=Hedge Fund Analytics for Nonprofits|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2011-11-23/hedge-fund-analytics-for-nonprofits|accessdate= March 11, 2017|work=Bloomberg.com|publisher=Bloomberg LP|date= November 24, 2011}}</ref> and its leading recommendations have been in these domains (including [[malaria]] prevention charities [[Against Malaria Foundation]] and [[Malaria Consortium]], deworming charities [[Schistosomiasis Control Initiative]] and [[Deworm the World Initiative]], and [[GiveDirectly]] for direct unconditional cash transfers).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.economist.com/news/international/21651815-lessons-business-charities-doing-good-doing-well|title=Doing good by doing well|website=The Economist|publisher=Hearst Communications, Inc|accessdate=10 March 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"huffpo-elie\">{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2015/03/26/elie-hassenfeld-givewell_n_6927320.html|title=That Time A Hedge Funder Quit His Job And Then Raised $60 Million For Charity|last=Pitney|first=Nico|date=March 26, 2015|work=[[Huffington Post]]|accessdate=April 27, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe effective altruism organization The Life You Can Save, which originated from Singer's book by the same name,<ref name=\"Singer2009\">{{cite book |last=Singer |first=Peter |authorlink=Peter Singer |date=2009 |title=[[The Life You Can Save|The Life You Can Save: Acting Now to End World Poverty]] |location=New York |publisher=Random House |isbn=9781400067107 |oclc=232980306 |ref=harv}}</ref> also works to alleviate global poverty by promoting evidence-backed charities, conducting philanthropy education and changing the culture of giving in affluent countries.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/how-to-do-good-a-conversation-with-the-worlds-leading_us_58cb8dcee4b0537abd956f91|title=How To Do Good: A Conversation With The World's Leading Ethicist|last=Zhang|first=Linch|date=March 17, 2017|website=Huffington Post|language=en-US|access-date=June 1, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thelifeyoucansave.org/about-us|title=About The Life You Can Save non-profit organization|website=www.thelifeyoucansave.org|access-date=2019-01-12}}</ref>\n\nWhile much of the initial focus of effective altruism was on direct strategies such as health interventions and cash transfers, there has also been interest in more systematic social, economic, and political reform that would facilitate larger long-term poverty reduction.<ref name=\"scott-weathers\">{{cite web|last1=Weathers|first1=Scott|title=Can 'effective altruism' change the world? It already has.|url=https://www.opendemocracy.net/transformation/scott-weathers/can-effective-altruism-change-world-it-already-has|website=Transformation|accessdate=11 March 2017|language=en|date=29 February 2016}}</ref> In 2011, GiveWell announced GiveWell Labs, which was later renamed as the [[Open Philanthropy Project]], for research and philanthropic funding of more speculative and diverse causes such as policy reform, global catastrophic risk reduction and scientific research.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.openphilanthropy.org/focus|title=Focus Areas {{!}} Open Philanthropy Project|website=www.openphilanthropy.org|access-date=2019-01-12}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.givewell.org/2011/09/08/announcing-givewell-labs/|title=Announcing GiveWell Labs|last=Karnofsky|first=Holden|date=September 8, 2011|website=|publisher=[[GiveWell]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=April 11, 2015}}</ref> It is a collaboration between GiveWell and [[Good Ventures]], a philanthropic foundation founded by [[Facebook]] co-founder [[Dustin Moskovitz]] and his wife Cari Tuna.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.openphilanthropy.org/about/who-we-are|title=Who We Are {{!}} Open Philanthropy Project|website=www.openphilanthropy.org|access-date=2019-01-12}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.givewell.org/2014/08/20/open-philanthropy-project-formerly-givewell-labs/|title=Open Philanthropy Project (formerly GiveWell Labs)|last=Karnofsky|first=Holden|date=August 20, 2014|website=|publisher=[[GiveWell]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=April 11, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Moses\">{{cite news|last1=Moses|first1=Sue-Lynn|title=Leverage: Why This Silicon Valley Funder Is Doubling Down on a Beltway Think Tank|url=https://www.insidephilanthropy.com/home/2016/3/9/leverage-why-this-silicon-valley-funder-is-doubling-down-on.html|accessdate=11 March 2017|work=Inside Philanthropy|date=9 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Animal welfare===\n\nSome effective altruists believe that reducing [[animal suffering]] should be a major priority and that, at the current margin, there are cost-effective ways of accomplishing this.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.effectivealtruism.org/articles/cause-profile-animal-welfare/|title=Cause Profile: Animal Welfare|last=Whittlestone|first=Jess|date=November 16, 2017|website=Effective Altruism|access-date=2019-01-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/davidebanis/2018/11/27/new-book-draws-detailed-roadmap-of-how-we-can-end-animal-farming/|title=New Book Draws Detailed Roadmap Of How We Can End Animal Farming |last=Banis|first=Davide|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2019-01-12}}</ref> Singer quotes estimates by the [[Food and Agriculture Organization]] of the [[United Nations]] and the British organization Fishcount according to which 60 billion land animals are [[Animal slaughter|slaughtered]] and between 1 and 2.7 trillion individual fish are killed each year for human consumption.<ref>{{Cite news|url= https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/cif-green/2010/sep/14/fish-forgotten-victims |title=Fish: the forgotten victims on our plate|date=2010-09-14|work=The Guardian|access-date=June 14, 2017|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url= http://www.fao.org/fileadmin/user_upload/animalwelfare/GlobalWarningExecutiveSummary1.pdf|title=Global Warming Climate Change and Farm Animal Welfare|last=|first=|publisher=Compassion in World Farming|year=2008|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url= http://www.fishcount.org.uk/published/standard/fishcountfullrptSR.pdf|title=Worse things happen at sea: the welfare of wild-caught fish|last=Mood|first=Alison|publisher=fishcount.org.uk|year=2010|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> He argues that effective animal welfare altruists should prioritize [[Intensive animal farming|factory farming]] over more overfunded popular causes such as pet welfare.<ref name=\"kristof\" /><ref name = whyfarmedanimals/> Singer also argues that, if farm animals such as chickens are assigned even a modicum of [[consciousness]], efforts to reduce factory farming (for example, by reducing global [[meat]] consumption) could be an even more underfunded and cost-effective way of reducing current global suffering than human [[poverty]] reduction.<ref name=\"Singer2015\"/>{{rp|138, 146\u2013147}} Philosophically, [[wild animal suffering]] may be an additional moral concern for effective altruists.<ref>{{cite web|title=\"Effective Altruism for Animals\" Panel, Animal Studies|url=http://animalstudies.as.nyu.edu/object/as.events.20150729|website=New York University Animal Studies Initiative |publisher=NYU|accessdate=11 March 2017}}</ref> In 2018, the book ''[[The End of Animal Farming]]'' by [[Jacy Reese]] discussed animal welfare issues from an effective altruism perspective, with a specific focus on the potential for [[cultured meat]] to address farm animal suffering and the importance of expanding the moral circle to help people care more about future beings, wild animals, invertebrates, and artificial sentience.<ref>{{cite book|title=The End of Animal Farming|publisher=[[Beacon Press]]|isbn=978-0807019450|year=2018}}</ref>\n\n'''Animal Charity Evaluators'''<!--boldface per [[WP:R#PLA]]--> (ACE) is an effective altruism organization that evaluates and compares various animal charities based on their cost-effectiveness and transparency, particularly those that are tackling factory farming.<ref name=\"animal-welfare-vox\" /><ref name=\"auto\">Daniel Engber, [http://www.slate.com/articles/health_and_science/science/2016/08/animal_activists_crunched_the_numbers_to_learn_that_the_creature_most_in.html \"Save the Chicken\"], ''Slate'', August 18, 2016.</ref><ref name=\"Singer2015\"/>{{rp|139}} [[Faunalytics]] (formerly the Humane Research Council) is an organization loosely affiliated with the effective altruism community that conducts independent research on important animal welfare topics, provides resources for advocates and donors, and works with animal protection organizations to evaluate their work.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/future-perfect/2018/10/31/18026418/vegan-vegetarian-animal-welfare-corporate-advocacy|title=Vegan diets are hard to sell. Animal activists might do better focused on corporate decisions, not people's plates.|last=Piper|first=Kelsey|date=2018-10-31|website=Vox|access-date=2019-01-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://faunalytics.org/about/|title=What We Do|website=Faunalytics|language=en-US|access-date=2019-01-12}}</ref> The [[Sentience Institute]] is a new effective altruism [[think tank]] founded in 2017 to address the expansion of the moral circle.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=5 August 2019 |title=Introducing Sentience Institute |url=https://www.sentienceinstitute.org/blog/introducing-sentience-institute |last1=Witwicki |first1=Kelly |last2=Reese |first2=Jacy|publisher=Sentience Institute}}</ref>\n\n===Long-term future and global catastrophic risks===\nFocusing on the long-term future, some effective altruists believe that the total value of any meaningful metric (wealth, potential for suffering, potential for happiness, etc.) summed up over future generations, far exceeds the value for people living today.<ref name=vox/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://80000hours.org/articles/future-generations/|title=If you want to do good, here's why future generations should be your focus|last=Todd|first=Benjamin|date=October 24, 2017|website=80,000 Hours|language=en-US|access-date=2019-01-12}}</ref><ref name=\"eaf-far-future\">{{cite web|title=The Importance of the Far Future|url=https://ea-foundation.org/blog/the-importance-of-the-far-future/|website=Effective Altruism Foundation|publisher=Effective Altruism Foundation|accessdate= March 11, 2017|date= August 5, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bostrom|first=Nick|date=2003|title=Astronomical Waste: The Opportunity Cost of Delayed Technological Development|url=http://www.nickbostrom.com/astronomical/waste.pdf|journal=Utilitas|volume=15|issue=3|pages=308\u2013314|via=|doi=10.1017/S0953820800004076}}</ref> Some researchers have found it psychologically difficult to contemplate the trade-off; Toby Ord has stated that \"Since there is so much work to be done to fix the needless suffering in our present, I was slow to turn to the future.\"<ref name=Precipice/>{{rp|8}} Reasons Ord gave for working on long-term issues include a belief that preventing long-term suffering is \"even more neglected\" than causes related to current suffering, and that the residents of the future are even more powerless to affect risks caused by current events than are current dispossessed populations.<ref name=Precipice>{{cite book |last=Ord |first=Toby |authorlink=Toby Ord |chapter=Introduction |title=[[The Precipice: Existential Risk and the Future of Humanity]] | date=2020 |location=London |publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing |isbn=9781526600196 |oclc=1143365836 |chapterurl=https://cdn.80000hours.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/The-Precipice-Introduction-Chapter-1.pdf}}</ref>{{rp|8}}\n\nPhilosophically, attempts to reduce the suffering of future populations (given they exist) depend on attitudes toward [[Social discount rate#\"Pure time preference\" debates|pure time discounting]], and initiatives focused on preventing human extinction (as opposed to preventing other dystopian futures) additionally depend on attitudes toward [[population ethics]] in order to compare with scenarios where future populations do not exist.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bostrom |first1=Nick |authorlink1=Nick Bostrom |title=Existential risk prevention as global priority |work=[[Global Policy]] |date=February 2013 |pages=15\u201331 |doi=10.1111/1758-5899.12002}}</ref> Peter Singer has argued that existential risk should not be \"the dominant public face of the effective altruism movement\" as doing so would drastically limit the movement's reach.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Klein |first1=Ezra |title=Peter Singer on the lives you can save |url=https://www.vox.com/future-perfect/2019/12/6/20992100/peter-singer-effective-altruism-lives-you-can-save-animal-liberation |accessdate=6 April 2020 |work=Vox |date=6 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn particular, the importance of addressing [[existential risk]]s such as dangers associated with [[biotechnology]] and [[Existential risk from advanced artificial intelligence|advanced artificial intelligence]] is often highlighted and the subject of active research.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://80000hours.org/articles/extinction-risk/|title=Why despite global progress, humanity is probably facing its most dangerous time ever|last=Todd|first=Benjamin|date=2017|website=80,000 Hours|language=en-US|access-date=2019-01-12}}</ref> Because it is often infeasible to use empirical science (such as randomized control trials) to measure the probability of an existential risk, researchers such as [[Nick Bostrom]] have used other methods such as expert opinion elicitation to estimate their importance.<ref name=\"xrisk methods\">{{cite journal |last1=Rowe |first1=Thomas |last2=Beard |first2=Simon |title=Probabilities, methodologies and the evidence base in existential risk assessments |journal=Working Paper, Centre for the Study of Existential Risk |date=2018 |url=http://eprints.lse.ac.uk/89506/1/Beard_Existential-Risk-Assessments_Accepted.pdf |accessdate=26 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nSome organizations that work actively on research and advocacy for improving the long term future, and have connections with the effective altruism community, are the [[Future of Humanity Institute]] at the University of Oxford, the [[Centre for the Study of Existential Risk]] at the University of Cambridge, and the [[Future of Life Institute]].<ref name=\"guan-op-ed\">{{cite news|last1=Guan|first1=Melody|title=The New Social Movement of our Generation: Effective Altruism|url=http://harvardpolitics.com/harvard/new-social-movement-generation-effective-altruism/|accessdate=11 March 2017|work=Harvard Political Review|date=19 April 2015}}</ref> In addition, the [[Machine Intelligence Research Institute]] is focused on the more narrow mission of [[Existential risk from artificial general intelligence#Mitigation|aligning advanced artificial intelligence]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/future-perfect/2018/12/21/18126576/ai-artificial-intelligence-machine-learning-safety-alignment|title=The case for taking AI seriously as a threat to humanity|last=Piper|first=Kelsey|date=2018-12-21|website=Vox|access-date=2019-01-12}}</ref><ref name=\"washpost-ai\">{{cite news|last1=Basulto|first1=Dominic|title=The very best ideas for preventing artificial intelligence from wrecking the planet|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/innovations/wp/2015/07/07/the-very-best-ideas-for-preventing-artificial-intelligence-from-wrecking-the-planet/|accessdate= March 11, 2017|work=Washington Post|date=July 7, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==History of the social movement==\n\nThe movement that came to identify with the name ''effective altruism'' was created in the late 2000s as a community formed around [[Giving What We Can]], founded in 2009 by philosopher Toby Ord with help from philosopher William MacAskill, who also co-founded [[80,000 Hours]] in 2011.<ref name=\"EA-history\">{{cite web|last=MacAskill|first=William|authorlink=William MacAskill|date=March 10, 2014|title=The history of the term 'effective altruism'|url=https://forum.effectivealtruism.org/posts/9a7xMXoSiQs3EYPA2/the-history-of-the-term-effective-altruism|website=forum.effectivealtruism.org|accessdate=February 2, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Singer2015\"/>{{rp|16\u201319}} Those two groups, while planning to incorporate as a charity under a new [[umbrella organization]], held a vote in late 2011 to choose a name for the new organization; the name \"Centre for Effective Altruism\" won.<ref name=ft>{{cite news|last1=Ram|first1=Aliya|title=The power and efficacy of effective altruism|url=https://www.ft.com/content/1954323c-8eb3-11e5-8be4-3506bf20cc2b|accessdate=February 14, 2018|work=Financial Times|date=December 4, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"EA-history\"/><ref name=\"Singer2015\"/>{{rp|18}} Ruair\u00ed Donnelly set up the \"Effective Altruists\" [[Facebook group]] in November 2012, and the movement gained wider exposure with Peter Singer's [[TED talk]] \"The Why and How of Effective Altruism\" in May 2013.<ref name=\"EA-history\"/> Other contributions to the social movement were the writings of philosophers such as Singer on [[applied ethics]] and Bostrom on reducing the risk of [[human extinction]], the founding of organizations such as [[GiveWell]] and [[The Life You Can Save]], and the creation of internet forums such as [[LessWrong]].<ref name=\"Utilitarianism2017\">{{cite book|last1=de Lazari-Radek|first1=Katarzyna|last2=Singer|first2=Peter|chapter=Effective altruism|title=Utilitarianism: A Very Short Introduction|date=September 27, 2017|series=Very short introductions|volume=530|location=Oxford; New York|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780198728795|oclc=965456936|doi=10.1093/actrade/9780198728795.003.0001|pages=108\u2013112}}</ref>{{rp|110}}<ref name=\"Lessons of EA\">{{cite web |last1=Rubenstein |first1=Jennifer |title=The Lessons of Effective Altruism |url=https://www.ethicsandinternationalaffairs.org/2016/the-lessons-of-effective-altruism/ |website=Ethics & International Affairs |accessdate=26 August 2018 |date=14 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nEffective altruism conferences (called [[Effective Altruism Global]]) have been held since 2013.<ref name=\"huffpost-ea-global\">{{cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/elon-musk-google-effective-altruism_us_55a56626e4b04740a3de3130|title=Elon Musk To Address 'Nerd Altruists' At Google HQ|last1=Pitney|first1=Nico|date=July 16, 2015|website=Huffington Post|accessdate=March 11, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.exponentialtimes.net/videos/jaan-tallinns-keynote-effective-altruism-summit-2013|title = Jaan Tallinn's Keynote - Effective Altruism Summit 2013 |date = November 13, 2013|accessdate = April 11, 2015|work= Exponential Times}}</ref> In 2015, Peter Singer published ''[[The Most Good You Can Do]]'', a book on effective altruism. The book describes the philosophy and social movement of effective altruism and argues in favor of it.<ref name=\"kristof\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/04/05/opinion/sunday/nicholas-kristof-the-trader-who-donates-half-his-pay.html|title = The Trader Who Donates Half His Pay|last = Kristof|first = Nicholas|authorlink = Nicholas Kristof|date = April 4, 2015|accessdate = April 11, 2015|newspaper = [[New York Times]]}}</ref> In the same year William MacAskill published his book ''[[Doing Good Better|Doing Good Better: How Effective Altruism Can Help You Make a Difference]]'' which helped to further popularize the movement.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2015/aug/20/doing-good-better-william-macaskill-review|title=Doing Good Better by William MacAskill review \u2013 if you read this book, you'll change the charities you donate to|last=Shariatmadari|first=David|date=August 20, 2015|work=The Guardian|access-date=May 21, 2017|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/08/16/upshot/effective-altruism-where-charity-and-rationality-meet.html|title=Effective Altruism: Where Charity and Rationality Meet|last=Cowen|first=Tyler|date=August 14, 2015|work=The New York Times|access-date=May 21, 2017|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref name=\"The Atlantic article The Greatest Good\" />\n\nIn 2018, American news website ''[[Vox (website)|Vox]]'' launched its ''Future Perfect'' section, led by journalist [[Dylan Matthews]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Schmidt |first=Christine |date=October 15, 2018 |title=Will Vox's new section on effective altruism... well, do any good? |url=https://www.niemanlab.org/2018/10/will-voxs-new-section-on-effective-altruism-well-do-any-good/ |website=[[Nieman Journalism Lab]] |accessdate=February 1, 2020}}</ref> ''Future Perfect'' has published written pieces and podcasts that cover effective altruism ideas on the mission of \"Finding the best ways to do good\",<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/future-perfect/2018/10/15/17924288/future-perfect-explained|title=Future Perfect, explained|last=Matthews|first=Dylan|date=October 15, 2018|website=Vox|access-date=December 8, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/future-perfect|title=Future Perfect|website=www.vox.com|access-date=February 1, 2020}}</ref> including topics such as effective philanthropy,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/2015/12/1/9826838/best-charities-donate-2018-giving-tuesday|title=These are the charities where your money will do the most good|last=Matthews|first=Dylan|date=December 17, 2019|website=Vox|access-date=February 1, 2020}}</ref> high-impact career choice,<ref name=\"career-choice-vox\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/future-perfect/2018/11/28/18114601/future-perfect-podcast-career-choice|title=How to pick a career that counts|last=Matthews|first=Dylan|date=November 28, 2018|website=Vox|access-date=December 8, 2018}}</ref> poverty reduction through [[women's empowerment]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/2018/11/5/18037688/gender-equality-poverty-human-rights|title=Want less poverty in the world? Empower women.|last=Illing|first=Sean|date=March 8, 2019|website=Vox|access-date=February 1, 2020}}</ref> improving children's learning efficiently through improving [[environmental health]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/2020/1/8/21051869/indoor-air-pollution-student-achievement|title=Installing air filters in classrooms has surprisingly large educational benefits: $1,000 can raise a class's test scores by as much as cutting class size by a third|last=Yglesias|first=Matthew|date=January 8, 2020|website=Vox|access-date=February 1, 2020}}</ref> animal welfare improvements,<ref name=\"animal-welfare-vox\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/2018/11/27/18111908/giving-tuesday-best-animal-charity|title=Where will your donations do the most for animals?|last=Piper|first=Kelsey|date=November 27, 2018|website=Vox|access-date=December 8, 2018}}</ref> and ways to reduce global catastrophic risks.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vox.com/future-perfect/2018/11/19/18097663/nick-bostrom-vulnerable-world-global-catastrophic-risks|title=How technological progress is making it likelier than ever that humans will destroy ourselves|last=Piper|first=Kelsey|date=November 19, 2018|work=Vox|access-date=December 9, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Key figures==\nKey figures in the effective altruism movement have included:\n* Princeton University philosopher [[Peter Singer]]<ref name=\"blog.ted.com\">{{cite web|last1=Walters|first1=Helen|title=The why and how of effective altruism: Peter Singer's talk visualized|url=http://blog.ted.com/why-how-effective-altruism-peter-singer-visualized/|website=TED Blog}}</ref>\n* Oxford University philosopher [[Derek Parfit]]<ref>{{cite news | last = Matthews | first = Derek | title = The whole philosophy community is mourning Derek Parfit. Here's why he mattered. | newspaper = Vox | date = January 3, 2017 | url = https://www.vox.com/science-and-health/2017/1/3/14148208/derek-parfit-rip-obit}}</ref>\n* Facebook cofounder [[Dustin Moskovitz]]<ref name=\"Washington Post on Dustin Moskovitz and Cari Tuna\">{{cite news | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/billionaire-couple-give-plenty-to-charity-but-they-do-quite-a-bit-of-homework/2014/12/26/19fae34c-86d6-11e4-b9b7-b8632ae73d25_story.html | title=Cari Tuna and Dustin Moskovitz: Young Silicon Valley billionaires pioneer new approach to philanthropy | date=December 26, 2014 | agency=The Washington Post}}</ref>\n* Future of Humanity Institute director [[Nick Bostrom]]<ref name=\"Utilitarianism2017\"/>{{rp|110}}\n* Global Priorities Institute director [[Hilary Greaves]]<ref>{{cite web | title = Global Priorities Institute opens at Oxford | date = April 5, 2018 | url = https://www.development.ox.ac.uk/news/new-global-priorities-institute-opens | access-date = 1 December 2019}}</ref>\n* Oxford University philosopher [[William MacAskill]]<ref name=\"The Atlantic article The Greatest Good\">{{cite news|last1=Thompson|first1=Derek|title=The Greatest Good|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/business/archive/2015/06/what-is-the-greatest-good/395768/#b06g25t20w15|work=The Atlantic|date=June 15, 2015}}</ref>\n* Future of Humanity Institute researcher [[Toby Ord]]<ref name=\"Peter Singer The Most Good You Can Do\">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NBWWX4ViD3E/|website=YouTube|title=Peter Singer: \"The Most Good You Can Do\" &#124; Talks at Google}}</ref>\n* Professional poker player [[Liv Boeree]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pokerstrategy.com/news/world-of-poker/Liv-Boeree-on-Effective-Altruism_100487/|title=News: Liv Boeree on Effective Altruism|website=www.pokerstrategy.com|access-date=April 11, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.livboeree.com/effective-altruism/|title=Effective Altruism {{!}} Liv Boeree|website=www.livboeree.com|language=en-GB|access-date=April 11, 2017}}</ref>\n* Artificial intelligence researcher [[Eliezer Yudkowsky]]{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n* GiveWell co-founder and Open Philanthropy Project CEO [[Holden Karnofsky]]<ref name=\"Lessons of EA\">{{cite web |last1=Rubenstein |first1=Jennifer |title=The Lessons of Effective Altruism |url=https://www.ethicsandinternationalaffairs.org/2016/the-lessons-of-effective-altruism/ |website=Ethics & International Affairs |accessdate=26 August 2018 |date=14 December 2016}}</ref>\n* Nanyang Technological University economist [[Yew-Kwang Ng]]<ref>{{cite web | last = Wiblin | first = Robert | title = Prof Yew-Kwang Ng is a visionary economist who anticipated many key ideas in effective altruism decades ago. Here's his take on ethics and how to create a much happier world. | website = 80,000 Hours | date = July 26, 2018| url = https://80000hours.org/podcast/episodes/yew-kwang-ng-anticipating-effective-altruism/ | access-date = 1 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Criticism==\n\n===Claims that comparisons within and across cause areas are illegitimate===\nIn the ''[[Stanford Social Innovation Review]]'', Ken Berger and Robert Penna of [[Charity Navigator]] condemned effective altruism's practice of \"weighing causes and beneficiaries against one another\", calling this \"moralistic, in the worst sense of the word\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ssireview.org/blog/entry/the_elitist_philanthropy_of_so_called_effective_altruism|title=The Elitist Philanthropy of So-Called Effective Altruism|last=Berger|first=Ken|last2=Penna|first2=Robert|date=November 25, 2013|website=|publisher=[[Stanford Social Innovation Review]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=November 26, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Bias toward measurable interventions===\nPascal-Emmanuel Gobry warns about the \"measurement problem\", stating that some areas, such as medical research, or helping to reform third-world governance \"one grinding step at a time\", are hard to measure with controlled cost-effectiveness experiments and therefore risk being undervalued by the effective altruism movement.<ref name=\"gobry\" /> Jennifer Rubenstein also hypothesizes that effective altruism can be biased against causes that are not straightforward to measure.<ref name=\"Lessons of EA\" />\n\n===Perceived neglect of radical economic change===\nIn ''[[Jacobin (magazine)|Jacobin]]'' magazine, Mathew Snow argued that effective altruism \"implores individuals to use their money to procure necessities for those who desperately need them, but says nothing about the system that determines how those necessities are produced and distributed in the first place\".<ref name=\"Jacobin\">{{cite web|url=https://www.jacobinmag.com/2015/08/peter-singer-charity-effective-altruism/|title=Against Charity|last=Snow|first=Mathew|date=August 25, 2015|website=|publisher=[[Jacobin (magazine)|Jacobin]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150828121204/https://www.jacobinmag.com/2015/08/peter-singer-charity-effective-altruism/|archive-date=August 28, 2015|accessdate=September 5, 2016|ref=harv}}</ref> Various critics have similarly objected to effective altruism on the basis of the fact that its proponents tend not to support political causes such as [[anti-capitalism]] that change \"the existing global institutional order\".<ref name=\"Berkey\" /> Joshua Kissel has replied that anti-capitalism is compatible with effective altruism in theory, while adding that effective altruists and anti-capitalists have reason to be more sympathetic to each other.<ref name=\"kissel\">{{cite web|url=http://commons.pacificu.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1573&context=eip/|title=Effective Altruism and Anti-Capitalism: An Attempt at Reconciliation|last=Kissel|first=Joshua|date=January 31, 2017|website=|publisher=Essays in Philosophy|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=February 19, 2017}}</ref> Brian Berkey has also argued that support for changing institutions such as capitalism does not contradict the principles of effective altruism, because effective altruism is open to any action that will have the greatest positive impact on the world, including the possibility of changing the existing global institutional order.<ref name=Berkey>{{cite journal |last1=Berkey |first1=Brian |title=The Institutional Critique of Effective Altruism |journal=Utilitas |date=2018 |volume=30 |issue=2 |url=https://faculty.wharton.upenn.edu/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/The-Institutional-Critique-of-Effective-Altruism.pdf |accessdate=26 August 2018}}</ref> Elizabeth Ashford argues that we are separately obligated to donate to effective aid charities and to reform the structures that are responsible for poverty.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Ashford |first1=Elizabeth |title=Severe Poverty as an Unjust Emergency |journal=The Ethics of Giving: Philosophers' Perspectives on Philanthropy |date=2018 |pages=103\u2013148 |doi=10.1093/oso/9780190648879.001.0001 |isbn=9780190648879 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Div col}}\n*[[Appropriate technology]]\n*[[Charity (practice)]]\n*[[Charity evaluator]]\n*[[Prosocial behavior]]\n*[[Speciesism]]\n*[[Structural fix]]\n*[[Veganism]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n== Notes and references ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite journal |last1=Earle |first1=Samantha |last2=Read |first2=Rupert |date=March 2016 |title=Effective altruism: Is it effective? Should it be more affective? |journal=[[The Philosophers' Magazine]] |issue=73 |pages=84\u201391 |doi=10.5840/tpm20167378 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Gabriel |first=Iason |date=August 2016 |title=Effective altruism and its critics |journal=[[Journal of Applied Philosophy]] |volume=34 |issue=4 |pages=457\u2013473 |doi=10.1111/japp.12176 |url=https://www.academia.edu/13786913 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |editor1-last=Greaves |editor1-first=Hilary |editor1-link=Hilary Greaves |editor2-last=Pummer |editor2-first=Theron |date=2019 |title=Effective Altruism: Philosophical Issues |series=Engaging philosophy |location=Oxford; New York |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |isbn=9780198841364 |oclc=1101772304 |doi=10.1093/oso/9780198841364.001.0001 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Lechterman |first=Theodore M. |date=June 2019 |title=Being good in a world of uncertainty: a reply to Temkin |journal=Journal of Practical Ethics |volume=7 |issue=1 |pages=33\u201339 |url=http://philarchive.org/archive/LECBGIv1 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Lechterman |first=Theodore M. |date=January 2020 |title=The effective altruist's political problem |journal=Polity |volume=52 |issue=1 |pages=88\u2013115 |doi=10.1086/706867 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |last=MacAskill |first=William |authorlink=William MacAskill |date=June 2019 |title=Aid scepticism and effective altruism |journal=Journal of Practical Ethics |volume=7 |issue=1 |pages=49\u201360 |url=http://philarchive.org/archive/MACASA-4v1 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |last=McMahan |first=Jeff |authorlink=Jeff McMahan (philosopher) |date=March 2016 |title=Philosophical critiques of effective altruism |journal=[[The Philosophers' Magazine]] |issue=73 |pages=92\u201399 |doi=10.5840/tpm20167379 |url=http://jeffersonmcmahan.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/11/Philosophical-Critiques-of-Effective-Altruism-refs-in-text.pdf |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite web |last1=Singer |first1=Peter |authorlink1=Peter Singer |last2=Saunders-Hastings |first2=Emma |last3=Deaton |first3=Angus |authorlink3=Angus Deaton |last4=Gabriel |first4=Iason |last5=Janah |first5=Leila |authorlink5=Leila Janah |last6=Acemoglu |first6=Daron |authorlink6=Daron Acemoglu |last7=Brest |first7=Paul |authorlink7=Paul Brest |last8=MacFarquhar |first8=Larissa |authorlink8=Larissa MacFarquhar |last9=Tumber |first9=Catherine |last10=Reich |first10=Rob |authorlink10=Rob Reich |title=Forum: The logic of effective altruism |url=https://bostonreview.net/forum/peter-singer-logic-effective-altruism |website=[[Boston Review]] |date=July 1, 2015 |accessdate=February 5, 2020}} An article based on the preface and first chapter of Singer's book ''[[The Most Good You Can Do]]'' was published in the ''Boston Review'' on July 1, 2015 with a forum of responses by other writers and a final response by Singer.\n* {{cite journal |last=Temkin |first=Larry S. |authorlink=Larry Temkin |date=June 2019 |title=Being good in a world of need: some empirical worries and an uncomfortable philosophical possibility |journal=Journal of Practical Ethics |volume=7 |issue=1 |pages=1\u201323 |url=http://philarchive.org/archive/TEMBGI |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Zuolo |first=Federico |date=July 2019 |title=Beyond moral efficiency: effective altruism and theorizing about effectiveness |journal=[[Utilitas]] |pages=1\u201314 |doi=10.1017/S0953820819000281 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/333618104 |ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote|Effective altruism}}\n\n*[https://www.effectivealtruism.org/ Effective Altruism]\n*[https://www.centreforeffectivealtruism.org/ Centre for Effective Altruism]\n*[https://80000hours.org/ 80,000 Hours]\n\n{{Effective altruism|state=expanded}}\n{{Charity}}\n{{Evidence-based practice|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Effective Altruism}}\n[[Category:Altruism]]\n[[Category:Career development]]